%@CR:MSE11000@%%@2@%%@AB@%1.1  Editing Capabilities%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE11001@%%@4@%Not only can the editor be customized, but it also supports many powerful%@EH@%
editing features:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE11002@%  ş  %@AB@%Use a full range of file-editing commands%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The editor supports a comprehensive range of file operations. You can%@NL@%
     load, merge, or save files, with or without exiting. You can execute%@NL@%
     the DOS or OS/2 shell, send highlighted areas to the printer, or insert%@NL@%
     program output directly into a file. The editor also supports a wide%@NL@%
     range of pattern-search and replacement functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%Save time with powerful block operations%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     You can manipulate different kinds of text blocks. For example, you can%@NL@%
     insert or delete ordinary sequences of characters between two file%@NL@%
     positions. You can also insert or delete rectangular areas, called%@NL@%
     "boxes." Box-shaped regions are highly useful for indenting paragraphs%@NL@%
     or moving columns of text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%Save typing effort with macros%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The Microsoft Editor includes a convenient macro language. A macro is a%@NL@%
     command that performs a series of predefined actions; for example, a%@NL@%
     macro can insert a given phrase or word or perform an entire series of%@NL@%
     editing commands. Define a macro, then invoke it with one keystroke.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%Edit complex files with windows%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     When editing a large file, you may want to view different parts of the%@NL@%
     file simultaneously. With the Microsoft Editor, you can split up your%@NL@%
     screen into as many as eight windowsÄÄeach displaying a different part%@NL@%
     of the file (or parts of different files).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%Handle multiple source files%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     A simple command switches you among the files you are working onÄÄyou%@NL@%
     never have to leave the editor and start it up again to work on a%@NL@%
     different file. As the editor moves between files, it saves the last%@NL@%
     cursor position and other relevant information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
