%@CR:MSE14000@%%@2@%%@AB@%1.4  Introducing the Microsoft(R) Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14001@%%@4@%You'll find the Microsoft Editor easy to use once you understand the%@EH@%
function-argument model it uses for executing commands. Each command
consists of a function that may or may not be given input in the form of an
"argument."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14002@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor uses a "reverse Polish" command structure. That is, you%@EH@%
specify the argument first, then give the command function. For example, if
you want to load a file, you first specify the file name, then invoke the
file loading function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14003@%%@4@%All Microsoft Editor functions work in this fashion. This arrangement is%@EH@%
different from that of conventional editors where you would choose the file
loading function first, then specify the desired file. This "argument first,
function second" sequence gives the Microsoft Editor unique advantages:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14004@%  ş  A single function can process different types of arguments, such as%@NL@%
     high-lighted blocks of text, a word or number typed on the dialog line,%@NL@%
     or the word at the current cursor position. Almost all functions work%@NL@%
     with all data types, so there aren't too many arbitrary details to%@NL@%
     memorize.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  It's easy to write macros because almost every action can be expressed%@NL@%
     as a function name. Macros are likewise easy to understandÄÄyou won't%@NL@%
     have trouble understanding another person's macro, or a macro %@AI@%you%@AE@% wrote%@NL@%
     six months ago.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14005@%%@4@%Function names follow a consistent pattern. For example, functions that%@EH@%
involve forward movement usually start with P (for "plus"). Functions that
involve backward movement usually start with M (for "minus").%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE14006@%%@4@%Before using the Microsoft Editor, run the installation program for your%@EH@%
Microsoft language product. The installation program sets up the powerful
on-line Help, which provides on-line information for editing functions and
the standard C library. It is recommended that you select the default
keystroke configuration in order to work through the early chapters of this
manual.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   If you choose to customize the Microsoft Editor during installation, its%@NL@%
   function-key assignments will match those of BRIEF(R), Epsilon(TM), or%@NL@%
   the Microsoft "Quick" Environment. This book describes the uncustomized%@NL@%
   version of the Microsoft Editor, so the commands described will not%@NL@%
   always match those on your version of the editor.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
