%@CR:MSE20000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 2  Edit Now%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE20001@%%@4@%This chapter shows you how to use the Microsoft Editor right away by%@EH@%
focusing on the functions you need to create a simple text file. "Functions"
are built-in editing capabilities you invoke to perform actions. Most of the
chapter consists of a tutorial that uses a specific example and features the
following functions:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE20002@%%@AB@%Function                              Default Keystroke%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Cursor movement                       DIRECTION keys, HOME, END%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Insertmode%@AE@%                            INS%@NL@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@%                                DEL%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (introduce argument)              ALT+A%@NL@%
%@AI@%Cancel%@AE@%                                ESC%@NL@%
%@AI@%Undo%@AE@%                                  ALT+BKSP%@NL@%
%@AI@%Paste%@AE@%                                 SHIFT+INS%@NL@%
%@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% (forward search)              F3%@NL@%
%@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% (insert new line)             CTRL+N%@NL@%
%@AI@%Exit%@AE@%                                  F8%@NL@%
%@AI@%Help%@AE@%                                  F1%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE20003@%%@4@%You can use this tutorial either by starting the editor and typing in each%@EH@%
command as shown, or you can simply read along. Because the results are
explained at each stage, you can get a good understanding of the editor just
by reading.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE20004@%%@4@%The chapter ends by presenting the complete command line for the editor with%@EH@%
all the possible options you may use, a complete list of items on the status
line, and some hints for learning the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE21000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.1  Starting the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE21001@%%@4@%Copy the file M.EXE into your current directory or a directory listed in the%@EH@%
PATH environment variable. To run the editor in OS/2 protected mode, copy
the file MEP.EXE. (You may want to rename the file as M.EXE.) Then start the
editor with this command:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%M NEW.TXT%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE21002@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor responds by asking if you want to create a new file%@EH@%
with this name. Press %@AS@%Y%@AE@% to indicate yes. The editor creates the file and
places it in the current directory. You are now ready to enter text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   If the editor cannot start correctly, it reports an error message. If you%@NL@%
   receive an error message on start-up, consult the list of error messages%@NL@%
   in Appendix C%@BO:   76d41@%. This list of error messages provides explanations,%@NL@%
   along with suggestions for solving the problem.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE21003@%%@4@%When you want to exit, press %@AS@%F8%@AE@%. Whenever you want to save your work without%@EH@%
exiting, type the following keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%ALT+A  ALT+A  F2%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.2  The Microsoft Editor's Screen%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22001@%%@4@%When starting the editor with a new file, you see a blank screen, as shown%@EH@%
in Figure 2.1%@FN@%
Figure 2.1 is found on page 9 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% below.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22002@%%@4@%The cursor first appears at the upper-left corner of the screen. Even though%@EH@%
the file is empty, you can use the DIRECTION keysÄÄdenoted as UP, DOWN,
LEFT, and RIGHTÄÄto move the cursor anywhere on the screen. (The DIRECTION
keys are the arrow keys on the numeric keypad. Newer keyboards may have an
additional set of arrow keys to the left of the numeric keypad.) Try
experimenting with cursor movement.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   The DIRECTION keys on the numeric keypad do not respond unless NUMLOCK is%@NL@%
   off. Press the NUMLOCK key to toggle the numeric keypad lock on and off.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22003@%%@4@%The next-to-bottom line is called the "dialog line," which is reserved for%@EH@%
displaying messages from the editor and letting you enter text arguments.
The bottom line is called the "status line." It always displays the
following fields:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22004@%%@AB@%Field                       Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AS@%c:\m\new.txt%@AE@%                File name, with complete path%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AS@%(text)%@AE@%                      Type of file%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AS@%Length=1%@AE@%                    Length of file, in number of lines (minimum%@NL@%
                            value is 1)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AS@%Window=(1,1)%@AE@%                Window or cursor position%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE22005@%%@4@%The field %@AS@%Window=(1,1)%@AE@% indicates that the upper-left corner of the screen%@EH@%
corresponds to the first row and column of the file. As you scroll through
files larger then one screen, the numbers in this field change. See Section
7.2.1%@BO:   34f56@%, "Changing Start-Up Conditions," to learn how to alter this field
so that it displays cursor position instead of window position.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.3  Sample Session%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23001@%%@4@%Once the Microsoft Editor is started, you can enter text immediately. Simply%@EH@%
start typing and press ENTER when you want to begin a new line. By default,
the editor starts in "overtype" mode, which means that anything you type
replaces the text at the cursor position.The editor also has an "insert"
mode for adding new material without replacing the current text. Insert mode
is explained in the next section.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23002@%%@4@%To begin, type in the following text. There are some intentional errors%@EH@%
you'll correct in a few moments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     It's mind over matter.%@NL@%
     What is mind?%@NL@%
     No mat matter.%@NL@%
     Wh is matter?%@NL@%
     Mever mind.%@AH@% %@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23003@%%@4@%The third, fourth, and fifth lines have errors near the beginning of each%@EH@%
line. To get to the beginning of the fifth line, you can press the LEFT key
until you move to the beginning of the line. However, you can get there
faster by pressing the HOME key. This key moves the cursor to the first
nonblank character in the line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23004@%%@4@%Now move the cursor to the beginning of the fifth line and correct the error%@EH@%
by typing the letter %@AS@%N%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     N%@AH@%e%@AE@%ver mind.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23100@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.1  Inserting Text with the Insertmode Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23101@%%@4@%To insert text in this example, move the cursor to the third position in the%@EH@%
fourth line:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Wh%@AH@% %@AE@%is matter?%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23102@%%@4@%The letters %@AS@%at%@AE@% need to be inserted at the end of the first word. Press the%@EH@%
INS key to invoke the %@AI@%Insertmode%@AE@% function, which toggles between overtype
and insert mode. You'll see the word %@AS@%insert%@AE@% appear at the end of the status
line. Type the letters %@AS@%at%@AE@% to produce the following line:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     What%@AH@% %@AE@%is matter?%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23103@%%@4@%To return to overtype mode, press INS again.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23200@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.2  Removing Text with the Delete Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23201@%%@4@%So far, you've used editing functions to replace old text and insert new%@EH@%
text. The third line requires text deletion, so move the cursor to the
beginning of the second word in the third line:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     No %@AH@%m%@AE@%at matter.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23202@%%@4@%Invoke the %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function by pressing the DEL key. Each time you press the%@EH@%
DEL key, the character at the cursor position is erased.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23203@%%@4@%It is inconvenient to delete a large amount of text one character at a time.%@EH@%
The %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function can also remove blocks of text that are specified as
arguments. The next section explains deleting a large block of text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23300@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.3  Using the Arg Function to Specify Text%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23301@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function is assigned to ALT+A; hold down the ALT key and press A to%@EH@%
invoke it. The %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function does nothing by itself. Rather, it tells the
editor that you are about to introduce an argument that another function
will operate on. (An "argument" is input, such as text or highlighted
characters.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23302@%%@4@%In this example you'll use the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function to highlight the group of%@EH@%
characters you wish to delete. After pressing ALT+A, move the cursor to the
beginning of the third word, as shown in Figure 2.2%@FN@%
Figure 2.2 is found on page 11 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% below. Now press DEL,
and the high-lighted characters are removed.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23400@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.4  Canceling and Undoing Commands%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23401@%%@4@%If you pressed ALT+A at the wrong time but did not complete the command you%@EH@%
were typing, you can cancel the argument by pressing the ESC key. This
key-stroke invokes the %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function. The %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function lets you start a
command sequence over again.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23402@%%@4@%If you complete an incorrect command, reverse it by pressing ALT+BKSP (hold%@EH@%
down the ALT key and then press the backspace key). This keystroke invokes
the %@AI@%Undo%@AE@% function. If you invoke %@AI@%Undo%@AE@% again, it reverses the next-to-last
editing command. Invoke %@AI@%Undo%@AE@% a third time, and it reverses the
second-to-last editing command, and so on. The number of commands that the
editor remembers is controlled by the %@AB@%undocount%@AE@% switch. The default number
of commands remembered is 10. See Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, "Switches, Assignments, and
the TOOLS.INI File," for information on how to set switches.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23403@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% function (F9) is a prefix, similar to %@AI@%r%@AE@%%@AI@% Arg%@AE@%, which reverses or%@EH@%
alters the effect of a function. You can cancel the effect of the %@AI@%Undo%@AE@%
function with the command sequence %@AI@%Meta%@AE@%%@AI@%Undo%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%F9 ALT+BKSP%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23404@%%@4@%This variation on the %@AI@%Undo%@AE@% function is often called "Redo." If you undo a%@EH@%
series of commands, you can recall each of these commands by using %@AI@%Meta Undo%@AE@%
repeatedly. %@AI@%Undo%@AE@% walks backward through the history of the file (it restores
an earlier state); %@AI@%Meta Undo%@AE@% walks forward.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23500@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.5  Using Delete to Move Text%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23501@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function can be used to move text as well as delete it. The last%@EH@%
text deleted is placed on the "Clipboard." The Clipboard holds text selected
by either the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% or %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function. Pressing SHIFT+INS invokes the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@%
function, which inserts the contents of the Clipboard into the file at the
present cursor position.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23502@%%@4@%In this section, %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% will be used to move two complete lines of text.%@EH@%
Consider the current text:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     It's mind over matter.%@NL@%
     What is mind?%@NL@%
     No matter.%@NL@%
     What is matter?%@NL@%
     Never mind.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23503@%%@4@%Move the cursor to the beginning of the fourth line. Select the bottom two%@EH@%
lines by pressing ALT+A and then pressing the DOWN key twice. You should see
the bottom two lines highlighted, as shown in Figure 2.3%@FN@%
Figure 2.3 is found on page 13 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% below.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23504@%%@4@%Now invoke the %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function by pressing DEL. The two lines disappear. The%@EH@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function deletes the characters you highlight.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23505@%%@4@%Having deleted a block of characters, you are ready to use the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@%%@EH@%
function (SHIFT+INS) to insert the deleted text at a new location. Move the
cursor to the beginning of the top line and press SHIFT+INS. You should see
the following text:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     What is matter?%@NL@%
     Never mind.%@NL@%
     It's mind over matter.%@NL@%
     What is mind?%@NL@%
     No matter.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23506@%%@4@%You can change the shape of the highlighted region by using the %@AI@%Boxstream%@AE@%%@EH@%
function (CTRL+B), which changes the region into a rectangular area. See
Chapter 3%@BO:    d239@% for more information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23600@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.6  Finding Strings with the Psearch Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23601@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% function takes different kinds of arguments but performs the%@EH@%
same general operation with eachÄÄsearching for a string of text. The term
%@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% stands for "plus search," and means the same thing as "forward
search." This function, which is assigned to the F3 key, takes both text
arguments and cursor-movement arguments. You can ask the editor to locate
the next occurrence of the word %@AS@%mind%@AE@% by typing the word in as a text
argument. Move the cursor to the beginning of the file, then try the
following sequence of keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23602@%  1. Press ALT+A%@NL@%
  2. Type the following text: %@AS@%mind%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Press F3%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23603@%%@4@%As you type the word, it appears on the dialog lineÄÄthe line just above the%@EH@%
status line at the bottom of the screen. As soon as you press ALT+A and type
the first character, the prompt %@AS@%Arg:%@AE@% appears on the dialog line. You can
retype  characters on the dialog line by pressing BKSP (the backspace key).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23604@%%@4@%You can achieve the same result by moving the cursor to the beginning of the%@EH@%
word %@AS@%mind%@AE@% on the screen, then highlighting the word with the following
sequence of keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%ALT+A RIGHT RIGHT RIGHT RIGHT F3%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23606@%%@4@%An even easier way of selecting the word is to give the keystroke sequence%@EH@%
ALT+A F3, which selects the word at the current cursor location. This word
(all characters up to the first blank or new-line character) becomes the
search string.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23607@%%@4@%Often when you use the %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% function, you want to look repeatedly for%@EH@%
some text string. To search for the text string most recently specified,
press F3 by itself.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23700@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.7  Inserting Spaces and Lines%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23701@%%@4@%You'll sometimes need to insert blank lines. There are two ways to do this:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23702@%  1. Press ENTER. When insert mode is on, pressing ENTER inserts a new-line%@NL@%
     character. (Recall that you turn insert mode on and off by pressing%@NL@%
     INS.) Any text to the right of the cursor moves down into the newly%@NL@%
     created line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Invoke %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% (line insert) by pressing CTRL+N. Regardless of cursor%@NL@%
     position, the %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% function inserts a blank line directly above the%@NL@%
     current line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23703@%%@4@%%@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% also accepts an argument. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A), move the cursor, and%@EH@%
then invoke %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% (CTRL+N). %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% inserts as many blank spaces in front
of the highlighted area as the number of characters you highlighted.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23800@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.3.8  Exiting the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23801@%%@4@%Press F8 to leave the editor. The F8 key sequence invokes the %@AI@%Exit%@AE@% function,%@EH@%
which automatically saves any changes you have made to the file and exits.
The sequence F9 F8 exits without saving, and the sequence ALT+A ALT+A F2
saves your most recent changes to the file without exiting.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE23802@%%@4@%See Section 4.1%@BO:   125dc@%, "Basic File Operations," for more information on%@EH@%
loading and saving files.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.4  Getting Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24001@%%@4@%One of the outstanding features of the editor is on-line Help. On-line Help%@EH@%
displays the information you need directly on the screen without your having
to exit the editor. You can quickly get information about any editing
function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24002@%%@4@%To use the basic on-line Help, you must first run the installation procedure%@EH@%
for the editor and follow all directions. The setup program for this
Microsoft language product should install the editor for you. Installing the
editor is important because it copies the Help files to your directories and
properly configures the editor's initialization file, TOOLS.INI.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24100@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.4.1  Starting On-Line Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24101@%%@4@%Press SHIFT+F1 to bring up the first Help screen. On-line Help is largely%@EH@%
self-explanatory. The first screen gives a list of the basic Help commands
and provides access to other parts of the Help system.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24102@%%@4@%Press F1 for context-sensitive Help. "Context-sensitive Help" displays a%@EH@%
Help screen for the word at the current cursor position. The entire word is
usedÄÄeven if the cursor is in the middle of the word. If the cursor is on a
space, the Help system uses the word immediately preceding the space. Thus
you can type a word, press F1, and get Help for that word.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24103@%%@4@%The editor searches through its list of Help files for a screen%@EH@%
corresponding to the word at the cursor position. If no screen exists for
the topic, the editor displays the first Help screen.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24200@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.4.2  Moving through On-Line Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24201@%%@4@%The first Help screen explains how to move between Help screens on different%@EH@%
topics. To move around within a Help topic, use the same keys (DIRECTION
keys, HOME, END, F3) that you use to move through a file. You can use PGUP
and PGDN  to move up or down a page at a time.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24300@%%@3@%%@AB@%2.4.3  Leaving On-Line Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24301@%%@4@%By default, the editor splits the screen into two windows when you bring up%@EH@%
a Help screen. You can move between windows by pressing F6. Moving from the
Help window to the editing window lets you continue editing while still
viewing Help information. To close the Help window, press ESC.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE24302@%%@4@%Section 7.2.5%@BO:   370ae@%, "Changing the Look and Feel of Help," explains how to%@EH@%
use Help without splitting the screen. If you use this technique, you leave
Help by press-ing F2 or ESC.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.5  The Microsoft Editor's Command Line%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25001@%%@4@%Use the following command line to start up the editor (the options are case%@EH@%
sensitive):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     M ®/D¯ ®/e %@AI@%command%@AE@%¯ ®/t¯ ®%@AI@%files%@AE@%¯%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25002@%%@4@%Begin the command line with the base of the editor's actual file name. For%@EH@%
example, if you are using the protected-mode version, the editor's file name
is MEP.EXE. (However, you can rename this file to M.EXE.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25003@%%@4@%The /D option prevents the editor from examining TOOLS.INI for%@EH@%
initialization settings (see Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, "Switches, Assignments, and the
TOOLS.INI File," for more information).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25004@%%@4@%The /e option enables you to specify a command upon start-up. The %@AI@%command%@AE@%%@EH@%
argument is a string that follows the same syntax rules as those given for
macros in Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%, "Function Assignments and Macros." If %@AI@%command%@AE@% contains
a space, the entire string should be enclosed in quotation marks. To
represent embedded quotation marks, precede each quotation mark by a
backslash (\"). To represent a literal backslash, use two backslashes (\\).
For example, the system-level command%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     M /e "arg \"search \\\" string\" psearch" FILE.TXT%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25005@%%@4@%causes the editor to start up and execute the following command:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     arg "search \" string" psearch%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25006@%%@4@%The /t option specifies that the names of any files following this option%@EH@%
are not retained in the editor's information file when the session
terminates. When you use the %@AI@%Information%@AE@% command at the next editing session
to list the most recently edited files, these names will not appear.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25007@%%@4@%If a single %@AI@%file%@AE@% is specified, the editor attempts to load the file. If the%@EH@%
file does not yet exist, the editor asks you if you want to create the file.
If you type Y (yes), the editor creates the file. If you type another
character, the editor does not create the file, but loads the most recently
edited file or (if no files have been previously edited) exits.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25008@%%@4@%If multiple %@AI@%files%@AE@% are specified, the first file is loaded; then, when you%@EH@%
invoke the %@AI@%Exit%@AE@% function, the editor saves the current file and loads the
next file in the list. If no %@AI@%files%@AE@% are specified, the editor attempts to
load the file you were editing when you last exited the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE25009@%%@4@%You can specify multiple %@AI@%files%@AE@% by either typing in different file names%@EH@%
explicitly or by using the DOS wildcard characters, ? and *. For example,
the following command line causes the editor to load every file in the
current directory with a .TXT extension:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     M *.txt%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE2500A@%%@4@%On start-up, the status line displays at least four fields. The status line%@EH@%
can display up to thirteen fields. The first four fields listed below are
always displayed:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE2500B@%  1. Name of the file being edited.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Type of file (based on extension).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. The length of the file in lines.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Cursor position or window position of upper-left corner.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. The word %@AS@%modified%@AE@% if the file has been changed.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. The letters %@AS@%NL%@AE@% if no carriage returns were found when the file was%@NL@%
     loaded (that is, if the file did not contain carriage returns to denote%@NL@%
     the end of each line, but used only line feeds).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  7. The word %@AS@%insert%@AE@% if you are in insert mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  8. The word %@AS@%meta%@AE@% if you have invoked the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  9. The word %@AS@%No-Edit%@AE@% if the file cannot be changed at any time during the%@NL@%
     editing session. Some of the internal files created by the editor, such%@NL@%
     as <information> and <assign>, fall into this category.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 1	. The word %@AS@%RO-File%@AE@% if the file has the read-only attribute. (This%@NL@%
     attribute is set outside of the editor.) The file can be modified, but%@NL@%
     after being modified, it can be saved only under a different file name.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 11. The word %@AS@%cancel%@AE@% if you recently invoked the %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 12. The letters %@AS@%BC%@AE@% if a background compilation is in progress under OS/2%@NL@%
     protected mode (or %@AS@%XX%@AE@% if the background compilation failed to begin).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 13. The letters %@AS@%REC%@AE@% while a macro is being recorded.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE26000@%%@2@%%@AB@%2.6  Hints for Using the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE26001@%%@CR:MSE26002@%%@4@%Here are two hints to keep in mind as you learn to use the editor:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE26003@%  1. The Microsoft Editor names functions in a consistent way. Section 3.2%@BO:    df64@%,%@NL@%
     "Naming Conventions for Functions," explains the conventions. Table A.1%@NL@%
     lists editing functions by category.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. If you forget which keystroke is associated with a function, use%@NL@%
     on-line Help for quick reference. If Help is installed, you can get%@NL@%
     function assignments by pressing SHIFT+F1 and then choosing the Current%@NL@%
     Assignments screen. If Help is not installed, pressing F1 takes you%@NL@%
     directly to this screen.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE30000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 3  Command Syntax%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE30001@%%@4@%If you've worked through Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@%, you have seen the flexibility of%@EH@%
Microsoft Editor commands. Many of the functions accept a variety of
argumentsÄÄtext arguments, cursor-movement argumentsÄÄor no argument at all.
This chapter describes each argument type in detail. The chapter also
presents the syntax and naming conventions used throughout the manual.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE30002@%%@4@%Topics are covered in the following order:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE30003@%  ş  Entering a command%@NL@%
  ş  Function naming conventions%@NL@%
  ş  Argument types%@NL@%
  ş  Text arguments (%@AI@%numarg, markarg, textarg%@AE@%)%@NL@%
  ş  Highlighting a text argument%@NL@%
  ş  Cursor-movement arguments (%@AI@%streamarg, linearg, boxarg%@AE@%)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.1  Entering a Command%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31001@%%@4@%Commands take two basic forms. You can invoke a function by itself, or you%@EH@%
can introduce an argument and then invoke a function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31002@%%@4@%Use the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix to introduce an argument. By default, %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% is assigned to%@EH@%
ALT+A (hold down the ALT key and press A). You can then type characters or
move the cursor to highlight part of the screen.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31003@%%@4@%Finally, invoke the function you want by pressing the corresponding%@EH@%
keystroke. If you forget the keystroke, you can look it up in on-line Help.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31004@%%@4@%The two basic forms of a command are summarized below:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%Function%@AE@%
     %@AI@%Arg argument Function%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31006@%%@4@%Some functions also let you form a command in one or more of the following%@EH@%
three ways:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31007@%  1. Some functions accept %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% with no argument: %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%%@AI@%Function%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Some functions accept %@AI@%Arg Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A twice). The sequence %@AI@%Arg Arg%@AE@%%@NL@%
     can introduce a function just as %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% does.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Some functions work differently when given the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% prefix. You can%@NL@%
     toggle %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% on and off by pressing F9. When %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% is on, the word %@AS@%meta%@AE@%%@NL@%
     appears on the status line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31008@%%@4@%See Chapter 4%@BO:   120e2@%, "A Survey of the Editor's Commands," and Table A.3 for%@EH@%
information on what syntax is accepted by each function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE31009@%%@4@%Once you begin entering a command, you can cancel %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% and any argument by%@EH@%
invoking the %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function (ESC). The Cancel function is also useful for
clearing the dialog line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
