%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE32000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.2  Naming Conventions for Functions%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE32001@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor follows a consistent pattern of function names.%@EH@%
Function names often begin with the letters P, M, S, L, or Cur, which can
have the following meanings:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE32002@%%@AB@%Initial Letter(s)           Usage%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
P                           Plus. Indicates forward movement of some kind.%@NL@%
                            For example, %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% is the forward-search%@NL@%
                            command, and %@AI@%Pword%@AE@% moves the cursor forward one%@NL@%
                            word.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
M                           Minus. Indicates backward movement of some kind.%@NL@%
                            For example, %@AI@%Msearch%@AE@% is the backward-search%@NL@%
                            command, and %@AI@%Mword%@AE@% moves the cursor backward one%@NL@%
                            word.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
S                           Stream. Indicates a stream-oriented,%@NL@%
                            block-of-text function. This category includes%@NL@%
                            %@AI@%Sinsert%@AE@%, which inserts spaces in the stream of%@NL@%
                            text between two cursor positions, and %@AI@%Sdelete%@AE@%,%@NL@%
                            which deletes the stream. Without an argument,%@NL@%
                            these functions insert or delete a single space.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
L                           Line. Indicates a line-and-box-oriented%@NL@%
                            function. This category includes %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@%, which%@NL@%
                            inserts spaces in the exact area highlighted on%@NL@%
                            screen, and %@AI@%Ldelete%@AE@%, which deletes it. Without%@NL@%
                            an argument, these functions insert or delete a%@NL@%
                            line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Cur                         Current. Indicates one of the special insertion%@NL@%
                            functions, such as %@AI@%Curdate%@AE@% (insert current date)%@NL@%
                            and %@AI@%Curfile%@AE@% (insert current file name).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE33000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.3  Argument Types%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE33001@%%@4@%There are two basic ways to enter arguments: you can enter text directly as%@EH@%
part of the command (text argument), or you can use cursor movement to
highlight characters on the screen (cursor-movement argument). Each of these
two methods has several variations, as shown in the following list:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE33002@%  1. Text argument. After you invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A), continue to type%@NL@%
     characters. These characters appear on the dialog line (the line next%@NL@%
     to the bottom of the screen). You can give three different kinds of%@NL@%
     text arguments:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     a.   A %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%, which consists of a string of digits.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     b.   A %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%, which is a string containing the name of a previously%@NL@%
          defined file marker.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     c.   A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%, which is any text argument not recognized as a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%%@NL@%
          or %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Cursor-movement argument. After you invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A), the current%@NL@%
     cursor position is highlighted. Highlight more characters by moving the%@NL@%
     cursor to a new position. You can give three different kinds of%@NL@%
     cursor-movement arguments:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     a.   A %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%, in which the old and new cursor positions are in%@NL@%
          different lines but the same column.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     b.   A %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%, in which the old and new cursor positions are in%@NL@%
          different columns.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     c.   A %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%, which can consist of any cursor movement.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.4  Text Arguments (numarg, markarg, textarg)%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34001@%%@4@%After you invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A), you can enter a text argument by typing any%@EH@%
printable characters, including blank spaces. The first time you invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%,
the following characters appear on the dialog line (the line next to the
bottom of the screen):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%Arg [1]%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34002@%%@4@%If you press ALT+A again, the number in the brackets changes. Any characters%@EH@%
you type appear on the dialog line after %@AS@%Arg [1]%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34003@%%@4@%When entering a text argument, you can edit, move through, or modify the%@EH@%
text argument in the following ways:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34004@%  1. Erase a character by pressing BKSP.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Erase the character at the current cursor position with the %@AI@%Sdelete%@AE@%%@NL@%
     function (DEL).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Move back and forth nondestructively with LEFT and RIGHT. If you use%@NL@%
     RIGHT to move past the end of current input, the editor inserts the%@NL@%
     character from the corresponding position in the previous text%@NL@%
     argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Insert a space at the cursor position with the %@AI@%Sinsert%@AE@% function%@NL@%
     (CTRL+J).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. Move to the beginning of the text with %@AI@%Begline%@AE@% (HOME) and to the end of%@NL@%
     the text with %@AI@%Endline%@AE@% (END).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. Clear characters from the current cursor position to the end of the%@NL@%
     line with the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (ALT+A).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34005@%%@4@%To repeat the most recently entered text argument, invoke the %@AI@%Lasttext%@AE@%%@EH@%
function, which by default is assigned to CTRL+O. When you use %@AI@%Lasttext%@AE@%, the
%@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix is unnecessary.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34100@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.4.1  The numarg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34101@%%@4@%A %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% is a string of digits that you enter as a text argument. Each of%@EH@%
the three following examples is a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%3%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%11%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%45%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34102@%%@4@%The number must be a valid decimal integer. A %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% is evaluated as a%@EH@%
number and not as literal text. Typically, it is used to indicate a range of
lines starting with the cursor position. For example, the following command
sequence deletes 10 lines starting with the cursor position:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34103@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Type the following text: %@AS@%10%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Ldelete%@AE@% (press CTRL+Y)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34104@%%@4@%Some functions accept text arguments but do not recognize a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%. These%@EH@%
functions treat a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% as an ordinary %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34200@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.4.2  The markarg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34201@%%@4@%A %@AI@%markarg%@AE@% is a file-marker name you have previously defined with the %@AI@%Mark%@AE@%%@EH@%
function (CTRL+M). See Section 4.4%@BO:   1839c@%, "Using File Markers," for information
about %@AI@%Mark%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34202@%%@4@%Once defined, you can enter the marker name as a %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%. The name is not%@EH@%
treated as literal text, but is interpreted as an actual file position. For
example, the following command sequence copies all text between the cursor
position and the file position previously marked as %@AS@%P1%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34203@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the following text: %@AS@%P1%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Copy%@AE@%(press CTRL+INS)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34204@%%@4@%Many functions accept text arguments but do not recognize a %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%. In%@EH@%
these cases, the %@AI@%markarg%@AE@% is treated as an ordinary %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34300@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.4.3  The textarg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34301@%%@4@%A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is similar to a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% or %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%. The only difference is that the%@EH@%
%@AI@%textarg%@AE@% has no special meaning; it is interpreted by the function as literal
text. For example, the following sequence finds the next occurrence of the
string %@AS@%Happy%@AE@%%@AS@%New Year%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34302@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Type the following: %@AS@%Happy New Year%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% (press F3)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE34303@%%@4@%A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% can either be typed in directly or highlighted on the screen. The%@EH@%
next section describes how to highlight a text argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.5  Highlighting a Text Argument%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35001@%%@4@%If the text argument already appears in the editing screen, you can save%@EH@%
typing by highlighting the text. You can highlight all or part of one line;
a text argument cannot consist of multiple lines.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35002@%%@4@%To highlight a text argument:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35003@%  1. Move the cursor to the first character in the text argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The current cursor position defines the "initial cursor position." As%@NL@%
     you move the cursor, characters between the initial cursor position and%@NL@%
     the new cursor position are highlighted.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Move the cursor to the right until all the desired text is highlighted.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Invoke the desired function. The editor passes the highlighted%@NL@%
     characters to this function, just as if you had directly typed in the%@NL@%
     highlighted characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35004@%%@4@%For example, the highlighted area in Figure 3.1%@EH@%%@FN@%
Figure 3.1 is found on page 25 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% defines the text argument
%@AS@%pascal MoveCur%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35005@%%@4@%Even if the highlighted text represents a legitimate %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% or %@AI@%markarg%@AE@%, it%@EH@%
will be interpreted by the function as a straight %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%. That is, a %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%
or %@AI@%markarg%@AE@% must be typed in on the status line; it cannot be selected from
the body of text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE35006@%%@4@%Highlighting a %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is a special case of a cursor-movement argument. The%@EH@%
next section discusses the other kinds of cursor-movement arguments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36000@%%@2@%%@AB@%3.6  Cursor-Movement Arguments (linearg, boxarg, streamarg)%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36001@%%@4@%You enter a cursor-movement argument by invoking %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A) and moving the%@EH@%
cursor. When you invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%, the current cursor position is marked with a
reverse-video highlight. This position is called the "initial cursor
position." As you move the cursor, characters between the initial cursor
position and the new cursor position are highlighted.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36002@%%@4@%When the initial and new cursor positions are on different lines, you can%@EH@%
high-light regions by one of two different modes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36003@%  ş  In "box mode," the editor highlights either complete lines (if the new%@NL@%
     and initial cursor position are in the same column) or rectangular%@NL@%
     areas. In box mode, you can select complete lines, or highlight,%@NL@%
     delete, and insert columns without affecting the surrounding text. In%@NL@%
     box mode, a cursor-movement argument is either a %@AI@%linearg%@AE@% or %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%, as%@NL@%
     explained in Sections 3.6.1%@BO:   11355@% and 3.6.2%@BO:   115ce@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  In "stream mode," the editor highlights text the way most text editors%@NL@%
     do. The highlighted region includes all text between the two positions,%@NL@%
     according to their sequence in the file. This region is usually not%@NL@%
     rectangular. In stream mode, a cursor-movement argument is always a%@NL@%
     %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%, as explained in Section 3.6.3%@BO:   119d6@%, "The streamarg Type."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36004@%%@4@%By default, the editor uses stream mode. You can toggle back and forth%@EH@%
between the two modes by invoking the %@AI@%Boxstream%@AE@% function (CTRL+B). You can
even invoke %@AI@%Boxstream%@AE@% while in the middle of creating a cursor-movement
argumentÄÄdoing so changes the highlighting instantly.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36005@%%@4@%To repeat the most recently entered cursor-movement argument, invoke the %@EH@%
%@AI@%Lastselect%@AE@% function, which by default is assigned to CTRL+U. When you use
%@AI@%Lastselect%@AE@%, the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix is unnecessary.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36006@%%@4@%If you create a cursor-movement argument and then type a character, the%@EH@%
editor removes the highlighted area and replaces it with the character
typed. A similar result occurs when you create a cursor-movement argument
and then invoke the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% functionÄÄthe highlighted area is replaced by the
contents of the Clipboard.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36100@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.6.1  The linearg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36101@%%@4@%A %@AI@%linearg%@AE@% is defined when the new cursor position is in the same column but%@EH@%
on a different line from the initial cursor position. The editor must be in
box mode. The editor responds by highlighting all lines between the two
cursor positions, including the lines that the cursor positions are on. For
example, the display in Figure 3.2%@FN@%
Figure 3.2 is found on page 26 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% is produced by invoking %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A) and
then pressing DOWN three times.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36200@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.6.2  The boxarg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36201@%%@4@%A %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% is a rectangular area on the screen. The two corners of the area%@EH@%
are determined by the initial and new cursor positions. A %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% is defined
when the two positions are in different columns (and possibly different
lines). The editor must be in box mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36202@%%@4@%After invoking %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (ALT+A), you can move the cursor left or right. The left%@EH@%
edge of the box includes the leftmost of the two cursor positions. The right
edge of the box includes the column just to the left of other cursor
positions. The box contains parts of all lines, inclusive, between the two
positions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36203@%%@4@%For example, the display shown in Figure 3.3%@EH@%%@FN@%
Figure 3.3 is found on page 27 in the printed version of this manual.%@EF@% is produced by invoking %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%
and then moving the cursor 3 lines down and 16 columns over.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36300@%%@3@%%@AB@%3.6.3  The streamarg Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36301@%%@4@%A %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% consists of text between the initial cursor and the new cursor%@EH@%
positions. When the editor is in stream mode, every cursor-movement argument
is a %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%. You toggle between box and stream mode by invoking %@AI@%Boxstream%@AE@%
(CTRL+B).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36302@%%@4@%After pressing ALT+A, you can move the cursor in any direction to create a %@EH@%
%@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%. The %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% is shown as highlighted characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36303@%%@4@%If you move the cursor forward (that is, to the right or down), the%@EH@%
%@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% includes the character at the initial cursor position. If you move
the cursor backward (that is, to the left or up), the %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% does %@AI@%not%@AE@%
include the character at the initial cursor position; the %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% starts
at the preceding character.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36304@%%@4@%When a %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% spans multiple lines, it includes some characters that a %@EH@%
%@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% does not. Specifically, a multiline %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% includes the following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36305@%  1. All characters from the first cursor position to the end of the line%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. All characters on the lines between the two cursor positions%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. All characters on the line of the second cursor position, up to but not%@NL@%
     including the cursor position itself%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE36306@%%@4@%For example, the display shown in Figure 3.4%@EH@%%@FN@%
Figure 3.4 is found on page 27 in the printed version of this guide.%@EF@% is produced with the same
cursor movement used in Figure 3.3, but with stream mode on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE40000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 4  A Survey of the Editor's Commands%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE40001@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor has all the standard features of a programmer's editor.%@EH@%
It lets you move quickly through a file, move blocks of text, search for
strings, and handle multiple files. In addition, the Microsoft Editor allows
you to use different windows for viewing more than one file or more than one
part of the same file. The Microsoft Editor can also invoke compilers and
assemblers, then display each compilation error.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE40002@%%@4@%This chapter expands on the editing topics introduced in Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@%. For a%@EH@%
complete list of the command syntax for every function, see Appendix A%@BO:   5d119@%,
"Reference Tables." This chapter covers topics in the following order:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE40003@%  ş  Basic file operations%@NL@%
  ş  Moving through a file%@NL@%
  ş  Inserting, copying, and deleting text%@NL@%
  ş  Using file markers%@NL@%
  ş  Searching and replacing%@NL@%
  ş  Compiling%@NL@%
  ş  Using editing windows%@NL@%
  ş  Working with multiple files%@NL@%
  ş  Printing all or part of a file%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41000@%%@2@%%@AB@%4.1  Basic File Operations%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41001@%%@4@%This section discusses how to work with files in general and how to use%@EH@%
internal files called "pseudo files."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41100@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.1.1  File Commands%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41101@%%@4@%File operations are basic to all work with the editor. You use file%@EH@%
operations to save your work, load in a new text file, or completely exit
from the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41102@%%@4@%Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@% described how to save the current file and exit from the editor.%@EH@%
However, the Microsoft Editor supports a number of other file operations.
The list below shows how to use some of the most common file operations:%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41103@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   24   1333  2 42 34 @%%@AB@%Command     %@AE@%%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)                  Description%@AE@%%@AI@%Exit%@AE@% (F8)                                 Exits editor after saving current                                          file%@AI@%Meta Exit%@AE@% (F9  F8)                        Exits editor without saving%@AI@%Arg Arg Setfile%@AE@% (ALT+A ALT+A F2)          Saves current file without exiting%@AI@%Arg Arg textarg Setfile%@AE@%                   Saves current file under the file(ALT+A ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% F2)                  name (%@AI@%textarg%@AE@%) without exiting%@AI@%Arg textarg Setfile%@AE@% (ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% F2)    Loads another file (entered as                                          %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%) into the editing window%@AI@%Arg Arg textarg Paste%@AE@%                     Merges (copies) another file(ALT+A ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% SHIFT+INS)           (entered as%@AI@%textarg%@AE@%) into current                                          fileÄÄthe new file is inserted at                                          the cursor position%@AI@%Refresh%@AE@% (SHIFT+F7)                        Discards most recent changes to                                          current file and rereads file from                                          disk%@TE:   24   1333  2 42 34 @%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41104@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41105@%%@4@%As explained in Chapter 3%@BO:    d239@%, a %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is simply an argument you type in%@EH@%
directly. For example, to load the file SAMPLE.TXT, you would follow these
steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41106@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following file name: %@AS@%SAMPLE.TXT%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% function (press F2)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41107@%%@4@%Each of the operations listed above is frequently useful, yet some should be%@EH@%
used with caution. For example, you should only exit without saving when you
have accidentally altered a file you do not want to change, or when you have
made many mistakes during the editing session. When you exit without saving,
all the work you did since the last save operation is discarded.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41108@%%@4@%Conversely, you may wish to save without leaving the editor. This operation%@EH@%
is usually safe, unless the current file is one that should not be changed.
Saving a file writes all the changes you made out to the disk. If your
system is vulnerable to power failures or other kinds of system failure, it
is a good idea to save your work often.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41109@%%@4@%Merging and loading a file are not the same. Merging a file copies the%@EH@%
contents of another file and inserts it into the current file. Loading a
file first saves the current file (assuming the %@AB@%autosave%@AE@% switch is on), then
restarts the editing session with a new file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE4110A@%%@4@%The editor supports other variations of these operations described above.%@EH@%
See Table A.3, under the %@AI@%Exit%@AE@% and %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% functions, for more information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41200@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.1.2  Special Syntax for Setfile%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41201@%%@4@%A text argument passed to %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% can take a number of different forms: a%@EH@%
file name, a file name with a DOS  wildcard character (* or ?), the name of
a directory, or the name of a disk drive. If the text argument is a
directory name, the editor changes the current directory. If the argument is
a drive name, the editor changes the current drive.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41202@%%@4@%File names can be complete path names and can include environment variables%@EH@%
defined with the system-level SET command. The %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% function interprets
an environment variables as a list of directories to search for a file. You
enter an environment variable using the syntax%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%$%@AE@%%@AI@%environ%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%filename%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41204@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%environ%@AE@% is the name of an environment variable. For example, the%@EH@%
following actions cause the editor to search the INIT environment variable
to find the TOOLS.INI file and load it:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41205@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following file name: %@AS@%$INIT:tools.ini%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% function (press F2)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41206@%%@4@%You can also use the environment-variable syntax with the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% function%@EH@%
when you use this function to merge a file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41207@%%@4@%Finally, you can switch to a recently edited file by using a short name. A%@EH@%
"short name" is a file name with no path or extension . The editor searches
its list of recently edited files to find a name that matches the short
name.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41300@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.1.3  Pseudo Files%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41301@%%@4@%A "pseudo file" is an internal editing file. It exists only in the%@EH@%
computer's memory and does not correspond to any disk file. The editor
treats a pseudo file just like any other file except for two important
differences:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41302@%  1. The name of a pseudo file always appears in angle brackets (<>).%@NL@%
  2. A pseudo file may not be saved to disk under its own name.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41303@%%@4@%Why use pseudo files? Pseudo files are useful for temporary storage. Pseudo%@EH@%
files are updated almost instantaneously because writing to RAM is much
faster than writing to disk. You can also insert the contents of a pseudo
file into the current file with the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41304@%%@4@%The editor creates several pseudo files of its own and gives them special%@EH@%
meaning. You can open these files just like any other with the %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@%
function.%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE41305@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   37   2148  1 28 48 @%%@AB@%Pseudo File                 Description%@AE@%<clipboard>                 Stores text selected by a copy or deletion. This                            file can be modified; the modified file is then                            inserted when you invoke %@AI@%Paste%@AE@%.                            However, if you copy or delete text while                            editing this file, the selected text is not                            saved to the Clipboard but simply discarded.<assign>                    Shows an updated list of function and switch                            assignments. You can create new function and                            switch assignments by directly modifying this                            file; however, the assignments you make must                            follow the syntax described in Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%,                            "Function Assignments and Macros."<information-file>          Shows a list of files that have been previously                            edited. This file cannot be modified. Each file                            currently open for editing is listed along with                            its length in lines.<compile>                   Shows error messages from the last compilation                            executed from within the editor. If the editor                            is running under protected mode, the error                            messages are dynamically updated while the                            compilation is running.<file-list>                 Shows a list of each file specified on the                            editor's command line that has not yet been                            opened. This file cannot be modified.<record>                    Records each editing command when you record a                            macro. The file is dynamic; it changes while you                            view it. You cannot 