%@CR:MSE42000@%%@2@%%@AB@%4.2  Moving through a File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42001@%%@4@%Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@%, "Edit Now," described how to the use DIRECTION keys to move%@EH@%
through a file one space at a time. The DIRECTION keys correspond to the
functions %@AI@%Up%@AE@%, %@AI@%Down%@AE@%, %@AI@%Right%@AE@%, and %@AI@%Left%@AE@%, to which you can assign different keys
if you wish. Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@% also presented the %@AI@%Begline%@AE@% function (HOME), which
moves the cursor to the first printable character in the current line.
Similar to the %@AI@%Begline%@AE@% function is the %@AI@%Endline%@AE@% function (END), which moves
the cursor just to the right of the last  printable character in the current
line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42002@%%@4@%Each of the four direction functions in the following list has a variation%@EH@%
that uses the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% function as a prefix. Each function, when used in a
command with the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% prefix, moves the cursor as far as possible within the
displayed screen (or window) without changing column position or causing the
screen to scroll.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42003@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%Command     %@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)     Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Up%@AE@% (F9  UP)             Moves the cursor to the top of the screen%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Down%@AE@% (F9  DOWN)         Moves the cursor to the bottom of the screen%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Left%@AE@% (F9  LEFT)         Moves the cursor to the left-most position on%@NL@%
                             the current line%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Right%@AE@% (F9  RIGHT)       Moves the cursor to the right-most position on%@NL@%
                             the current line%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Begline%@AE@% (F9  HOME)      Moves the cursor to column 1%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42100@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.2.1  Scrolling at the Screen's Edge%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42101@%%@4@%You can use the four direction functions (%@AI@%Up%@AE@%,  %@AI@%Down%@AE@%, %@AI@%Right%@AE@% , %@AI@%Left%@AE@%) to cause%@EH@%
scrolling. The screen (or current window) can scroll in all four
directions. Although the editor does not wrap lines that are wider than the
screen, you can have lines of text that are up to 250 characters wide. Use
the DIRECTION keys to scroll right and left when your text lines are wider
than the screen or current window.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42102@%%@4@%Unlike some editors, the Microsoft Editor does not automatically scroll by%@EH@%
only one column or one line. Instead, the internal switches %@AB@%hscroll%@AE@%
(horizontal-scroll) and %@AB@%vscroll%@AE@% (vertical-scroll) control how fast the
editor scrolls. For example, if %@AB@%vscroll%@AE@% is set to 7, the editor advances the
screen position seven lines when you attempt to move the cursor off the
bottom of the screen. See Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@% for more information on these switches.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42200@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.2.2  Scrolling a Page at a Time%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42201@%%@4@%The editor provides the %@AI@%Ppage%@AE@% (PGDN) and %@AI@%Mpage%@AE@% (PGUP) functions to move%@EH@%
through a file more quickly than you can by using the DIRECTION keys to move
one line or one column at a time.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42202@%%@4@%The term "page" is defined as the amount of text that can be displayed in%@EH@%
the current window or screen. To advance one page forward through a file,
invoke the function %@AI@%Ppage%@AE@% (PGDN), which stands for "plus page."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42203@%%@4@%The function %@AI@%Mpage%@AE@% (PGUP), which stands for "minus page," is the inverse of%@EH@%
%@AI@%Ppage%@AE@%, and it moves back through the file one page at a time.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   In Version 1.0 of the editor, the %@AI@%Ppage%@AE@% and %@AI@%Mpage%@AE@% functions took%@NL@%
   arguments. You can use them to help build a cursor-movement argument;%@NL@%
   they do not cancel the current argument. The editor also provides two new%@NL@%
   functionsÄÄ%@AI@%Begfile%@AE@% and %@AI@%Endfile%@AE@%ÄÄthat move to the beginning and end of the%@NL@%
   file. The next section describes these functions.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42300@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.2.3  Moving to the Top or Bottom of the File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42301@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Begfile%@AE@% and %@AI@%Endfile%@AE@% functions provide the fastest cursor movement.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42302@%%@4@%To move the cursor to the beginning of the file, invoke the %@AI@%Begfile%@AE@% function%@EH@%
by pressing CTRL+UP (the up-arrow key on the numeric keypad).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42303@%%@4@%To move the cursor to the end of the file, invoke the %@AI@%Endfile%@AE@% function by%@EH@%
pressing CTRL+DOWN (the down-arrow key on the numeric keypad).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42400@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.2.4  Other File-Navigation Functions%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42401@%%@4@%The following functions are useful for moving through a file:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42402@%%@AB@%Function     %@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)    Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Pword%@AE@%  (CTRL+RIGHT)         Moves the cursor forward (plus) one word%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Mword%@AE@% (CTRL+LEFT)           Moves the cursor backward (minus) one word%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Ppara%@AE@%                       Moves the cursor forward (plus) one paragraph%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Mpara%@AE@%                       Moves the cursor backward (minus) one paragraph%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Mark%@AE@% (CTRL+M)               Defines or moves to a marker, or moves to a%@NL@%
                            specified line number%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE42403@%%@4@%With the %@AI@%Mark%@AE@% function, you can define a marker or move to a marker. Markers%@EH@%
constitute a special topic that is discussed in Section 4.4%@BO:   1839c@%, "Using File
Markers."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43000@%%@2@%%@AB@%4.3  Inserting, Copying, and Deleting Text%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43001@%%@4@%You may often need to move, copy, or delete blocks of text. The Microsoft%@EH@%
Editor is particularly powerful because it provides a variety of ways to
define a block of characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43002@%%@4@%For example, you can delete a highlighted box, a range of lines, or a stream%@EH@%
of text between any two file positions. Sections 4.3.1%@BO:   162ea@%-4.3.4 discuss how to
work with blocks of text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43100@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.3.1  Inserting and Deleting Text%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43101@%%@4@%Chapter 2%@BO:    7023@%, "Edit Now," described how to use the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@%, %@AI@%Insertmode%@AE@%, and%@EH@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@% functions to insert, move, and delete text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43102@%%@4@%The following list presents some of the most common commands that use the %@EH@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43103@%%@AB@%Command%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)     Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@% (DEL)                Deletes the character at the cursor position.%@NL@%
                            (This command does not join two lines of text,%@NL@%
                            even if the cursor is at the end of the line.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg Delete%@AE@% (ALT+A DEL)      Deletes all text from the cursor position to the%@NL@%
                            end of the line and joins the current line of%@NL@%
                            text with the next line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg cursor-movement%@AE@%         Deletes the highlighted area, whether it is a%@NL@%
%@AI@%Delete%@AE@% (ALT+A               %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%, %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%, or %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%. You can toggle%@NL@%
%@AI@%cursor-movement%@AE@% DEL)        between stream and box selection with the%@NL@%
                            %@AI@%Boxstream%@AE@% function (CTRL+B).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43104@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function copies all deleted text (except single-character%@EH@%
deletions) to the Clipboard. For any argument, the %@AI@%Meta Delete%@AE@% function
discards the text without copying it to the Clipboard.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43105@%%@4@%To deal with whole lines of text, the Microsoft Editor provides the%@EH@%
following functions:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43106@%%@AB@%Function%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)    Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Ldelete%@AE@% (CTRL+Y)            Deletes a line of text or a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% (CTRL+N)            Inserts a line of text or a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43107@%%@4@%You can use these functions in commands without an argument or prefix. These%@EH@%
functions also take cursor-movement arguments. They produce the same results
that %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% and %@AI@%Insert%@AE@% do, but they always act as if the editor were in box
mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   When you want to delete or copy large areas of text, you may find the%@NL@%
   DIRECTION keys move too slowly. However, you can define a highlighted%@NL@%
   area with any cursor-movement function that does not take an argument.%@NL@%
   Mpage (PGUP) and Ppage (PGDN) can be used this way. The Ppara and Mpara%@NL@%
   functions can also be used this way, but they do not have default key%@NL@%
   assignments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
   To delete large amounts of text, you can also use a markarg or a numarg%@NL@%
   with a delete function. See Table A.3 for more information.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43200@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.3.2  Copying Text%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43201@%%@4@%To copy text without first deleting it, use the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% function (CTRL+INS),%@EH@%
which copies a range of text into the <clipboard> pseudo file. Text in the
Clipboard is then inserted into the file when you invoke the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% function.
The following list presents different commands that use the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% function:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43202@%%@AB@%Command     %@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)             Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg cursor-movementCopy%@AE@%              Copies the highlighted area into the%@NL@%
(ALT+A %@AI@%cursor-movement%@AE@% CTRL+INS)     Clipboard.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg numarg Copy%@AE@%                      Copies the specified number of lines%@NL@%
(ALT+A %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% CTRL+INS)              into the Clipboard, beginning with the%@NL@%
                                     line that the cursor is on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg markarg Copy%@AE@%                     Copies the text between the specified%@NL@%
(ALT+A %@AI@%markarg%@AE@% CTRL+INS)             marker and the cursor into the%@NL@%
                                     Clipboard. The shape of this region%@NL@%
                                     changes depending on whether the editor%@NL@%
                                     is in box or stream mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43203@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% function (SHIFT+INS) is useful both for moving and copying text.%@EH@%
To move text, first delete it and then invoke %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% after moving the cursor
to the destination.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   If you highlight an area on the screen and then invoke Paste, the editor%@NL@%
   deletes the highlighted area and replaces it with the contents of the%@NL@%
   Clipboard.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43204@%%@4@%See Section 4.4%@BO:   1839c@% for more information on markers.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43300@%%@3@%%@AB@%4.3.3  Other Insert Commands%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43301@%%@4@%The following functions insert specific items at the current cursor position%@EH@%
(each function is a complete command). These functions do not have
preassigned keys; see Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%, "Function Assignments and Macros," for
information on how to assign keys to functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43302@%%@AB@%Function                     Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curdate%@AE@%                     Inserts current date%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curday%@AE@%                      Inserts current day of the week%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curfile%@AE@%                     Inserts current file name%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curfileext%@AE@%                  Inserts current file extension%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curfilenam%@AE@%                  Inserts base name of current file%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Curtime%@AE@%                     Inserts current time%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43303@%%@4@%These functions all use time of execution, rather than time of editor%@EH@%
start-up, as the current time.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE43304@%%@4@%Although the functions above are not preassigned to any keystrokes, you can%@EH@%
assign them to keystrokes by using the technique described in Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%.
