%@CR:MSE50000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 5  Regular Expressions%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50001@%%@4@%A "regular expression" is a special search string that matches a %@AI@%pattern%@AE@% of%@EH@%
text rather than a specific sequence of characters. With regular
expressions, you can search for such targets as every five-digit number, or
every string in quotes, without having to specify the exact text to search
for.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50002@%%@4@%In a regular expression, certain characters lose their literal meaning,%@EH@%
becoming symbols or placeholders that specify the text pattern you want to
match. In a regular expression such as %@AS@%a[123]%@AE@%, the %@AS@%a%@AE@% is still the literal
character "a". The brackets, however, are not search targets. Rather, they
enclose a set of characters, any one of which is a match. Therefore, the
regular expression %@AS@%a[123]%@AE@% matches any of these strings:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%a1%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%a2%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%a3%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50004@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor supports two versions of regular-expression syntax:%@EH@%
UNIX(R) and M 1.0. The UNIX syntax provides compatibility with the syntax
used by programming utilities for the UNIX and XENIX(R) operating systems
and CodeView(R). M 1.0 syntax does not provide this compatibility; however,
it offers more power.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50005@%%@4@%This chapter examines three aspects of regular-expression syntax:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50006@%  ş  Choosing the syntax%@NL@%
  ş  Using UNIX syntax%@NL@%
  ş  Using M 1.0 syntax%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE50007@%%@4@%You can use regular expressions with the search functions (%@AI@%Psearch%@AE@%, %@AI@%Msearch%@AE@%,%@EH@%
%@AI@%Replace%@AE@%, and %@AI@%Qreplace%@AE@%). Each of these functions recognizes a regular
expression (rather than an ordinary text string) when you use %@AI@%Arg Arg%@AE@% to
introduce the string.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51000@%%@2@%%@AB@%5.1  Choosing the Syntax%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51001@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor supports two forms of regular-expression syntax: the%@EH@%
M 1.0 form and the UNIX standard. If you know the UNIX standard, you can use
it immediately. However, the slightly different M 1.0 syntax of the
Microsoft Editor is more powerful.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51002@%%@4@%By default, the editor recognizes the UNIX syntax for regular expressions.%@EH@%
To use the M 1.0 syntax instead, follow these steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51003@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following: %@AS@%unixre:no%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51004@%%@4@%To enable the standard UNIX syntax, follow the same steps but type %@AS@%unixre:%@AE@%%@EH@%
instead of %@AS@%unixre:no%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE51005@%%@4@%If you would like the editor to run automatically in M 1.0 mode, rather than%@EH@%
having to manually invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function, add a %@AS@%unixre:no%@AE@% entry to the
TOOLS.INI file. See Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, "Switches, Assignments, and the TOOLS.INI
File," for more information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52000@%%@2@%%@AB@%5.2  UNIX(R) Regular-Expression Syntax%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52001@%%@4@%The UNIX regular-expression syntax is compatibile with UNIX utilities and%@EH@%
CodeView. By default, the editor uses UNIX syntax for regular expressions.
The M 1.0 syntax offers the same capabilities as the UNIX syntax, plus a few
additional features.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52100@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.2.1  UNIX Regular Expressions as Simple Strings%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52101@%%@4@%The power of regular expressions comes from the use of the special%@EH@%
characters and character sequences listed below. A regular expression that
does not contain these special characters or character sequences acts as a
literal text string:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%\(  \)  [  ]  !  .  ^  $  *%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52103@%%@4@%For example, the regular expression %@AS@%match me precisely%@AE@% matches only a%@EH@%
literal occurrence of itself because it contains no special characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52200@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.2.2  UNIX Special Characters%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52201@%%@4@%The UNIX operators offer the standard pattern-matching capabilities found in%@EH@%
many other editors and utilities that use regular expressions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52202@%%@4@%The list below describes the special characters that have a simple usage.%@EH@%
The term %@AI@%class%@AE@% has a special meaning defined below. All other characters
should be interpreted literally.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52203@%%@AB@%Expression                  Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%\%@AE@%                           Escape. Causes the editor to ignore the special%@NL@%
                            meaning of the next character. For example, the%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%\.%@AE@% matches %@AS@%.%@AE@% in the text file; the%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%\^%@AE@% matches %@AS@% %@AE@%%@AS@%^%@AE@%; and the expression %@AS@%\\%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            matches %@AS@%\%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%.%@AE@%                           Wildcard. Matches any single character. For%@NL@%
                            example, the expression %@AS@%a.a%@AE@% matches %@AS@%aaa%@AE@%, %@AS@%aBa%@AE@%,%@NL@%
                            and %@AS@%a1a%@AE@%, but not %@AS@%aBBBa%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%^%@AE@%                           Beginning of line. For example, %@AS@%^The%@AE@% matches the%@NL@%
                            word %@AS@%The%@AE@% only when it occurs at the beginning of%@NL@%
                            a line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%$%@AE@%                           End of line. For example, %@AS@%end$%@AE@% matches the word %@AS@%%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            %@AS@%end%@AE@% only when it occurs at the end of a line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%[%@AE@%%@AI@%class%@AE@%%@AB@%]%@AE@%                     Character class. Matches any one character in%@NL@%
                            the class. Use a dash (%@AB@%-%@AE@%) to specify a%@NL@%
                            contiguous range of ASCII values. For example,%@NL@%
                            %@AS@%[a-zA-Z0-9]%@AE@% matches any letter or digit, and%@NL@%
                            %@AS@%[abc] %@AE@%%@AS@%%@AE@% matches %@AS@%a%@AE@%, %@AS@%b%@AE@%, or %@AS@%c%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%[^%@AE@%%@AI@%class%@AE@%%@AB@%]%@AE@%                    Inverse of character class. Matches any%@NL@%
                            character not specified in the class.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52204@%%@4@%The special characters with more complex usage are described in the%@EH@%
following list. The expression %@AI@%X%@AE@% is a placeholder representing a regular
expression that is either a single character, a group of characters enclosed
in brackets (%@AB@%[]%@AE@%), or the regular-expression delimiters %@AB@%\(%@AE@% and %@AB@%\)%@AE@%. The letter
%@AI@%n%@AE@% represents a one-digit number.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52205@%%@AB@%Expression                  Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%*%@AE@%                          Repeat operator. Matches zero or more%@NL@%
                            occurrences of %@AI@%X%@AE@%. For example, the regular%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%ba*b%@AE@% matches %@AS@%baaab%@AE@%, %@AS@%bab%@AE@%, and %@AS@%bb%@AE@%. This%@NL@%
                            operator always matches as many characters as%@NL@%
                            possible.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%\(%@AE@% ... %@AB@%\)%@AE@%                   Tagged expression. A marked substring which you%@NL@%
                            can refer to elsewhere in the search string, or%@NL@%
                            in a replacement string, as %@AB@%\%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%. When a tagged%@NL@%
                            expression is referred to in a search string,%@NL@%
                            the editor finds text with the tagged expression%@NL@%
                            repeated. When a tagged expression is referred%@NL@%
                            to in a replacement string, the editor reuses%@NL@%
                            part of the text it is replacing.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
                            The exact use of tags is explained in Sections%@NL@%
                            5.2.4%@BO:   231bc@% and 5.2.5%@BO:   23b94@%. Characters falling between %@NL@%
                            %@AB@%\(%@AE@% and %@AB@%\)%@AE@% are treated as a group.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%\%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%                          Reference to the characters matched by a tagged%@NL@%
                            expression. The number %@AI@%n%@AE@% indicates which%@NL@%
                            expression. The first tagged expression is%@NL@%
                            represented as %@AB@%\%@AE@%1, the second as %@AB@%\%@AE@%2, and so%@NL@%
                            on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52206@%%@4@%The procedure below uses some of the special characters presented in this%@EH@%
section. To find the next occurrence of a number (that is, a string of
digits) beginning with a digit 1 or 2, perform the following sequence of
keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52207@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% twice (press ALT+A twice)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following characters: %@AS@%[12][0-9]*%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% (press F3)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52300@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.2.3  Combining UNIX Special Characters%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52301@%%@4@%Special characters are most powerful when used in combination. For example,%@EH@%
the wildcard (%@AS@%.%@AE@%) and repeat (%@AS@%*%@AE@%) characters are often used together:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%.*%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52302@%%@4@%The expression above means "match any string of characters." Although this%@EH@%
expression is not useful by itself, it is quite useful when part of a larger
expression. For example,%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%B.*ing%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52303@%%@4@%means "match any string beginning with %@AS@%B%@AE@% and ending with %@AS@%ing%@AE@%".%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52304@%%@4@%In cases where a single character is surrounded by two operators, regular%@EH@%
expressions are interpreted from left to right. For example, suppose the
following is part of a regular expression:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%\1*%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52305@%%@4@%In the expression above, the repeat operator (%@AS@%*%@AE@%) applies to the characters%@EH@%
%@AS@%\1%@AE@% as a single unit.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52306@%%@4@%If you want the repeat operator to apply to a group, enclose the group%@EH@%
inside the symbols %@AB@%\%@AE@%( and %@AB@%\%@AE@%). These characters tag an expression (as
explained in the next section) and are useful for treating a series of
characters as a group.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52400@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.2.4  Tagged Expressions in the UNIX Search String%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52401@%%@4@%A "tagged expression" is a substring delimited by the symbols %@AB@%\%@AE@% (and %@AB@%\%@AE@%). You%@EH@%
can enter any regular-expression characters between these delimiters. Tagged
expressions are used to specify text patterns that contain repeated elements
and to mark a string for reuse.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52402@%%@4@%The editor first searches for a character string that matches the entire%@EH@%
regular expression. It then tags each substring specified in a tagged
expression. Up to nine substrings at a time may be tagged.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52403@%%@4@%Once a tagged expression has been matched, you can refer to the specific%@EH@%
string of characters that matched that expression. Use the syntax%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%\%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52405@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%n%@AE@% is a number that selects the expression. The symbol %@AS@%\1%@AE@%%@EH@%
represents the first tagged expression, the symbol %@AB@%\%@AE@%2 represents the second
tagged expression, and so on. The use of %@AB@%\%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@% does not search for a new match
for the tagged expression. Rather, it matches only an occurrence of the same
characters that the tagged expression itself matched.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52406@%%@4@%For example, consider the following expression:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%\(.\)\1\1%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52407@%%@4@%The expression above means, "match any character, then see if it's followed%@EH@%
by two occurrences of the same character." The following strings all satisfy
this requirement:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%aaa%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%XXX%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%111%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52409@%%@4@%Note that this regular expression is not equivalent to %@AS@%...%@AE@% (three wild%@EH@%
cards).  The expression %@AS@%...%@AE@% matches any three characters; the characters do
not need to be the same.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE5240A@%%@4@%The next expression is more complex:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%\([A-Za-z]*\)==\1%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE5240B@%%@4@%This expression means "match any number of letters, then see if the letters%@EH@%
are followed by two equals signs (%@AB@%==%@AE@%) and a repetition of the original
group." This expression matches the first two strings below but not the
third:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%ABCxyz==ABCxyz%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%i==i%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AS@%ABCxyz==KBCxjj%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52500@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.2.5  Tagged Expressions in the UNIX Replacement String%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52501@%%@4@%You can refer to tagged expressions in replacement strings as well as in%@EH@%
search strings. Parts of the string to be replaced may be reused by
referring to the tagged expressions that originally matched those parts. Use
the syntax described in the previous section.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52502@%%@4@%For example, suppose you want to find all occurrences of %@AI@%hexdigits%@AE@%%@AB@%H%@AE@% and%@EH@%
replace them with strings of the form %@AB@%16#%@AE@%%@AI@%hexdigits%@AE@%. You can search for
strings of the form %@AI@%hexdigits%@AE@%%@AB@%H%@AE@% by specifying the regular expression%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%\([0-9a-fA-F]*\)H%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52503@%%@4@%and then specifying the following replacement string:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%16#\1%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52504@%%@4@%The result is that the Microsoft Editor searches for any occurrence of one%@EH@%
or more hexadecimal digits (digits 0-9 and the letters a-f) followed by the
letter %@AB@%H%@AE@%. Each matching string is replaced by a new string that consists of
the original digits (which were tagged so they could be reused) and the
prefix %@AB@%16#%@AE@%. For example, the string %@AS@%1a000H%@AE@% is replaced with the string
%@AS@%16#1a000%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE52505@%%@4@%Use two backslashes (%@AB@%\\%@AE@%) to represent a literal backslash (%@AB@%\%@AE@%). Within%@EH@%
replacement strings, all characters except the backslashes are literals. The
backslash is considered to be the first character of a regular-expression
reference, such as %@AS@%\4%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53000@%%@2@%%@AB@%5.3  M 1.0 Regular-Expression Syntax%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53001@%%@4@%The M 1.0 syntax is fully compatible with the regular-expression syntax used%@EH@%
by Version 1.0 of the Microsoft Editor. This syntax offers all the features
of UNIX regular-expression syntax (though sometimes using different
characters), plus additional features.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53002@%%@4@%To choose M 1.0 syntax, you must set the %@AB@%unixre%@AE@% switch to off, as described%@EH@%
in Section 5.1%@BO:   20e9f@%, "Choosing the Syntax."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53100@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.3.1  M 1.0 Regular Expressions as Simple Strings%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53101@%%@4@%The power of regular expressions comes from the use of the special%@EH@%
characters listed below. A regular expression that does not contain these
special characters acts as if it were a literal text string:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%\  {  }  (  )  [  ]  !  ~  :  ?  ^  $  +  *  @  #%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53103@%%@4@%For example, the regular expression %@AS@%match me precisely%@AE@% matches only a%@EH@%
literal occurrence of itself because it contains no special characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53200@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.3.2  M 1.0 Special Characters%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53201@%%@4@%The M 1.0 syntax offers a rich set of pattern-matching capabilities. Most of%@EH@%
the special characters described below have analogs in other editors and
utilities that use regular expressions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53202@%%@4@%The list below describes the special characters that have a simple usage.%@EH@%
The term %@AI@%class%@AE@% has a special meaning defined below. All other characters
should be interpreted literally.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53203@%%@AB@%Expression                  Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%\%@AE@%                           Escape. Causes the editor to ignore the special%@NL@%
                            meaning of the next character. For example, the%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%\?%@AE@% matches %@AS@%?%@AE@% in the text file; the%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%\^%@AE@% matches %@AS@% %@AE@%%@AS@%^%@AE@%; and the expression %@AS@%\\%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            matches %@AS@%\%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%?%@AE@%                           Wildcard. Matches any single character. For%@NL@%
                            example, the expression %@AS@%a?a%@AE@% matches %@AS@%aaa%@AE@%, %@AS@%aBa%@AE@%,%@NL@%
                            and %@AS@%a1a%@AE@%, but not %@AS@%aBBBa%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%^%@AE@%                           Beginning of line. For example, %@AS@%^The%@AE@% matches the%@NL@%
                            word %@AS@%The%@AE@% only when it occurs at the beginning of%@NL@%
                            a line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%$%@AE@%                           End of line. For example, %@AS@%end$%@AE@% matches the word %@AS@%%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            %@AS@%end%@AE@% only when it occurs at the end of a line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%[%@AE@%%@AI@%class%@AE@%%@AB@%]%@AE@%                     Character class. Matches any one character in%@NL@%
                            the class. Use a dash (%@AB@%-%@AE@%) to specify ranges. For%@NL@%
                            example, %@AS@%[a-zA-Z0-9]%@AE@% matches any character or%@NL@%
                            digit, and %@AS@%[abc]%@AE@% matches %@AS@%a%@AE@%, %@AS@%b%@AE@%, or %@AS@%c%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%[~%@AE@%%@AI@%class%@AE@%%@AB@%]%@AE@%                    Noncharacter class. Matches any character not%@NL@%
                            specified in the class.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53204@%%@4@%The special characters with more complex usage are described in the%@EH@%
following list. The expression %@AI@%X%@AE@% is a placeholder representing a regular
expression that is either a single character or a group of characters
enclosed in parentheses (%@AB@%()%@AE@%), brackets (%@AB@%[]%@AE@%), or braces (%@AB@%{}%@AE@%). The
placeholders %@AI@%X1%@AE@%, %@AI@%X2%@AE@%, and so on, represent any regular expression.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53205@%%@AU@%Expression                  Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%*%@AE@%                          Minimal matching. Matches zero or more%@NL@%
                            occurrences of %@AI@%X%@AE@%. For example: the regular%@NL@%
                            expression %@AS@%ba*b%@AE@% matches %@AS@%baaab%@AE@%, %@AS@%bab%@AE@%, and %@AS@%bb%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%+%@AE@%                          Minimal matching plus (shorthand for %@AI@%XX%@AE@%%@AB@%*%@AE@%).%@NL@%
                            Matches one or more occurrences of %@AI@%X%@AE@%. The%@NL@%
                            regular expression %@AS@%ba+b%@AE@% matches %@AS@%baab%@AE@% and %@AS@%bab%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            but not %@AS@%bb%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%@%@AE@%                          Maximal matching. Identical to %@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%*%@AE@%, except for%@NL@%
                            differences in matching method explained in%@NL@%
                            Section 5.3.4.%@BO:   26bc3@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%#%@AE@%                          Maximal matching plus. Identical to %@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%+%@AE@%, except%@NL@%
                            for differences in matching method explained in%@NL@%
                            Section 5.3.4.%@BO:   26bc3@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%(%@AE@%%@AI@%X1%@AE@%%@AB@%!%@AE@%%@AI@%X2%@AE@%%@AB@%!%@AE@%...%@AB@%!%@AE@%%@AI@%Xn%@AE@%%@AB@%)%@AE@%              Alternation. Matches either %@AI@%X1%@AE@%, %@AI@%X2%@AE@%, and so%@NL@%
                            forth. It tries to match them in that order and%@NL@%
                            switches from %@AI@%Xi%@AE@% to %@AI@%Xi+1%@AE@% only if the rest of the%@NL@%
                            expression fails to match. For example, the%@NL@%
                            regular expression %@AS@%(ww!xx!xxyy)zz%@AE@% matches %@AS@%xxzz%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            on the second alternative and %@AS@%xxyyzz%@AE@% on the%@NL@%
                            third.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%~%@AE@%%@AI@%X%@AE@%                          Not function. Matches nothing, but checks to see%@NL@%
                            if the string matches %@AI@%X%@AE@% at this point and fails%@NL@%
                            if it does. For example, %@AS@%^~(if!while)?*$%@AE@% matches%@NL@%
                            all lines that do not begin with %@AS@%if%@AE@% or %@AS@%while%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%X%@AE@%%@AB@%^%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%                         Power function. Matches exactly %@AI@%n%@AE@% copies of %@AI@%X%@AE@%.%@NL@%
                            For example, %@AS@%w^4%@AE@% matches %@AS@%wwww%@AE@% and %@AS@%(a?)^3%@AE@% matches%@NL@%
                            %@AS@%a#aba5%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%{%@AE@%...%@AB@%}%@AE@%                       Tagged expression, which is a string of%@NL@%
                            characters you identify so that you can refer to%@NL@%
                            them elsewhere, as %@AB@%$%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%. By referring to a tagged%@NL@%
                            expression in a search string, you cause the%@NL@%
                            editor to look for patterns involving%@NL@%
                            duplication. By referring to a tagged expression%@NL@%
                            in a replacement string, you cause the editor to%@NL@%
                            reuse part of the text that it is replacing.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
                            The exact use of tags is explained in Sections%@NL@%
                            5.3.5%@BO:   27441@% and 5.3.6%@BO:   27df8@%. Characters within braces are%@NL@%
                            treated as a group.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%$%@AE@%%@AI@%n%@AE@%                          Reference to a previously tagged substring. The%@NL@%
                            number %@AI@%n%@AE@% indicates which substring. The first%@NL@%
                            tagged substring is represented as %@AB@%$%@AE@% 1, the%@NL@%
                            second as %@AB@%$%@AE@% 2, and so on. %@AB@%$%@AE@% 0 represents the%@NL@%
                            entire matched string.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%letter%@AE@%                     Predefined string. The list of predefined%@NL@%
                            strings is given in Section 5.3.7.%@BO:   2885d@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53206@%%@4@%The procedure below uses some of the special characters presented in this%@EH@%
section. To find the next occurrence of a number (that is, a string of
digits) beginning with a digit 1 or 2, perform the following sequence of
keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53207@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% twice(press ALT + A twice)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following characters: %@AS@%[12][0-9]*%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% (press F3)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53300@%%@3@%%@AB@%5.3.3  Combining M 1.0 Special Characters%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53301@%%@4@%Special characters are most powerful when used in combination. For example,%@EH@%
the %@AS@%?%@AE@% and %@AS@%*%@AE@% characters are often used together:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%?*%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53302@%%@4@%The expression above means "match any string of characters." Although this%@EH@%
expression is not useful by itself, it is quite useful when part of a larger
expression. For example,%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%B?*ing%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53303@%%@4@%means "match any characters beginning with %@AS@%B%@AE@% and ending with %@AS@%ing%@AE@%".%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53304@%%@4@%Many of the special characters in the previous section (such as + and *) are%@EH@%
%@AI@%operators%@AE@%; they work with other characters to form expressions. These
operators usually apply to the previous character or an expression enclosed
in braces, brackets, or parentheses. However, it is possible to find
exceptions to this rule. For example, the following expression is
meaningful:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AS@%S^2+%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE53305@%%@4@%The plus sign (%@AS@%+%@AE@%) applies to the entire expression %@AS@%S^2%@AE@%. In effect, this%@EH@%
expression means, "match any even number of occurrences of the letter S."
