%@CR:MSE60000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 6  Function Assignments and Macros%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE60001@%%@4@%One of the strengths of the Microsoft Editor is you can customize it to your%@EH@%
own needs. You can change screen characteristics, select default behavior,
and specify which functions are connected to which keystrokes. You can also
create new editing functions. The editor supports four techniques for
customization, described in Section 6.1.%@BO:   292f2@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE60002@%%@4@%This chapter discusses two of those techniques: function assignments and%@EH@%
macros. Function assignments alter the action of keystrokes. Macros are
editing commands that you create using a simple syntax. The other two
methods for customizing the editor, switch settings and C extensions, are
described in Chapters 7%@BO:   3396c@%, 8%@BO:   3fbeb@%, and 9%@BO:   50fea@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE60003@%%@4@%This chapter covers the following topics:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE60004@%  ş  Techniques for customizing the editor%@NL@%
  ş  Assigning functions to keystrokes%@NL@%
  ş  Creating macros%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE61000@%%@2@%%@AB@%6.1  The Four Techniques for Customizing the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE61001@%%@4@%Each of the four techniques for customizing the editor has a distinct%@EH@%
purpose. Yet you can use these techniques in combination. For example, an
extension can execute a macro, and a macro can make an assignment. Each
technique is described below:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE61002@%%@AB@%Technique                   Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Function assignment         Assigns a function to a particular keystroke.%@NL@%
                            This capability lets you control the meaning of%@NL@%
                            all recognized keystrokes.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Macro assignment            Creates a new editing command out of strings of%@NL@%
                            text and existing editing functions. Macros use%@NL@%
                            a simple syntax and can be created very fast.%@NL@%
                            Use macros when you need to quickly define a new%@NL@%
                            command or repetitive activity.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Switch assignment           Alters a specific editor condition, for example,%@NL@%
                            screen colors, screen height, scrolling%@NL@%
                            behavior, tab behavior, and many other%@NL@%
                            conditions. These conditions are adjusted by%@NL@%
                            setting various editing "switches," as explained%@NL@%
                            in Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
C extension                 Generates a new editing function compiled with%@NL@%
                            Microsoft C or assembled with the Macro%@NL@%
                            Assembler. Extensions take longer to create than%@NL@%
                            macros, but they run faster and are more%@NL@%
                            flexible. See Chapter 8%@BO:   3fbeb@% for more information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62000@%%@2@%%@AB@%6.2  Assigning Functions to Keystrokes%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62001@%%@4@%A function assignment lets you alter the meaning of any keystroke. In this%@EH@%
context, a "keystroke" is any recognized function key, special key, or ALT+,
SHIFT+, or CTRL+key combination. You can also alter the meaning of
alphanumeric keys, but doing so can interfere with your ability to type
characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Any editing function, macro, or extension function can be assigned to a%@NL@%
   keystroke as described in this chapter.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62002@%%@4@%When a new assignment has been made, you can use that keystroke to invoke%@EH@%
the function at any time during the editing session. Take into account the
following points when assigning functions to keystrokes:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62003@%  1. The function assignments you make during the editing session are lost%@NL@%
     when you exit the editor. See Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, "Switches, Assignments, and%@NL@%
     the TOOLS.INI File," for information on making assignments that are%@NL@%
     automatically recognized in each editing session.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     When using the assignments screen to view and alter assignments, you%@NL@%
     have the option of automatically saving your changes. See Section%@NL@%
     6.2.2%@BO:   2b13c@%, "Viewing and Changing Function Assignments," for more%@NL@%
     information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. A function can be assigned to more than one keystroke at the same time.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Each keystroke can have only one function assigned to it at any one%@NL@%
     time. Therefore, a new function assignment to a given keystroke cancels%@NL@%
     any previous meaning the keystroke may have had. Assigning the%@NL@%
     %@AI@%Unassigned%@AE@% function, as explained in Section 6.2.3%@BO:   2bbd2@%, cancels the%@NL@%
     keystroke's previous meaning without substituting a new meaning.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62100@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.2.1  Making Function Assignments%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62101@%%@4@%There are two ways to make a function assignment. You can use the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%%@EH@%
function, or edit the assignments screen as described in the next section.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62102@%%@4@%To assign a function to a keystroke with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command, issue the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%%@EH@%
%@AI@%textarg Assign%@AE@% command (ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% ALT+=), where %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% uses the
following syntax:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%functionname%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%keystroke%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62104@%%@4@%Here, %@AI@%keystroke%@AE@% may be any of the following:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62105@%  1. Numeric keys: 0 through 9%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Lowercase letter keys: a through z%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Uppercase letter keys: A through Z%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Function keys: F1 through F10 (F11 and F12 recognized for enhanced%@NL@%
     keyboards)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. Lowercase punctuation: ` - = [ ] \ ; ' , . /%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. Uppercase punctuation: ~ ! @ # $ % ^ & * ( ) _ + { } | : " ?%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  7. Numeric-keypad white keys when NUMLOCK is turned off: HOME, END, LEFT,%@NL@%
     RIGHT, UP, DOWN, PGUP, PGDN, INS, and GOTO, which corresponds to the%@NL@%
     numeric-keypad 5 key.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  8. Numeric-keypad white keys when NUMLOCK is turned on: 0 through 9. To%@NL@%
     assign a function to the 4 key on the numeric keypad, enter the%@NL@%
     following as the %@AI@%keystroke%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         %@AS@%NUM4%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  9. Numeric-keypad gray keys: NUM-, NUM+, and NUM*%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 10. Other named keys: BKSP, TAB, ESC, SPACEBAR, and ENTER%@NL@%
%@NL@%
 11. Combinations:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     a.   ALT+ followed by items 1, 2, 4, 5, 9, or 10%@NL@%
     b.   CTRL+ followed by items 2, 4, 7, 8, 9, or 10%@NL@%
     c.   SHIFT+ followed by items 4, 7, 8, 9, or 10%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62106@%%@4@%If you have a Tandy(R) 1000, the following additional keystrokes are%@EH@%
recognized:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62107@%  1. Function keys: F11 and F12%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. CTRL+ followed by UP and DOWN%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. ALT+ followed by UP, DOWN, LEFT, and RIGHT%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. SHIFT+ followed by UP, DOWN, LEFT, and RIGHT%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62108@%%@4@%If you have a 101-key enhanced keyboard, all the keystrokes recognized for%@EH@%
the Tandy 1000 are supported, as well as the following: NUMENTER, NUM\, and
all CTRL, ALT, and SHIFT combinations of these two keys. In addition, the
enhanced keyboard has a duplicate set of item 7 above, which is not affected
by the state of NUMLOCK. All CTRL, ALT, and SHIFT combinations of these keys
are recognized.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62109@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6210A@%%@4@%For example, the function %@AI@%Savecur%@AE@% is assigned to the keystroke CTRL+B in%@EH@%
this manner:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6210B@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the function and keystroke as the %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% by typing the%@NL@%
     following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         %@AS@%savecur:CTRL+W%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Note that function names are not case-sensitive, so you can enter them%@NL@%
     as all lowercase.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6210C@%%@4@%From this point on, pressing CTRL+W invokes the %@AI@%Savecur%@AE@% function and saves%@EH@%
the current cursor position. You can make this assignment automatic by
placing it in the TOOLS.INI file, as explained in Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62200@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.2.2  Viewing and Changing Function Assignments%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62201@%%@4@%The <assign> pseudo file shows you what function assignments and switch%@EH@%
values are in effect at any time during the editing session. This file lists
all functions in alphabetical order along with the keys to which they are
assigned. Use any of the following methods to get to this screen:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62202@%  ş  Press SHIFT+F1 to get the initial Help screen. Then select Current%@NL@%
     Assignments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  Use the %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% function (F2), giving %@AS@%<assign>%@AE@% as a text argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  Give the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command (ALT+A), entering a question mark (%@AS@%?%@AE@%) as a text%@NL@%
     argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62203@%%@4@%Once you get to the assignments screen, you can scroll through the%@EH@%
information as you would through any file.  Use the %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% function (F2) to
return to your original file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62204@%%@4@%You can also change assignments from within this file by following these%@EH@%
steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62205@%  1. Move the cursor to the line that contains the function assignment you%@NL@%
     wish to change.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Edit the line so that it contains a new function assignment.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Move the cursor to a different line. If the assignment you entered is%@NL@%
     syntactically correct, the editor highlights the line to show that the%@NL@%
     new assignment was accepted. If the assignment was incorrect, the%@NL@%
     editor restores the line to its previous state and reports an error%@NL@%
     message.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62206@%%@4@%You can execute a save operation while in the <assign> pseudo file by giving%@EH@%
the %@AI@%Arg Arg Setfile%@AE@% command. This command (which normally saves a file to
disk under its own name) directs the editor to write any new assignments you
have made to the TOOLS.INI file. Each time it starts, the editor
automatically recognizes function assignments placed in this file. See
Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, "Switches, Assignments, and the TOOLS.INI File," for more
information about TOOLS.INI.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62207@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Tell%@AE@% function (CTRL+T) gives you an alternative way of seeing what%@EH@%
function is assigned to any given keystroke. Give the command %@AI@%Arg Tell%@AE@%
(ALT+A CTRL+T), then enter a keystroke. The editor prints the name of the
function assigned to this keystroke on the dialog line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62208@%%@4@%For more information on the %@AI@%Tell%@AE@% function, see Appendix A%@BO:   5d119@%, "Reference%@EH@%
Tables."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62300@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.2.3  Disabling a Keystroke%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62301@%%@4@%To disable a keystroke so it invokes no function at all, assign the function%@EH@%
%@AI@%Unassigned%@AE@% to the keystroke. As with other function assignments, use the
%@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@% command. The argument %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% uses the following syntax:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%unassigned%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%key%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62303@%%@4@%Here, %@AI@%key%@AE@% is the keystroke you want to remove.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62304@%%@4@%For example, to disable the keystroke CTRL+A, perform the following steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62305@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the function name as %@AI@%Unassigned%@AE@% and the keystroke by typing the%@NL@%
     following:%@AS@% unassigned:CTRL+A%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62306@%%@4@%After these steps are carried out, pressing CTRL+A does not invoke any%@EH@%
functions. (Disabling a keystroke is temporary if you have set the key
assignment in the TOOLS.INI file. For permanent results, change the
TOOLS.INI file.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62400@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.2.4  Making a Keystroke Literal%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62401@%%@4@%Many text editors allow you to enter only alphanumeric characters and%@EH@%
punctuation into a file. However, the Microsoft Editor makes it easy for you
to insert special characters.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62402@%%@4@%Each keystroke corresponds to an ASCII value. When a keystroke is considered%@EH@%
a "literal" or "graphic," pressing the key causes the editor to place the
corresponding value into the file.  For example, if you make the keystroke
CTRL+D a literal key, the editor places a character with the decimal value 4
into the file each time you press CTRL+D.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   When you use a special keystroke (such as %@AI@%F1%@AE@% or %@AI@%ALT+A%@AE@%) as a literal, it%@NL@%
   loses any special meaning it would otherwise have and will not invoke a%@NL@%
   function. If the special value is one that can be printed (for example,%@NL@%
   if it is a printable extended-ASCII character), the editor displays the%@NL@%
   corresponding character on the screen.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62403@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor provides two methods for converting a keystroke to a%@EH@%
literal character. The first method is to use the %@AI@%Quote%@AE@% function. When you
invoke the %@AI@%Quote%@AE@% function (CTRL+P),  the next key that you pressÄÄregardless
of what-ever special meaning it may otherwise haveÄÄis regarded as a literal
character.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62404@%%@4@%The second method is to assign the %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% function to the keystroke.  This%@EH@%
uses the same syntax as any other function assignment: %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@%.
Assigning %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% cancels any previous assignment to the keystroke, and
causes the editor to consider the keystroke a literal character. For
example, to insert a form-feed character in the file whenever CTRL+L is
pressed, first follow these steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62405@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the function %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% and the keystroke as the %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% by typing%@NL@%
     the following: %@AS@%graphic:CTRL+L%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62406@%%@4@%The choice between assigning the %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% function or invoking the %@AI@%Quote%@AE@%%@EH@%
function depends on the situation. If you want to enter a special value into
the file repeatedly, it is often easier to assign the %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% function to
the keystrokeÄÄsince you only need to do it once. However, use of the %@AI@%Quote%@AE@%
function provides you with more control.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE62407@%%@4@%By default, the %@AI@%Graphic%@AE@% function is assigned to all alphanumeric characters.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63000@%%@2@%%@AB@%6.3  Creating Macros within the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63001@%%@4@%The fastest way to create a new editing function for the Microsoft Editor is%@EH@%
to create a macro. This editing function can be as simple as inserting a
long word or phrase, or it can involve complex operations.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63002@%%@4@%There are two ways to create a macro. The easiest is to use the %@AI@%Record%@AE@%%@EH@%
function to automatically record a series of actions. You can also enter a
macro directly. The second method requires more knowledge of syntax, but
allows you to use sophisticated features, such as conditionals.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63003@%%@4@%After you have used the editor for awhile, you may want to use both methods.%@EH@%
You can create a simple function by recording a macro, then increase the
macro's power by editing it directly, using the techniques described in
Sections 6.3.2%@BO:   2def3@%-6.3.8.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63004@%%@4@%Once a macro is defined and assigned to a keystroke, you can see how the%@EH@%
macro is defined by using the %@AI@%Tell%@AE@% function. Give the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%%@AI@%textarg Tell%@AE@%
command (ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% CTRL+T), in which %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is the name of the macro.
For more information on the %@AI@%Tell%@AE@% function, see Appendix A%@BO:   5d119@%, "Reference
Tables."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63005@%%@4@%The maximum number of macros that can be defined at one time is 1,024.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63100@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.1  Recording a Macro%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63101@%%@4@%Much like a tape recorder, the %@AI@%Record%@AE@% (ALT+R) function tells the editor,%@EH@%
"make a record of all editing commands until I tell you to stop." After you
stop the recording, the editor creates a macro function consisting of all
the editing commands you just gave. When you invoke this macro, the editor
plays back these commands in the order you gave them.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63102@%%@4@%While the editor is recording commands, the letters %@AS@%REC%@AE@% appear at the end of%@EH@%
the status line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63103@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Record%@AE@% function starts a recording and gives the macro the default name %@EH@%
%@AB@%recordvalue%@AE@% when the recording is done. Invoking %@AI@%Record%@AE@% again turns the
recording off.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63104@%%@4@%The following steps are the quickest way to create a macro:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63105@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Record%@AE@% function (ALT+R) to start the recording.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Execute the series of actions you wish to record.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Turn off the recording by invoking %@AI@%Record%@AE@% (ALT+R) again.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. If %@AB@%recordvalue%@AE@% is not already assigned, assign it to a keystroke as%@NL@%
     described in Section 6.2%@BO:   29ab0@%, "Assigning Functions to Keystrokes."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63106@%%@4@%After you complete these steps, the editor associates the new macro with the%@EH@%
keystroke that %@AB@%recordvalue%@AE@% is assigned to. Whenever you press this key, the
editor plays back the editing commands you gave in Step 2 above.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63107@%%@4@%Other variations of the %@AI@%Record%@AE@% function are shown below:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63108@%%@AB@%Command     %@AE@%%@NL@%
%@AB@%(and Default Keystrokes)    Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg textarg Record%@AE@%          Turns on a recording. When the recording is%@NL@%
(ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% ALT+R)       finished, the macro is given the name specified%@NL@%
                            in the text argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Meta Record%@AE@% (F9 ALT+R)      Turns on a recording in which commands you give%@NL@%
                            are recorded but not executed. This is in effect%@NL@%
                            a silent recording.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AI@%Arg Arg textarg Record%@AE@%      Turns on a recording, but if the specified macro%@NL@%
(ALT+A ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%        already exists, the editor appends editing%@NL@%
ALT+R)                      commands to the macro instead of replacing it.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63109@%%@4@%By using the window and file commands described in Chapter 4%@BO:   120e2@%, you can open%@EH@%
a second window and load the <record> pseudo file. This file dynamically
displays the value of the current recording.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6310A@%%@4@%By opening the <record> pseudo file in a separate window, you can watch the%@EH@%
editor record the macro as you create it. The macro writes out the actual
name of each editing command you give. As a result, the editor displays a
macro definition using the syntax described in the next section.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63200@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.2  Entering a Macro Directly%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63201@%%@4@%A macro is nothing more than a predefined series of functions and/or literal%@EH@%
text. This fact makes the syntax of most macros almost self-evident: you
build a macro by using the same syntax used throughout this manual. The most
advanced macros, however, use the return value of functions to alter control
flow. This special feature is presented in Section 6.3.8%@BO:   320fc@%, "Macros That Use
Conditionals."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63202@%%@4@%To define a macro directly, follow these steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63203@%  1. Choose a name. The name should not be a macro or function name already%@NL@%
     in use.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the macro definition by using the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@% command%@NL@%
     (ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% ALT+=), in which %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% has the following syntax:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%macroname%@AE@%%@AB@%:=%@AE@%%@AI@%list%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     No spaces should separate %@AI@%macroname%@AE@% from the definition symbol (%@AB@%:=%@AE@%).%@NL@%
     The %@AI@%list%@AE@% contains function names and text strings enclosed in double%@NL@%
     quotes, as explained in the next section.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Assign the macro with the command %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@%, in which the%@NL@%
     %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% has the following form:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%macroname%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%keystroke%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63204@%%@4@%The last step is optional. If you want to build a nested macro as described%@EH@%
in Section 6.3.5%@BO:   302f6@%, only the last macro defined needs to be assigned to a
keystroke.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63205@%%@4@%Instead of assigning a macro to a keystroke, you can execute the macro by%@EH@%
giving its name as input to the %@AI@%Execute%@AE@% function, as explained in Section
6.3.4%@BO:   2ff89@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63206@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63207@%%@4@%The following sequence of actions defines a macro called %@AS@%InsPhrase%@AE@%, which%@EH@%
inserts a certain sentence. The simplest macros insert a fixed string of
textÄÄthese macros are useful because they can save you a lot of typing.
This macro is then assigned to the key CTRL+F10. After you do the following
action, the editor inserts the words "This is a sentence." at the current
cursor position, every time you press CTRL+F10.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63208@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Enter the macro name and definition by typing the following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
        %@AS@%InsPhrase:="This is a sentence."%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. Assign this macro to a keystroke by typing the following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
        %@AS@%InsPhrase:CTRL+F10%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63300@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.3  Building the Macro List%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63301@%%@4@%Each item in a macro-definition list is either a function name or a string%@EH@%
of text. The function names are the same as used throughout this manual but
are not case sensitive. You can enter them all lowercase, all uppercase, or
any combination.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63302@%%@4@%Each string of text must be enclosed in quotes. Embedded quote marks are%@EH@%
represented as \", and embedded backslashes are represented as \\.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63303@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63304@%%@4@%The following text arguments are all valid macro definitions:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Callfun:="x = QuadCalc(a, b, c);"%@NL@%
     Callfun2:=linsert begline "x = QuadCalc(a, b, c);"%@NL@%
     Movedown:=arg "15" plines%@NL@%
     Putcomm:=begline "/*  " endline " */"%@NL@%
     Join:=endline right arg sdelete%@NL@%
     Del3:=arg right right right ldelete%@NL@%
     Join2:=savecur endline right arg sdelete restcur%@NL@%
     endword:=arg arg "( !.!$!\\:!;!\\)!\\(!,)" psearch%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63305@%%@4@%The rest of this section examines each of these macro definitions.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Callfun:="x = QuadCalc(a, b, c);"%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63306@%%@4@%The example above defines a macro that inserts the text "x = QuadCalc(a, b,%@EH@%
c);" whenever invoked. This macro is simple, yet useful. It replaces the
typing of a phrase with a single editing function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63307@%%@4@%Executing this macro has the same effect as typing the phrase. The precise%@EH@%
effect of this macro therefore depends on whether insert mode is on or off.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Callfun2:=linsert begline "x = QuadCalc(a, b, c);"%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63308@%%@4@%The example above uses both function names and text to define a new editing%@EH@%
function. The effect of invoking this macro is precisely the same as the
effect of invoking %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@%, invoking %@AI@%Begline%@AE@%, and then typing the text
inside the quotes. The macro inserts a new line and places the text at the
beginning of this line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Movedown:=arg "15" plines%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63309@%%@4@%Like the example before it, the example above uses a combination of%@EH@%
functions and a string of text. However, because the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function precedes
the text, the text does not appear on screen. Instead, the text becomes an
argument to the %@AI@%Plines%@AE@% function. This macro moves the window down 15 lines.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Putcomm:=begline "/*  " endline " */"%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330A@%%@4@%The example above uses a combination of functions and text to insert%@EH@%
C-language comment marks at the beginning and end of a line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Join:=endline right arg sdelete%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330B@%%@4@%The example above defines a macro that joins the current line to the next%@EH@%
line. Recall that the sequence %@AI@%Arg Sdelete%@AE@% deletes all text to the right of
the cursor, then joins lines.  This macro does not delete any text. First,
it moves the cursor to the end of the line. Next, it moves one space to the
right to leave a space before the next line. It then executes %@AI@%Arg Sdelete%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330C@%%@4@%You can use the cursor-movement functions (%@AI@%Up%@AE@%, %@AI@%Down%@AE@%, %@AI@%Right%@AE@%, %@AI@%Left%@AE@%) within%@EH@%
macros.  The next macro uses these functions to build an on-screen argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Del3:=arg right right right ldelete%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330D@%%@4@%The example above deletes three characters. The middle three arguments%@EH@%
create a cursor-movement argument that is passed to the %@AI@%Ldelete%@AE@% function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Join2:=savecur endline right arg sdelete restcur%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330E@%%@4@%The example above performs almost the same activity as the %@AS@%Join%@AE@% macro%@EH@%
presented earlier. However, this macro begins by saving the cursor position
with %@AI@%Savecur%@AE@%. After the lines are joined, the macro restores the original
cursor position by executing %@AI@%Restcur%@AE@%. This macro works even if %@AI@%Savecur%@AE@% and
%@AI@%Restcur%@AE@% have not been assigned to keystrokes.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     endword:=arg arg "( !.!$!\\:!;!\\)!\\(!,)" psearch%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330F@%%@4@%This last example uses the regular-expression syntax described in Chapter%@EH@%
5%@BO:   206bc@%. The %@AI@%Arg Arg%@AE@% syntax directs the %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@% function to treat the text
argument as a regular-expression pattern. This pattern, in turn, causes the
editor to find the next space, period (.), end of line ($), colon (:),
semicolon (;), right parenthesis ()), left parenthesis ((), or comma (,).
Some characters must be preceded by a backslash (\) in order to be
interpreted literally. Furthermore, when you give a text argument inside a
macro list, you must use two backslashes in a row (\\) to indicate a single
backslash.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6330G@%%@4@%The effect of this macro is to go to the end of the current word. By%@EH@%
rewriting the regular expression, you control what constitutes the end of a
word. This macro can be especially useful when nested inside other macros,
as described in Section 6.3.5.%@BO:   302f6@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63400@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.4  Executing a Macro List Directly%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63401@%%@4@%Instead of defining a macro and then assigning it to a keystroke, you can%@EH@%
execute a macro-definition list directly, by using the %@AI@%Execute%@AE@% function.
This function, which by default is assigned to F7, takes a function name,
macro name, or macro-definition command list as a text argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63402@%%@4@%For example, the following sequence finds the next occurrence of the word%@EH@%
%@AS@%fluke%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63403@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following string: %@AS@%arg "fluke" psearch%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke %@AI@%Execute%@AE@% (press F7)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63404@%%@4@%You can also give the name of a macro as input to the %@AI@%Execute%@AE@% command.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63500@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.5  Building Macros from Other Macros%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63501@%%@4@%Macros can contain references to previously defined macros.  Since a macro%@EH@%
definition must be contained on one line (except in the TOOLS.INI file,
where you can use a line-continuation character), you may need to break up a
macro definition into several smaller macros as shown in the example below.
Only the final macro definition need be assigned to a keystroke. Each of the
following lines is entered one at a time using the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@%
command:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     head1:=arg "3" linsert "/************************"%@NL@%
     head2:=newline "** Routine:"%@NL@%
     head3:=newline "*************************/"%@NL@%
     header:=head1 head2 head3%@NL@%
     header:alt+h%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63502@%%@4@%The example above inserts three blank lines (by passing the argument 3 to%@EH@%
the %@AI@%Linsert%@AE@% function), and then inserts the given strings of text. The macro
is then assigned to ALT+H. This macro is an example of one that automates
the creation of comment blocks for C programs.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Nested macros are cumbersome to enter while running the editor. Usually,%@NL@%
   you'll want to enter them once in your TOOLS.INI file so that they are%@NL@%
   available automatically, as explained in Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63600@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.6  Handling Prompts within Macros%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63601@%%@4@%Some commands prompt the user for confirmation. For example, the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@%%@AI@%Exit%@AE@%%@EH@%
command (exit without saving) asks the user if he really wants to exit.
These questions take the answer yes (Y) or no (N).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63602@%%@4@%By default, macros assume an answer of yes. For example, if you assigned%@EH@%
%@AI@%Meta Exit%@AE@% to a macro and then executed the macro, the editor would not
prompt for confirmation. Instead, the editor would assume an answer of yes
and proceed to exit without saving.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63603@%%@4@%You can control the answers to prompts within macros by using the following%@EH@%
operators, each of which applies to the immediately preceding function:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63604@%%@AB@%Operator                    Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%<%@AE@%                           Asks the user for confirmation. (If not followed%@NL@%
                            by another %@AB@%<%@AE@% character, prompts user for all%@NL@%
                            further questions.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%<Y%@AE@%                          Assumes an answer of yes.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%<N%@AE@%                          Assumes an answer of no.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63605@%%@4@%You can use a series of operators. For example, consider the following%@EH@%
macro:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     newfile:=arg "newfile.txt" setfile <y <n%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63606@%%@4@%The macro %@AS@%newfile%@AE@% assumes an answer of yes for the first prompt, and no for%@EH@%
the second. If %@AS@%newfile%@AE@% requires only one prompt, it ignores the second
operator, %@AS@%<n%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63607@%%@4@%If the last prompt character that appears is %@AS@%<%@AE@%, the editor prompts the user%@EH@%
directly for all remaining yes/no questions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63608@%%@4@%You can use the prompt characters throughout your macro. For example:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     newfile:=refresh < arg "newfile.txt" setfile <y <n <%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63700@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.7  Macros That Take Arguments%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63701@%%@4@%Macros have no explicit syntax for accepting user-defined arguments.%@EH@%
However, if you enter an argument and then invoke a macro, the argument is
passed to the first function that accepts an argument:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     tripleit:=copy paste paste%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63702@%%@4@%In the example above, you can invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% and use cursor movement to%@EH@%
highlight an argument. Then invoke %@AS@%tripleit%@AE@%. Your highlighted argument is
passed to the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% function, which copies the argument to the Clipboard. The
macro then executes the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% function two times. As a result, two
additional copies of the argument are added to the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63703@%%@4@%If you do not highlight an argument before invoking %@AS@%tripleit%@AE@%, the macro%@EH@%
responds by printing two more copies of the current line. By default,
%@AS@%tripleit%@AE@% works on the current line because %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% selects the current line
when no argument is given.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63704@%%@4@%When you execute the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@% or %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% function at the beginning of a macro,%@EH@%
the highlighted argument is stored in the Clipboard. You can then load the
<clipboard> pseudo file and manipulate the argument itself, as in the
following macro:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     addto1:=copy arg "<clipboard>" setfile%@NL@%
     addto2:=arg arg "TMP.TXT" setfile%@NL@%
     addto3:=arg "type TMP.TXT >>> BIG.TXT" shell%@NL@%
     addto4:=arg "del TMP.TXT" shell setfile%@NL@%
     addto:=addto1 addto2 addto3 addto4%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63705@%%@4@%The %@AS@%addto%@AE@% macro appends the highlighted argument to the file BIG.TXT. If you%@EH@%
do not give an argument, the macro appends the current line. The %@AS@%addto%@AE@% macro
works by executing %@AS@%addto1%@AE@%, %@AS@%addto2%@AE@%, %@AS@%addto3%@AE@%, and %@AS@%addto4%@AE@%, each of which does
some of the work of adding to the highlighted area. The following list
describes the steps of the %@AS@%addto%@AE@% macro:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63706@%  1. Copy argument to the Clipboard, then load the <clipboard> pseudo file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Save the contents of the current file (which is now <clipboard>) to the%@NL@%
     file TMP.TXT.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Execute a DOS shell that appends TMP.TXT to BIG.TXT.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Execute a DOS shell that deletes TMP.TXT, then use %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% to return to%@NL@%
     the original file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63707@%%@4@%Another way to respond to an argument is to put the %@AI@%Replace%@AE@% function at the%@EH@%
beginning of your macro. Replacements then take place throughout the
highlighted area. For example, the following macro replaces each occurrence
of the period (.) with a blank space:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     blankout:=replace "." newline " " newline%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63708@%%@4@%The %@AI@%Newline%@AE@% function is necessary because the %@AI@%Replace%@AE@% function prompts for%@EH@%
search-and-replace strings.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63709@%%@4@%To use the macro above in a practical way, invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% twice to enable%@EH@%
regular expressions, highlight an area of text, and then execute %@AS@%blankout%@AE@%.
Assuming that the editor is using Unix regular-expression syntax, the effect
is that each character in the highlighted area is replaced by a blank space.
The effect is different from %@AI@%Delete%@AE@% because the space occupied by the text
is not removed, simply replaced with blanks.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%WARNING%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Using %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% twice and then executing %@AS@%blankout%@AE@% without a highlighted region%@NL@%
   replaces the rest of your file with blank spaces. Make sure you use a%@NL@%
   highlighted argument.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63800@%%@3@%%@AB@%6.3.8  Macros That Use Conditionals%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63801@%%@4@%You can write macros that execute different actions depending on certain%@EH@%
conditions. These macros take advantage of function return values. A "return
value" is simply a piece of information that a function passes back after it
is executed. Editing functions always return the value TRUE (nonzero) or
FALSE (zero).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63802@%%@4@%Each editing function has different criteria for determining what to return,%@EH@%
but usually an editing function returns TRUE if the function is successful,
or FALSE if it fails. For example, a cursor-movement function fails if the
cursor does not move.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63803@%%@4@%Table A.4%@BO:   701fe@%, in Appendix A, gives a complete list of function return values.%@EH@%
You use these return values with the syntax described in Table 6.1%@BO:   324a9@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6T100@%%@4@%%@AU@%Table 6.1  Macro Conditionals%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   15    844  1 18 68 @%%@AB@%Conditional       Description%@AE@%%@AB@%:>%@AE@%%@AI@%label%@AE@%           Defines a label that can be referenced by other macro                  conditionals.%@AB@%=>%@AE@%%@AI@%label%@AE@%           Causes a direct transfer to %@AI@%label%@AE@%. If %@AI@%label%@AE@% is omitted,                  then the current macro exits.%@AB@%->%@AE@%%@AI@%label%@AE@%           Causes a direct transfer to %@AI@%label%@AE@% if the previous function                  returns FALSE. If %@AI@%label%@AE@% is omitted, then the current macro                  exits on FALSE.%@AB@%+>%@AE@%%@AI@%label%@AE@%           Causes a direct transfer to %@AI@%label%@AE@% if the previous function                  returns TRUE. If %@AI@%label%@AE@% is omitted, then the current macro                  exits on TRUE.%@TE:   15    844  1 18 68 @%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63804@%%@4@%The table above refers to a macro exiting. In this context, exiting a macro%@EH@%
only affects the current macro. If macro %@AS@%doall%@AE@% executes macro %@AS@%submacro%@AE@%, when
%@AS@%submacro%@AE@% exits, control returns to %@AS@%doall%@AE@%, which continues execution.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63805@%%@4@%%@AB@%Examples%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63806@%%@4@%The first example turns insert mode on. The only function that turns insert%@EH@%
mode on or off is the %@AI@%Insertmode%@AE@% function. This function toggles between the
on and off condition, and returns the new state of insert mode:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%Initial state               Effect of Insertmode%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
Off                         Turn insert mode on; return TRUE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
On                          Turn insert mode off; return FALSE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63808@%%@4@%Unfortunately, testing the state of insert mode may turn insert mode off,%@EH@%
even though the goal is to leave it on. Fortunately, a conditional macro can
turn insert mode back on again as appropriate:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     turnon:=insertmode +> insertmode%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE63809@%%@4@%This macro consists of three simple steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6380A@%  1. %@AS@%insertmode%@AE@% toggles the state of insert mode. This function returns TRUE%@NL@%
     if insert mode is now on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. The %@AS@%+>%@AE@% operator exits the macro if the last function executed returned%@NL@%
     TRUE. In this case, a return value of TRUE indicates that insert mode%@NL@%
     is now on, so the macro exits on TRUE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. If the last function returned FALSE, the macro continues to the last%@NL@%
     step, which executes %@AS@%insertmode%@AE@% again. If the macro reaches this step,%@NL@%
     insert mode was initially on but the first step turned it off. This%@NL@%
     step turns insert mode back on again.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6380B@%%@4@%The macro defined above, %@AS@%turnon%@AE@%, is highly useful when used within nested%@EH@%
macros. Define %@AS@%turnon%@AE@% first. Then place %@AS@%turnon%@AE@% at the beginning of a macro
definition whenever the macro needs to assume that insert mode is on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   In the next chapter, you'll learn how to use the %@AI@%enterinsmode%@AE@% switch to%@NL@%
   achieve the same result as the macro defined above.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6380C@%%@4@%The next example turns insert mode on temporarily, executes the predefined%@EH@%
macro %@AS@%cmd%@AE@%, and then leaves the editor in the same state that it was in
before the macro was executed.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     icmd:=insertmode +>on insertmode cmd => :>on cmd insertmode%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6380D@%%@4@%The macro executes the commands in the following order:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE6380E@%  1. %@AS@%insertmode%@AE@% toggles the state of insert mode, so if insert mode was off,%@NL@%
     it is now on, and vice versa. This function returns TRUE if insert mode%@NL@%
     is on after the function is executed, and FALSE otherwise.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. %@AS@%+>on%@AE@% transfers control to the label %@AS@%on%@AE@% if the previous function%@NL@%
     returned TRUEÄÄin other words, if insert mode is now on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. %@AS@%insertmode%@AE@% turns insert on. If the macro reaches this point, insert%@NL@%
     mode was originally on but the first step turned it off and returned%@NL@%
     FALSE. This step turns insert mode back on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. %@AS@%cmd%@AE@% executes the predefined macro.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. %@AS@%=>%@AE@% exits the macro. Insert mode was on when the macro started, it is%@NL@%
     now back on, and %@AS@%cmd%@AE@% has been executed. Therefore the macro is done.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. %@AS@%:>on%@AE@% defines a label. Execution transfers here directly from the item%@NL@%
     %@AS@%+>on%@AE@% if insert mode was turned on.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  7. %@AS@%cmd%@AE@% executes the predefined macro.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  8. %@AS@%insertmode%@AE@% turns insert mode back off. Since execution flowed through%@NL@%
     to this point, insert mode must have been off when the macro%@NL@%
     beganÄÄinsert mode is turned back off now.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 7  Switches, Assignments, and the TOOLS.INI File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70001@%%@4@%A "switch" is a variable that controls some condition of the editor. For%@EH@%
example, changing the %@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@% switch alters the foreground color of the
editor, and changing the %@AB@%height%@AE@% switch alters the number of lines on the
screen. Although switches come in three varieties (numeric, text, and
Boolean), all three kinds of switches can be controlled with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%
function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70002@%%@4@%Usually, the most convenient way to work with switches is to set them in the%@EH@%
initialization file, named TOOLS.INI. This file contains switch values,
function assignments, and macros for the Microsoft Editor to automatically
assume at the beginning of each session. This file can be used to initialize
settings for other products. Therefore, all the settings for the editor have
to be put under a special heading called a "tag."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70003@%%@4@%If you are interested in using TOOLS.INI right away to make the editor%@EH@%
automatically start up with your own function assignments and macros, turn
to Section 7.4%@BO:   3b535@%, "Sample TOOLS.INI File."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70004@%%@4@%This chapter covers the following topics:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE70005@%  ş  Syntax for switch settings%@NL@%
  ş  Using switches to configure the editor%@NL@%
  ş  Special syntax for text switches%@NL@%
  ş  Sample TOOLS.INI file%@NL@%
  ş  The structure of the TOOLS.INI file%@NL@%
  ş  Configuring on-line Help%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.1  Syntax for Switch Settings%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71001@%%@4@%To change the behavior of the editor, set a switch with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function%@EH@%
or in the TOOLS.INI file. You set a switch differently depending on the type
of the switch. Each switch is one of three types: numeric, text, or Boolean.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71002@%%@4@%To set a numeric or text switch, give the assignment%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%switch%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@AI@%value%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71004@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%switch%@AE@% is the name of the switch and %@AI@%value%@AE@% is either a string of%@EH@%
digits (in the case of a numeric switch), or any string of text (in the case
of a text switch). Most numeric switches use decimal digits. However, the
color switches use hexadecimal digits, as described in Section 7.2.3%@BO:   35a6f@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71005@%%@4@%Boolean switches can be off or on. To turn a Boolean switch on, give either%@EH@%
of the following assignments:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%switch%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%switch%@AE@%%@AB@%:yes%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71007@%%@4@%To turn a Boolean switch off, prefix the letters %@AB@%no%@AE@% to the assignment or%@EH@%
type %@AB@%no%@AE@% after the colon:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%no%@AE@%%@AI@%switch%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%switch%@AE@%%@AB@%:no%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE71009@%%@4@%A switch assignment looks similar to a function assignment.  However, a%@EH@%
switch assignment has a different effect. A function assignment changes the
meaning of a keystroke, whereas a switch assignment alters a basic
condition, such as screen color.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7100A@%%@4@%%@AB@%Examples%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7100B@%%@4@%The following examples show a numeric, text, and four Boolean assignments,%@EH@%
respectively:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     tabstops:8%@NL@%
     backup:none%@NL@%
     case:%@NL@%
     nocase:%@NL@%
     case:yes%@NL@%
     case:no%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7100C@%%@4@%You could make any of these assignments by placing them in the TOOLS.INI%@EH@%
file, or by using the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@% command. For example, to set
%@AB@%tabstops%@AE@% to 8, follow these steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7100D@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%tabstops:8%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+= )%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Some text switches recognize special characters. These characters are%@NL@%
   never required, but can be convenient. See Section 7.3%@BO:   3a7a5@%, "Special Syntax%@NL@%
   for Text Switches," for more information.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.2  Using Switches to Configure the Editor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72001@%%@4@%This section explains how to use some of the more common switches. You can%@EH@%
follow the instructions to get a feel for how to adjust conditions within
the editor. For example, you may want to change screen colors, screen
height, or tab behavior. Sections 7.4%@BO:   3b535@% and 7.5%@BO:   3c086@% explain how to make these
settings automatic by placing them in the TOOLS.INI file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72002@%%@4@%Sections 7.2.1%@BO:   34f56@%-7.2.8 cover the following topics:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72003@%  ş  Changing start-up conditions%@NL@%
  ş  Changing scrolling behavior%@NL@%
  ş  Setting screen colors with %@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  Setting colors for other parts of the screen%@NL@%
  ş  Changing the look and feel of Help%@NL@%
  ş  Controlling use of tabs%@NL@%
  ş  Changing how the editor handles trailing spaces%@NL@%
  ş  Changing screen height%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72100@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.1  Changing Start-Up Conditions%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72101@%%@4@%By default, the editor starts with insert mode off and status line%@EH@%
displaying window position (rather than cursor position). To start with
insert mode on, place the following statement in the [M] section of your
TOOLS.INI file:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     enterinsmode:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72102@%%@4@%You can also set this switch by executing these steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72103@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%enterinsmode:%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72104@%%@4@%Setting this switch while in an editing session turns insert mode on%@EH@%
regardless of the current state of insert mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72105@%%@4@%The status line at the bottom of the screen displays window position by%@EH@%
default. The window position gives the file coordinates (by line and column)
of the top left corner. To change this field so that it displays cursor
position instead, follow these steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72106@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%displaycursor:%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72107@%%@4@%The editor numbers rows and columns beginning with the number one. Cursor%@EH@%
position is (1,1) when the cursor is at the very beginning of the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72108@%%@4@%The %@AB@%enterinsmode%@AE@% and %@AB@%displaycursor%@AE@% switches are both examples of Boolean%@EH@%
switches. To turn these switches off, follow the directions above but
precede the switch with the word %@AB@%no%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72200@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.2  Changing Scrolling Behavior%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72201@%%@4@%Two switches control scrolling behavior in the Microsoft Editor: %@AB@%vscroll%@AE@% and%@EH@%
%@AB@%hscroll%@AE@%. Each time you attempt to move the cursor off the top or bottom of
the screen, the editor moves the editing window up or down a certain
distance. This distance is set by the value of %@AB@%vscroll%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72202@%%@4@%For smooth vertical scrolling, set %@AB@%vscroll%@AE@% to 1:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72203@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%vscroll:1%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72204@%%@4@%For smooth horizontal scrolling, set %@AB@%hscroll%@AE@% to 1. Give the %@AI@%Arg textarg%@AE@%%@EH@%
%@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command (ALT+A %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% ALT+=), in which %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is %@AS@%hscroll:1%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72300@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.3  Setting Screen Colors with fgcolor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72301@%%@4@%The %@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@% switch controls the most important screen colors: background%@EH@%
and foreground colors of editing windows. The background color is the
primary color of a region of the screen. The foreground color is the color
of characters that appear in this region.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72302@%%@4@%The %@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@% switch uses one numeric value to control both background and%@EH@%
foreground colors. The other color switches (%@AB@%errcolor%@AE@%, %@AB@%hgcolor%@AE@%, %@AB@%infcolor%@AE@%,
and %@AB@%stacolor%@AE@%) all work in the same way: each sets a background and
foreground color according to a single numeric value.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72303@%%@4@%The editor reads a color switch as a two-digit hexadecimal number. The first%@EH@%
digit sets the background color; the second sets the foreground color. Table
7.1%@BO:   35f29@% states the digits that correspond to each color.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72304@%%@4@%In the case of background colors, the digits 8-F correspond to the digits%@EH@%
0-7, except that they make the foreground text blink on and off.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7T100@%%@4@%%@AU@%Table 7.1  Colors and Numeric Values%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   33    504  1 24 52 @%%@AB@%Color                   Value%@AE@%Black                   0Blue                    1Green                   2Cyan                    3Red                     4Magenta                 5Brown                   6Light Gray              7Dark Gray               8Light Blue              9Light Green             ALight Cyan              BLight Red               CLight Magenta           DLight Yellow            EWhite                   F%@TE:   33    504  1 24 52 @%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72305@%%@4@%Each two-digit number describes some combination of background and%@EH@%
foreground colors. The list below gives a few examples:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72306@%%@AB@%Number                      Meaning%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
17                          Blue (1) background, light gray (7) foreground%@NL@%
%@NL@%
07                          Black (0) background, light gray (7) foreground%@NL@%
%@NL@%
2F                          Green (2) background, white (F) foreground%@NL@%
%@NL@%
24                          Green (2) background, red (4) foreground%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Only color adapter cards support all the colors listed above. If you have%@NL@%
   a monochrome adapter or monochrome monitor, the only colors available are%@NL@%
   white (F), black (0), and light gray (7). All other colors are treated as%@NL@%
   white.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72307@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72308@%%@4@%At any time during the editing session, you can set new screen colors%@EH@%
(although to set these colors permanently, you should use TOOLS.INI). To set
a blue background with a light gray foreground, execute the following steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72309@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%fgcolor:17%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72400@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.4  Setting Colors for Other Parts of the Screen%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72401@%%@4@%All color switches interpret digits in the same way. However, each color%@EH@%
switch controls a different region of the screen, as described in the list
below:%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72402@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   26   1482  2 28 48 @%%@AB@%Switch                      Description%@AE@%%@AB@%errcolor%@AE@%                    Controls the colors used to display error                            messages on the dialog line.%@AB@%hgcolor%@AE@%                     Controls the colors in a region of text                            highlighted by a search command.%@AB@%infcolor%@AE@%                    Controls the colors used for informative text:                            messages (other than error messages) that the                            editor displays on the dialog line, as well as                            strings to be replaced that are located by                            %@AI@%Qreplace%@AE@%. The editor displays messages after                            executing an operation, such as saving a file or                            loading a new file. These colors provide the                            default background for the dialog line, and also                            control the color of "insert" and "meta" when                            they appear on the status line.%@AB@%selcolor%@AE@%                    Controls the color of text that the user                            highlights as a cursor-movement argument.%@AB@%stacolor%@AE@%                    Controls the colors of most items on the status                            line.%@AB@%wdcolor%@AE@%                     Controls the color used to draw window borders.%@TE:   26   1482  2 28 48 @%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72403@%%@4@%The following procedure sets a black (0) background for error messages,%@EH@%
combined with a red (4) foreground. Error messages will appear in red
letters against a black background:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72404@%  1. Invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%errcolor:04%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72500@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.5  Changing the Look and Feel of Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72501@%%@4@%The information in this section applies only to systems configured to use%@EH@%
the powerful Microsoft Help engine. If Help is not installed when you press
SHIFT+F1, a message appears saying that you have not installed Help yet. Run
the installation program for your Microsoft language, or follow the
directions in Section 7.6%@BO:   3eb8b@%, "Configuring On-Line Help."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72502@%%@4@%By default, Help splits the screen and displays Help information in a%@EH@%
separate window. This behavior has the advantage of letting you view both
the current file and Help information at the same time. You can move the
cursor between windows by pressing F6. You can also copy examples from the
Help window and paste them into an editing window.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72503@%%@4@%You can change the behavior of Help so that it does not split the screen.%@EH@%
Instead, Help will save the current file (if the %@AB@%autosave%@AE@% switch is on) and
load Help information into the current editing window. This behavior has the
advantage of using more room to display Help information.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72504@%%@4@%The split-screen behavior is controlled by the %@AB@%helpwindow%@AE@% switch. This%@EH@%
switch is a Boolean switch; it can be either on or off. Turning the switch
off prevents the editor from splitting the screen to display Help
information:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72505@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%nohelpwindow:%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72506@%%@4@%Conversely, to turn the split-screen behavior back on, give the %@AI@%Arg textarg%@AE@%%@EH@%
%@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command, in which %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is %@AS@%helpwindow:%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   When %@AI@%helpwindow%@AE@% is on, use the %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function (ESC) to close the Help%@NL@%
   window. When %@AI@%helpwindow%@AE@% is off, use the %@AI@%Cancel%@AE@% function (ESC) to return%@NL@%
   to the previous file.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72507@%%@4@%You can also control the colors used in the Help window. The writer of a%@EH@%
help file can designate text as foreground, bold, italicized, underlined, or
as warning text. You cannot change these designations. However, you can
easily change the choice of colors used to illustrate each kind of text:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72508@%%@AB@%Switch                      Meaning%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@%                     Foreground color, which controls the color of%@NL@%
                            normal text. This switch also controls the%@NL@%
                            foreground color of editing windows.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%helpboldcolor%@AE@%               Color of text designated as bold.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%helpitalcolor%@AE@%               Color of text designated as italicized.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%helpundcolor%@AE@%                Color of text designated as underlined.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%helpwarncolor%@AE@%               Color of text used for a "warning" note. Also%@NL@%
                            controls color of highlighted cross-references.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72509@%%@4@%All of the switches above are set the same way the %@AB@%fgcolor%@AE@% switch is, as%@EH@%
explained in Section 7.2.3.%@BO:   35a6f@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72600@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.6  Controlling Use of Tabs%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72601@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor provides two basic ways of working with tab characters:%@EH@%
you can either treat tabs as real characters, or you can have the editor
convert each tab into a series of spaces. This behavior is controlled by the
%@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% switch.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72602@%%@4@%The %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% switch is a Boolean switch that by default is on, causing the%@EH@%
editor to treat each tab (ASCII 9) as an independent character. Unlike other
characters, a tab may correspond to several positions on the screen. If you
place the cursor on a tab character and press RIGHT, the cursor jumps to the
next tab column. Tab columns occur at regular intervals, as determined by
the %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% switch.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72603@%%@4@%As you add and delete characters, the editor maintains the tab-column%@EH@%
alignment of the text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72604@%%@4@%Whether or not %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% is on, the %@AI@%Tab%@AE@% function is simply a movement%@EH@%
function, and it does not insert tabs into a file. To use the TAB key to
directly insert tabs, put the following assignment in your TOOLS.INI file,
or give it as input to the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     graphic:tab%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72605@%%@4@%This assignment makes the TAB key a graphic character. Each time you press%@EH@%
TAB, you directly place an actual tab character into the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72606@%%@4@%If you turn the %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% switch off, the Microsoft Editor translates tab%@EH@%
characters into spaces. This behavior only affects the individual lines that
you modify. If you read a file but make no changes, the tab-to-space
conversion does not alter the file on disk, even if you execute a save
operation.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72607@%%@4@%The editor may also convert spaces to tabs, according to the setting of the%@EH@%
%@AB@%entab%@AE@% switch, described below. This behavior also only affects the
individual lines that you modify.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72608@%%@4@%The %@AB@%tabdisp%@AE@% switch is useful for viewing the effect of writing to a disk%@EH@%
file. If you set %@AB@%tabdisp%@AE@% to a number other than 0 or 32, the editor shows
you which spaces will be compressed into a tab character at the next write
to the disk file. All such spaces are displayed as the ASCII equivalent of
the value of %@AB@%tabdisp%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72609@%%@4@%If %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% is on, each position in a tab field displays this same%@EH@%
character.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7260A@%%@4@%For example, the following steps set %@AB@%tabdisp%@AE@% to 249:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7260B@%  1. Invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% (press ALT+A)%@NL@%
  2. Type the following switch assignment: %@AS@%tabdisp:249%@AE@%%@NL@%
  3. Invoke the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% function (press ALT+=)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7260C@%%@4@%After you carry out these steps, the editor displays the ASCII equivalent of%@EH@%
249 in place of each position in a tab field.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7260D@%%@4@%The following list describes the meaning of the four tab-handling switches:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7260E@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   67   4383 02 28 48 @%%@AB@%Switch                      Description%@AE@%%@AB@%realtabs%@AE@%                    Controls whether or not tabs are treated as real                            characters, as described above. If on, tab                            columns are aligned according to the %@AB@%filetab%@AE@%                            switch. If %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% is off, every tab read is                            treated as a series of spaces, according to the                            %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% switch.%@AB@%entab%@AE@%                       Controls the extent to which the editor converts                            a series of tabs and spaces to tabs when saving                            a file. Only the lines you modify during the                            editing session are affected by space-to-tab                            conversion.                            A value of 0 means the editor does not replace                            spaces by tabs. A value of 1 (the default) means                            the editor can replace a series of tabs and                            spaces by tabs when the spaces fall outside of                            quoted strings. A value of 2 means all series of                            tabs and spaces can be replaced by tabs.                            The %@AB@%entab%@AE@% switch determines what kind of                            space-to-tab replacements are possible. Whether                            a replacement is made in any given case depends                            on the position of the spaces, and on the                            %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% switch, described next.%@AB@%filetab%@AE@%                     Controls the physical (disk-file) meaning of tab                            characters. If %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% is on, the %@AB@%filetab%@AE@%                            switch determines tab alignment. If%@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% is                            off, the %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% switch determines how the                            editor translates tab characters to spaces when                            a line of text is modified. If %@AB@%entab%@AE@% is set to 1                            or 2, %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% also determines how the editor                            translates spaces to tabs when you save the file                            to disk. (Only modified lines are affected.)                            The value of the switch gives the number of                            spaces associated with each tab column. For                            example, the setting "filetab:4" assumes a tab                            column every 4 positions on each line. Every                            time the editor finds a tab character (ASCII 9),                            it loads the buffer with the number of spaces                            necessary to get to the next tab column. The                            default value of %@AB@%filetab%@AE@% is 8.%@AB@%tabalign%@AE@%                    If %@AB@%realtabs%@AE@% and %@AB@%tabalign%@AE@% are both set, the                            cursor automatically moves to the first column                            position of a tab character when it is placed                            anywhere within a tab character. Cursor movement                            corresponds to the actual characters in the                            file.                            When not set (the default), the cursor may be                            placed anywhere in any column of a tab                            character. If a character is typed at this                            position, sufficient leading blanks will be                            inserted to assure that the character actually                            appears in this column position. Cursor movement                            is independent of the actual characters in the                            file.%@AB@%tabstops%@AE@%                    Determines the size of columns associated with                            the %@AI@%Tab%@AE@% and %@AI@%Backtab%@AE@% cursor-movement functions.                            It has no affect on actual tab characters. The                            default value of %@AB@%tabstops%@AE@% is 4.%@TE:   67   4383 02 28 48 @%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72700@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.7  Changing How the Editor Handles Trailing Spaces%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72701@%%@4@%A "trailing space" is a space character located to the right of the last%@EH@%
printable character on a line. A trailing space is normally invisible. By
default, the editor deletes all trailing spaces on each line you modify.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72702@%%@4@%However, you can change this behavior by resetting the value of the%@EH@%
%@AB@%trailspace%@AE@% switch. This switch is Boolean switch; it can be either on or
off. To turn this switch on, give the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@% command (ALT+A
%@AI@%textarg%@AE@% ALT+=), in which %@AS@%trailspace:%@AE@% is the %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%. When you wish to turn
this switch off, give the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@% command, in which %@AS@%notrailspace:%@AE@%
is the %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72703@%%@4@%When this switch is on, any space you type at the end of a line remains in%@EH@%
the file as a trailing space. You can verify the existence of trailing
spaces by invoking the %@AI@%Endline%@AE@% function (press END). If the cursor moves
past the last printable character when you invoke %@AI@%Endline%@AE@%, the line contains
trailing spaces.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72704@%%@4@%To display trailing spaces, set the %@AB@%traildisp%@AE@% switch to a number greater%@EH@%
than 0. The editor displays the ASCII-character equivalent of the number you
choose, in place of each trailing space. For example, invoke the %@AI@%Arg textarg%@AE@%
%@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command in which %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is %@AS@%traildisp:1%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72705@%%@4@%The example above displays the ASCII equivalent of the number 1 in place of%@EH@%
each trailing space. To restore normal display, set %@AB@%traildisp%@AE@% back to 0.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72800@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.2.8  Changing Screen Height%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72801@%%@4@%Change the screen height by setting the %@AB@%height%@AE@% switch. This switch takes%@EH@%
only a few values that are limited by the kind of graphics adapter card you
are using:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72802@%%@AB@%Graphics Card               Legal Values%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
CGA or monochrome           23  (25-line mode)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
EGA                         23  (25-line mode) 41  (43-line mode)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
VGA                         23  (25-line mode) 41  (43-line mode) 48%@NL@%
                            (50-line mode)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE72803@%%@4@%Note that you assign to %@AB@%height%@AE@% a number two less than the desired mode. That%@EH@%
is because %@AB@%height%@AE@% refers to the height of the editing window, not the full
screen. (Two lines at the bottom of the screen are reserved for dialog and
status.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.3  Special Syntax for Text Switches%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73001@%%@4@%The following text switches recognize special characters for referring to%@EH@%
file names or directories:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73002@%  ş  %@AB@%extmake%@AE@%, which can be repeatedly assigned to different compilation%@NL@%
     commands%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%readonly%@AE@%, which gives a system-level command, executed whenever you%@NL@%
     attempt to overwrite a read-only file%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%load%@AE@%, which loads a C extension as described in Chapter 8%@BO:   3fbeb@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%markfile%@AE@%, which loads file markers from a specially prepared file%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@%, which specifies which .HLP files should be used by on-line%@NL@%
     Help%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73003@%%@4@%This syntax presented in the next two sections is never required, but is%@EH@%
provided for convenience.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73100@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.3.1  Special Syntax for extmake and readonly%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73101@%%@4@%The text switches %@AB@%extmake%@AE@% and %@AB@%readonly%@AE@% each interpret the following%@EH@%
characters as the name of the current file:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%%s%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73103@%%@4@%You can also use a more comprehensive syntax that lets you specify drive,%@EH@%
file name, base name, or file extension. The syntax consists of the
characters%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%%|%@AE@%%@AI@%letters%@AE@%%@AB@%F%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73105@%%@4@%where %@AI@%letters%@AE@% consists of any of the following: p for path, d for drive, f%@EH@%
for file base name, or e for file extension. For example, if you are editing
the file c:\dir1\sample.c, and you make the switch assignment%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     extmake:c cl /Fod:%|pfF %|dfeF%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73106@%%@4@%then each time you give the command %@AI@%Arg Compilation%@AE@%, the editor performs the%@EH@%
following system-level command:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     cl /Fod:\dir1\sample c:sample.c%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73107@%%@4@%The expression %@AS@%%s%@AE@% is equivalent to %@AS@%%|feF%@AE@% except that the former is only%@EH@%
accepted once in each assignment, whereas the latter can appear any number
of times in the %@AB@%extmake%@AE@% switch assignment. The expression %@AS@%%|F%@AE@% is equivalent
to %@AS@%%|dpfeF%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73200@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.3.2  Special Syntax for load, markfile, and helpfiles%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73201@%%@4@%The %@AB@%load%@AE@%, %@AB@%markfile%@AE@%, and %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switches each search for a file. These%@EH@%
switches can also take the syntax%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%$%@AE@%%@AI@%environ%@AE@%%@AB@%:%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73203@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%environ%@AE@% is the name of an environment variable recognized by the%@EH@%
operating system. The editor will search directories listed in the
environment variable to find the file. Environment variables are created
with the system-level SET command. See your operating-system documentation
for more information on the SET command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73204@%%@4@%For example, the following assignment causes the editor to search%@EH@%
directories in the INIT environment variable for the file MARKERS.DAT:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     markfile:$INIT:markers.dat%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE73205@%%@4@%Note that the environment variable should be entered in uppercase letters.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE74000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.4  Sample TOOLS.INI File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE74001@%%@4@%Each time you start the editor, it checks the [M] section of the TOOLS.INI%@EH@%
file for any function assignments, switch assignments, and macro definitions
you have placed there. (However, the editor may check a different section if
the editor is not named M.EXE.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE74002@%%@4@%You can change these settings at any time during the editing session by%@EH@%
using the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command. However, using TOOLS.INI is more convenient for
settings you want to use every time. Use TOOLS.INI to make the editor
automatically start up with all the screen colors, tab behavior, function
assignments, and special editing functions you want to make available for
all editing sessions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE74003@%%@4@%The editor loads settings from TOOLS.INI when it starts and when you invoke%@EH@%
the %@AI@%Initialize%@AE@% function (SHIFT+F8) during the editing session. By giving a
text argument, you can also use %@AI@%Initialize%@AE@% to load specific sections within
TOOLS.INI.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   The editor checks the directories listed in the INIT environment variable%@NL@%
   for the location of the TOOLS.INI file. For example, if the TOOLS.INI%@NL@%
   file is in the directory %@AI@%C:\BIN%@AE@%, place the following statement in your%@NL@%
   AUTOEXEC.BAT file: %@AS@%SET INIT=C:\BIN.%@AE@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE74004@%%@4@%The example below shows a sample TOOLS.INI file. The next section explains%@EH@%
each section of this file in depth. Note that text following the semicolon
(;) is a comment.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M MEP]                       %@AI@%; Settings for both M and MEP%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             enterinsmode:         %@AI@%; Start up in insert mode%@AE@%%@NL@%
             backup:none           %@AI@%; Perform no backup%@AE@%%@NL@%
             displaycursor:        %@AI@%; Display cursor on status line%@AE@%%@NL@%
             fgcolor:17            %@AI@%; Set primary and error colors%@AE@%%@NL@%
             errcolor:04%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             join:=savecur endline right arg sdelete savecur   %@AI@%; Macro%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             savecur:ctrl+f5       %@AI@%; Assignments to keys%@AE@%%@NL@%
             restcur:ctrl+f6%@NL@%
             join:alt+j%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-C MEP-C]                   %@AI@%; C specific section - enable with Initialize%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             tabstops:3            %@AI@%; Tab columns 3 wide within editor%@AE@%%@NL@%
             case:                 %@AI@%; Case-sensitive searches%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [NMAKE]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     #  This is a comment line recognized by NMAKE%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.5  The Structure of the TOOLS.INI File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75001@%%@4@%To create a TOOLS.INI file for the editor, you need to follow a few simple%@EH@%
rules:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75002@%  1. You must precede your editor settings by a tag, or they will not be%@NL@%
     recognized. A "tag" is a heading within the TOOLS.INI file that divides%@NL@%
     the file into sections.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     For example, you can use tags to create a section for the editor ([M]%@NL@%
     or [MEP], unless you have renamed the editor) and a section for another%@NL@%
     utility such as NMAKE, which looks for a section headed by the [NMAKE]%@NL@%
     tag. Each utility has its own syntax for interpreting TOOLS.INI%@NL@%
     statements, but all utilities must recognize tags. See the %@AI@%Microsoft%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%CodeView and Utilities User's Guide%@AE@% for more information on NMAKE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. A semicolon (%@AB@%;%@AE@%) indicates that all text from the semicolon to the end%@NL@%
     of the line is a comment, and is ignored by the editor. To mark the%@NL@%
     beginning of a comment, a semicolon must either appear at the beginning%@NL@%
     of a line or be preceded by a space.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. All macro definitions, function assignments, and switch assignments use%@NL@%
     exactly the same syntax used with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     However, you do not invoke %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% or %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%; simply enter the assignment%@NL@%
     itself. (See the sample TOOLS.INI file for clarification.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. You can use the backslash (%@AB@%\%@AE@%) as a line-continuation character to%@NL@%
     continue  statements too long for one line. The backslash must be%@NL@%
     preceded by a space and can be followed only by trailing spaces and an%@NL@%
     optional comment. Normally, you should precede the backslash by two%@NL@%
     spaces.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75003@%%@4@%The next few sections explain each part of the fileÄÄtags, comments, and%@EH@%
assignments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75100@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.5.1  Creating Sections with Tags%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75101@%%@4@%Tags divide the TOOLS.INI file into sections.  All statements are associated%@EH@%
only with the tag they immediately follow. This feature allows programs
other than the Microsoft Editor to use this file for configuration
information. The most common way to use a tag is to simply include all
assignments and macro definitions after an M or MEP tag (depending on the
name of the editor):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75103@%%@4@%When you run the Microsoft Editor under DOS 2.%@AI@%x%@AE@%, the editor always responds%@EH@%
to the tag [M]. Otherwise, the tag should use the base file name of the
editor. If the editor is named MEP.EXE, use the tag [MEP]. Use [M MEP] if
you have both M.EXE and MEP.EXE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%IMPORTANT%@AE@%%@NL@%
   The name you use for the main editor tag should appear in all other%@NL@%
   editor tags as well. For example, if the main editor tag is [EDIT]%@NL@%
   (because you renamed the editor to EDIT.EXE), all editor tags should%@NL@%
   begin with the word EDIT. Instead of using [M-3.20], you would use%@NL@%
   [EDIT-3.20].%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75104@%%@4@%When the Microsoft Editor is started, the tagged sections are loaded in the%@EH@%
following order:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75105@%  1. Information used for all editing sessions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     All of the statements in the [M] section are loaded. Remember to use a%@NL@%
     different tag if you rename the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Information specific to the operating system.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Depending upon the operating system you are running, one of the%@NL@%
     following tagged sections is loaded (if present):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
       ş  [M-3.20] (MS-DOS)%@NL@%
       ş  [M-10.0] (OS/2 protected mode)%@NL@%
       ş  [M-10.0R] (OS/2 real mode)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     With the DOS or OS/2 version tag, you should insert the version number%@NL@%
     you are using. (OS/2 1.10 uses the tag 10.10.) You can combine%@NL@%
     operating-system tags by grouping them together within the brackets:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
          [M-3.20 M-3.30]                      %@AI@%; For DOS versions%@AE@%%@NL@%
          [MEP-10.0 MEP-10.10]                 %@AI@%; For OS/2 versions%@AE@%%@NL@%
          [M-3.20 M-3.30 M-10.0R M-10.10R]     %@AI@%; For real mode%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Information specific to the display.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Depending on the video display you are using, one of the following%@NL@%
     tagged sections is loaded (if present):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
       ş  [M-mono]%@NL@%
       ş  [M-cga]%@NL@%
       ş  [M-ega]%@NL@%
       ş  [M-vga]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     You can also put statements for setting the screen dimensions and%@NL@%
     colors in these tagged sections.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     All tags can be combined so one section of statements applies to more%@NL@%
     than one tag:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
        %@AS@%[M-mono M-cga MEP-mono MEP-cga]%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The example above begins a section that is loaded if your computer has%@NL@%
     either a monochrome adapter or a CGA adapter.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75106@%%@4@%You can also create a tag with statements specific to a file extension. The%@EH@%
form is%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-%@AI@%.ext%@AE@%]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75107@%%@4@%where .%@AI@%ext%@AE@% is an extension of up to three characters. Whenever you load a%@EH@%
new file, or switch to editing a different file, the editor automatically
searches TOOLS.INI for a tag that matches the new file extension. If it
finds a matching tag, the statements following that tag are executed. If
not, the existing configuration is retained.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75108@%%@4@%This feature can be used to create operating environments that are specific%@EH@%
to a particular type of text file or programming language. For example, the
tag %@AS@%[M-.FOR]%@AE@% could precede a set of statements for editing .FOR (FORTRAN)
files:  a blue background, the right margin at column 72, and tabs set every
three columns. C-language files with the .C extension could have their own
set of statements following a %@AS@%[M-.C]%@AE@% tag: a magenta background, the right
margin at column 128, and tabs set every five columns.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7510A@%%@4@%You can also use a tag to create a special section that is loaded manually%@EH@%
with the %@AI@%Arg textarg Initialize%@AE@% command. These tags use the following
syntax:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-%@AI@%textarg%@AE@%]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE7510C@%%@4@%This feature lets you make special key assignments, load rarely used macros,%@EH@%
or switch the operating environment to a special configuration, only when
required.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75200@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.5.2  Using Comments%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75201@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor considers text from a semicolon (;) to the end of a%@EH@%
line to be a comment. Comments are for documentation purposes only and are
ignored by the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75202@%%@4@%To be considered part of a comment, the semicolon must either appear at the%@EH@%
beginning of a line or else be preceded by a space. Thus, in the following
line, the first semicolon is considered part of a command, and the second
begins a comment:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     extmake:asm masm /Zi /MX %s; %@AI@%; "Compile" setting for MASM%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75203@%%@4@%Semicolons inside a quoted string do not begin a comment.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75300@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.5.3  Line Continuation%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75301@%%@4@%Use the backslash (%@AB@%\%@AE@%) to continue a long macro definition to the next line.%@EH@%
To be interpreted as the line-continuation character, the backslash must be
preceded by a space. It should be the last character on the line except for
spaces and comments. The editor does not interpret the backslash as the
line-continuation char-acter in the following statement:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     qreplace:ctrl+\%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75302@%%@4@%The following statement illustrates valid use of line continuation:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     findswitch:=psearch ->skip arg mark :>skip arg "<assign>"  \%@NL@%
                 setfile begfile psearch%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75303@%%@4@%Note that the backslash should be followed by at least two spaces, unless%@EH@%
you want the end of one line to be concatenated without a break to the
beginning of the next. In the example above, two spaces are necessary to
prevent the editor from viewing %@AS@%"<assign>"setfile%@AE@% as one item.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75304@%%@4@%You can use line continuation to extend a single assignment statement over%@EH@%
several lines.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75400@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.5.4  Assignments and Macros%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75401@%%@4@%Function assignments, switch assignments, and macro definitions all use the%@EH@%
same syntax within the TOOLS.INI file as they do with the %@AI@%Arg textarg Assign%@AE@%
command. The only difference is you do not need to invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% or %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%
functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75402@%%@4@%The TOOLS.INI file is convenient for defining complicated macros, especially%@EH@%
nested macros. By placing macro definitions in the TOOLS.INI file, you can
view how you wrote a macro. Furthermore, you can easily modify a macro that
doesn't work correctly by loading the TOOLS.INI file, making changes to your
macro definitions, and reinitializing.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75403@%%@4@%If you customized your copy of the Microsoft Editor when you installed it, a%@EH@%
special TOOLS.INI was created that contains the special key assignments.
This TOOLS.INI file also contains a number of useful macros from the
TOOLS.PRE file. You may want to study TOOLS.PRE to see how macros are
entered and which macros might be useful to you.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75404@%%@4@%Use the %@AI@%Initialize%@AE@% function (SHIFT+F8) to reload your TOOLS.INI settings.%@EH@%
When you give the %@AI@%Initialize%@AE@% function a %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%, it attempts to use settings
from the following section:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-%@AI@%textarg%@AE@%]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75406@%%@4@%However, when you invoke %@AI@%Initialize%@AE@% with no argument, the editor reloads%@EH@%
settings in the TOOLS.INI file in the same way that it does on start-up.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE75407@%%@4@%You can create a macro to be executed whenever the editor starts up. Simply%@EH@%
define a macro and assign it the name %@AS@%autostart%@AE@%. For example, when you place
the following macro in the [M] section of the TOOLS.INI file, the editor
transfers to the Clipboard and returns, thus making the Clipboard the
previous file:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     autostart:=arg "<clipboard>" setfile setfile%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76000@%%@2@%%@AB@%7.6  Configuring On-Line Help%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76001@%%@4@%The installation program for your Microsoft language is the recommended%@EH@%
method for configuring on-line Help. The procedure varies, depending on
whether you use OS/2 (supporting protected mode and real mode) or DOS (real
mode only).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76002@%  1. If you are running under DOS or real-mode OS/2 only, copy the M.HLP and%@NL@%
     MHELP.MXT files to any directory specified in the PATH environment%@NL@%
     variable in your AUTOEXEC.BAT file (DOS) or STARTUP.CMD file (OS/2).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. If you are running under protected-mode OS/2 only, copy the M.HLP and%@NL@%
     MHELP.PXT files to any directory specified in the PATH environment%@NL@%
     variable. Also copy MSHELP.DLL to any directory listed in the LIBPATH%@NL@%
     variable in the CONFIG.SYS file. MHELP.DLL is an extension to the%@NL@%
     editor. MSHELP.DLL is a support library that implements the standard%@NL@%
     Microsoft Help engine.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. If you are setting up for both real- and protected-mode OS/2, perform%@NL@%
     both the preceding steps.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76003@%%@4@%Other Microsoft products include .HLP files that the Microsoft Editor can%@EH@%
read. If you want to add additional .HLP files to Help, you need to include
the following tagged section in your TOOLS.INI file:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-MHELP.MXT MEP-MHELP.MXT]%@NL@%
     helpfiles:%@AI@%path%@AE@%\%@AI@%file.hlp%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76004@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%path%@AE@% is the directory of the Help file. The tag [M-MHELP.MXT%@EH@%
MEP-MHELP.MXT] is the heading for the section in the TOOLS.INI file executed
whenever Help is loaded. If this section is missing, the editor looks for
the file M.HLP in your PATH directories. To install more than one Help file,
you must have this tagged section in TOOLS.INI.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76005@%%@4@%Whenever you use context-sensitive Help, the editor searches the files%@EH@%
specified in the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switch in the order listed. The search is slower
if the topics you most often inquire about are in files at the end of the
list. You can alter the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switch at any time with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%
command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76100@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.6.1  Controlling Search Order%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76101@%%@4@%Context-sensitive Help searches all the Help files for the selected topic.%@EH@%
The order in which files are searched is important. Two different Help files
may have an entry for the same topic. Furthermore, searching the appropriate
file first speeds up Help.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76102@%%@4@%You can use the file extension of the current file to change the order in%@EH@%
which .HLP files are searched. Precede files specified in the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@%
switch by a file extension and a colon (:):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     helpfiles: M.HLP .BAS:QB.HLP .C.H:C.HLP .ASM:OS2.HLP%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76103@%%@4@%In the example above, Help searches QB.HLP first when the current file has a%@EH@%
.BAS extension, C.HLP when the current file has a .C or .H extension, and
OS2.HLP when the current file has a .ASM extension. In all cases, all of the
files listed are searched before Help concludes it cannot find a topic.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76200@%%@3@%%@AB@%7.6.2  Default Help File Search%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76201@%%@4@%The editor looks for .HLP files according to the following rules:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE76202@%  1. If the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switch is set, the editor uses the files specified in%@NL@%
     this switch.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. If %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% is not set, the editor checks next to see if the HELPFILES%@NL@%
     environment variable is set. If it is, this environment variable is%@NL@%
     evaluated the same way the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switch is.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. If neither the %@AB@%helpfiles%@AE@% switch nor the HELPFILES environment variable%@NL@%
     is set, the editor searches for the file M.HLP. The editor finds M.HLP%@NL@%
     if this file is in a directory listed in the PATH environment variable.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE80000@%%@1@%%@AB@%Chapter 8  Programming C Extensions%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE80001@%%@4@%C extensions provide the most powerful means of customizing the Microsoft%@EH@%
Editor. A "C extension" is a C-language module containing new editing
functions you program. Your functions can be attached to a key, given
arguments, or used in macros just as standard editing functions are. The
module can also define new switches. The user can adjust these switches to
modify the behavior of your functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE80002@%%@4@%With C extensions, you can use the power of the C languageÄÄdata structures,%@EH@%
control-flow structures, and C operators. Furthermore, C extensions are much
faster than macros because they are compiled.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   This chapter assumes you already know how to program in C. Before you%@NL@%
   read the chapter, make sure you understand the following C-language%@NL@%
   programming concepts: functions, pointers, structures, and unions. You%@NL@%
   also need to know how to compile and link a C source file.%@NL@%
   You can also write extensions with the Microsoft Macro Assembler if you%@NL@%
   simulate the C memory model specified in Section 8.5.1%@BO:   4ab20@%, "Compiling and%@NL@%
   Linking in Real Mode." However, this chapter is primarily addressed to C%@NL@%
   programmers.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE80003@%%@4@%This chapter gradually develops concepts for writing C extensions. The first%@EH@%
time you read the chapter, read the sections in order. The chapter first
describes requirements for writing C extensions and explains how C
extensions work. It then explains how to create the required objects in a C
extension, to program your editing functions, to compile and link your
module, and to use the editor's low-level functions to read and write to
files.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE81000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.1  Requirements%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE81001@%%@4@%To create C extensions, you need to have the following files and software%@EH@%
present in your current directory (or directories listed in the PATH or
INCLUDE environment variables, as appropriate):%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE81002@%  ş  The Microsoft C Optimizing Compiler, Version 5.1 or later. You can use%@NL@%
     Version 4.0 or 5.0 of the compiler, but the files you need are provided%@NL@%
     with Version 5.1 and later. You also get these files with the Microsoft%@NL@%
     Macro Assembler, Version 5.1 and later.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  The Microsoft Overlay Linker, Version 3.60 or later; the OS/2 version%@NL@%
     of the linker; or the Microsoft Segmented-Executable Linker, Version%@NL@%
     5.01.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  EXTHDR.OBJ (supplied with the C compiler) or EXTHDRP.OBJ (a file%@NL@%
     supplied with the C compiler for creating protected-mode extensions).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  EXT.H (supplied with the C compiler).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  SKEL.C (a template supplied with the C compiler you can replace with%@NL@%
     your own code).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE81003@%%@4@%You need a minimum of 220K of available memory for the editor to load a C%@EH@%
extension at run time, plus the size of the extension itself.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.2  How C Extensions Work%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82001@%%@4@%A C-extension module is similar in the following respects to an OS/2 or%@EH@%
Windows dynamic-link library:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82002@%  ş  There is no function called %@AB@%main%@AE@% in your module. Instead, you use%@NL@%
     certain names and structures the editor recognizes.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  You compile and link to create an executable file, but this executable%@NL@%
     file is separate from the "main program," M.EXE or MEP.EXE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  ş  The editor loads your executable file into memory at run time and uses%@NL@%
     a table-driven method for enabling your module to call functions within%@NL@%
     the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82003@%%@4@%Once your executable file is loaded, it resides in memory along with the%@EH@%
editor. The editor can call your functions, and your functions can call the
Microsoft Editor's low-level functions that perform input and output
operations.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82004@%%@4@%The following list summarizes the process of developing and using a C%@EH@%
extension:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE82005@%  1. Compile a C module with a special memory-model option, then link the%@NL@%
     resulting object file to create an executable file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     You also link in the object file EXTHDR.OBJ  (or EXTHDRP.OBJ, if%@NL@%
     linking for protected mode) to the beginning of your executable file.%@NL@%
     This object file contains a special table that enables your functions%@NL@%
     to effectively call functions within the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Start up the Microsoft Editor. Set the %@AB@%load%@AE@% switch  to look for the%@NL@%
     executable file you created. (As discussed in Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%, the %@AB@%load%@AE@%%@NL@%
     switch can be set in the TOOLS.INI file or manually with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@%%@NL@%
     function.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The editor loads your executable file into memory.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. As soon as the executable file is loaded, the Microsoft Editor calls%@NL@%
     the function %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@%ÄÄa special function your module must define.%@NL@%
     At the same time, the editor examines the table %@AB@%cmdTable%@AE@%, which is an%@NL@%
     array of structures your module must declare. The editor examines this%@NL@%
     table to recognize the editing functions you created. The table%@NL@%
     contains function names and pointers to functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. You can assign keys to call your functions. Assign a key manually or in%@NL@%
     the %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@% function, then press the assigned key. You can also call%@NL@%
     an editing function indirectly by placing it in a macro and calling the%@NL@%
     macro.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  5. When you invoke a C-extension function, the editor responds by calling%@NL@%
     your module.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  6. Your editing function is executed. It calls the Microsoft Editor's%@NL@%
     low-level functions to read from the text file, read output to the text%@NL@%
     file, and print messages.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.3  Writing a C Extension%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83001@%%@4@%To create a successful C extension, you need to follow these guidelines:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83002@%  1. Include the file EXT.H.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     This file declares all structures and types required to establish an%@NL@%
     interface to the editor.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Include the standard items that are described in Section 8.3.1%@BO:   41aca@%,%@NL@%
     "Required Objects," and write your functions by following the steps in%@NL@%
     Section 8.4%@BO:   45aeb@%, "Programming Your Function." Then compile and link as%@NL@%
     directed in Section 8.5%@BO:   4a7bb@%, "Compiling and Linking."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Call the low-level extension functions to do most any operation with%@NL@%
     files, such as read from a file, write to a file, delete or add files,%@NL@%
     and move the cursor. These functions are completely described in%@NL@%
     Chapter 9%@BO:   50fea@%, "C-Extension Functions," (an alphabetical reference), and%@NL@%
     summarized by topic at the end of this chapter.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Do not call functions from the C library routine, except for the ones%@NL@%
     specifically listed in Section 8.7%@BO:   4fa83@%, "Calling Library Functions."%@NL@%
     Futhermore, floating-point arithmetic is not supported.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83100@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.3.1  Required Objects%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83101@%%@4@%A C-extension module must have at minimum the three objects described below:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83102@%%@AB@%Object Name                 Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%swiTable%@AE@%                    An array of structures that declares internal%@NL@%
                            switches you wish to create%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%cmdTable%@AE@%                    An array of structures that declares editing%@NL@%
                            functions you have coded%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@%                  A function that the editor calls as soon as the%@NL@%
                            C-extension module is loaded%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83103@%%@4@%Each of these items can be as short or long as you wish. Each table can be%@EH@%
as short as a single row of entries. The %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@% function can return
immediately, or it can perform useful initialization tasks, such as
assigning keys to functions or printing a message.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83200@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.3.2  The Switch Table%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83201@%%@4@%The switch table, %@AB@%swiTable%@AE@%, consists of a series of structures in which each%@EH@%
structure describes a switch you wish to create. The table ends with a
structure that has all null (all zero) values. Though you may choose not to
create any switches, the table must still be present. The simplest table
allowed is therefore%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct swiDesc swiTable[] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          { (void *) 0, (void *) 0, 0 }%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83202@%%@4@%The structure type %@AB@%swiDesc%@AE@% is defined in EXT.H. This structure contains the%@EH@%
following three fields that define a switch for the editor to recognize:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83203@%  1. A pointer to the name of the switch.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. A pointer to the switch itself or to a function. If the switch is%@NL@%
     Boolean, this field must point to the switch (an integer which assumes%@NL@%
     the value -1 or 0). If the switch is text, this field must point to a%@NL@%
     function, as explained below. If the switch is numeric, this field%@NL@%
     points to switch itselfÄÄan integer.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. A flag that indicates the type of switch: either %@AB@%SWI_BOOLEAN%@AE@%,%@NL@%
     %@AB@%SWI_NUMERIC%@AE@%, or %@AB@%SWI_SPECIAL%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83204@%%@4@%If the third field has value %@AB@%SWI_NUMERIC%@AE@%, you must combine it with the value%@EH@%
%@AB@%RADIX10%@AE@% or %@AB@%RADIX16%@AE@% by using binary or (%@AB@%|%@AE@%). (See the second example below.)
If you specify %@AB@%RADIX10%@AE@%, the editor interprets user-assigned values as
decimal digits. If you specify %@AB@%RADIX16%@AE@%, the editor interprets these values
as hexadecimal.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83205@%%@4@%If the third field has value %@AB@%SWI_SPECIAL%@AE@%, the second field must be a pointer%@EH@%
to a function of type %@AB@%int far pascal%@AE@%. You define this function in your code.
Each time the value of the switch changes, the editor calls your function
and passes the updated value in a character string. Your function should
declare exactly one parameter: a far pointer to a character string.
Typically, this function might set a global variable:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     char globalstr[BUFLEN];%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     int far pascal setstr (char far *p)%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          strcpy (globalstr, p);%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83206@%%@4@%The table may have any number of rows (each row being a structure), and must%@EH@%
at least include the final row of all null values. Here is an example of a
table that creates a numeric switch with a default value of 27:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     int n = 27;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct swiDesc swiTable [] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          { "newswitch", &n, SWI_NUMERIC|RADIX10  } ,%@NL@%
          { (void *) 0, (void *) 0, 0 }%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83300@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.3.3  The Command Table%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83301@%%@4@%The command table, %@AB@%cmdTable%@AE@%, is similar to the switch table, %@AB@%swiTable%@AE@%, in%@EH@%
its construction. Each "row" of the table consists of a structure that
describes an editing function you want the editor to recognize. The last row
must contain all null values. The simplest table allowed is the following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct cmdDesc cmdTable[] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          { (void *) 0, (void *) 0, 0, 0 }%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83302@%%@4@%Usually you'll want to declare at least one new editing function. The%@EH@%
structure type %@AB@%cmdDesc%@AE@% is defined in EXT.H. This structure contains the
following four fields that make an editing function recognizable to the
editor:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83303@%  1. A pointer to the name of the function, in ASCII format. This name could%@NL@%
     appear in assignments and macros.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. The address of the function itself. Give the function name but do not%@NL@%
     follow it with parentheses.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. A field used internally by the editor. Always declare this field as%@NL@%
     null.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Flags indicating the type of the function. Function types are described%@NL@%
     below and define what type of argument the function will accept.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83304@%%@4@%Here is an example of a command table declaring a function that takes no%@EH@%
arguments and a second function that takes either a %@AI@%linearg%@AE@% or a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% or
can be entered without arguments:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct cmdDesc cmdTable[] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          { "newfun", newfun, 0, NOARG } ,%@NL@%
          { "fun2",  fun2,     0, LINEARG | BOXARG | NOARG } ,%@NL@%
          { (void *) 0, (void *) 0, 0, 0 }%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83305@%%@4@%In the fourth field of the command table, use one or more of the values%@EH@%
described in Table 8.1%@BO:   435cc@% below.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83306@%%@4@%The first column of Table 8.1%@BO:   435cc@% contains a flag you can enter in the fourth%@EH@%
field of %@AB@%cmdTable%@AE@%. The second column describes the associated behavior. The
third column indicates which of the six data formats the editor uses to pass
information. Your function determines the format at run time by testing the
value of pArg->argType. Sections 8.4.3%@BO:   470c5@%-8.4.8 give complete descriptions of
these formats.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83307@%%@4@%Many of the descriptions below state that the editor responds by passing%@EH@%
certain information. However, these responses only apply when the editor
detects the associated condition. For example, the %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@% flag controls the
editor's behavior only when a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% is detected. However, %@AB@%KEEPMETA%@AE@%,
%@AB@%MODIFIES%@AE@%, and %@AB@%CURSORFUNC%@AE@% apply regardless of argument type.%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8T100@%%@NL@%
%@4@%%@AU@%Table 8.1  Meaning of cmdTable Flags%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@TH:   68   3808  3 14 51 11 @%%@AB@%cmdTable                                                         argType%@AE@%%@AB@%Flag          Behavior                                           Format%@AE@%%@AB@%KEEPMETA%@AE@%      Preserves the state of the %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% prefix, which is   Not              normally reset upon completion of the function.    applicable%@AB@%MODIFIES%@AE@%      Prevents execution of the function when the        Not              current file is No-Edit.                           applicable%@AB@%WINDOWFUNC%@AE@%    Does not cancel highlight resulting from a         Not              previous command, such as %@AI@%Psearch%@AE@%. This flag is    applicable              useful for window-movement functions.%@AB@%CURSORFUNC%@AE@%    Does not recognize or cancel %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix. The       %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%              function is useful for helping define              cursor-movement arguments, since it preserves the              preexisting argument. Conflicts with all flags              except %@AB@%KEEPMETA%@AE@% and %@AB@%MODIFIES%@AE@%.%@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%         Accepts absence of the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix. The editor      %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%              passes location of the cursor.%@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%       Accepts %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% without an argument. The editor        %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%              passes location of the cursor. Conflicts with              %@AB@%NULLEOL%@AE@% and %@AB@%NULLEOW%@AE@%.%@AB@%NULLEOL%@AE@%       Accepts %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% without an argument. The editor        %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%              passes the string of text from the cursor              position up to the end of the line. Conflicts              with %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@% and %@AB@%NULLEOW%@AE@%.%@AB@%NULLEOW%@AE@%       Accepts %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% without an argument. The editor        %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%              passes the string of text from the cursor              position up to the next white space. Conflicts              with %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@% and %@AB@%NULLEOL%@AE@%.%@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%       Accepts a text argument that the user types in     %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%              directly.%@AB@%BOXSTR%@AE@%        Accepts a one-line box argument. The editor        %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%              passes the highlighted string as a text argument.%@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%       Accepts a %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%. The editor passes location of   %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%              first and last lines.%@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%        Accepts a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%. The editor passes location of    %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%              the four edges of the box.%@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%     Interprets any cursor-movement argument as a       %@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%              stream of text. The stream may span more than one              line. The editor passes location of beginning and              ending points.%@AB@%NUMARG%@AE@%        Interprets a numeric text argument as a file       Any cursor-              position exactly %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% lines down from the        movement              cursor. This position and the cursor position      type              then define a region in the file. (The two              positions form the end points of the region.) Use              this flag in conjunction with other              cursor-movement-argument flags, especially              %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%.%@AB@%MARKARG%@AE@%       Interprets a valid file-marker name as a file      Any cursor-              position. This position and the cursor position    movement              then define a region in the file. (The two         type              positions form the end points of the region.) Use              this flag in conjunction with other              cursor-movement-argument flags.%@TE:   68   3808  3 14 51 11 @%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83308@%%@4@%The descriptions also refer to the passing of information to the function;%@EH@%
you'll see how the function receives information in Section 8.3.5%@BO:   44a45@%,
"Defining the Editing Function."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83309@%%@4@%The flags are bit masks; each turns a specific bit within an unsigned%@EH@%
integer. You can combine these bit masks with binary or ( %@AB@%|%@AE@% ). For example,
you can specify a function that accepts a %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%, %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%, or %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% as:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     BOXARG | LINEARG | NUMARG%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83400@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.3.4  The WhenLoaded Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83401@%%@4@%The function %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@% takes no arguments and can return immediately.%@EH@%
However, you must include the function because the editor expects it to be
present. The simplest version of %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@% is this:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     WhenLoaded()%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          return TRUE;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83402@%%@4@%In Section 8.7%@BO:   4fa83@%, "Calling Library Functions," you'll learn how to call%@EH@%
functions that assign keys to functions and print a message on the message
line. These functions are often useful to call from within %@AB@%WhenLoaded%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83500@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.3.5  Defining the Editing Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83501@%%@4@%This section describes how to define an editing function. The section also%@EH@%
gives an overview of the information the editor passes to every function.
Section 8.4%@BO:   45aeb@%, "Programming Your Function," gives specific information on how
to interpret user-defined arguments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83502@%%@4@%The editing function must be declared %@AB@%flagType pascal EXPORT%@AE@%. The %@AB@%flagType%@AE@%%@EH@%
declaration indicates that your function returns one of two values: TRUE
(nonzero) or FALSE (zero). (Returning a value is recommended, because once
loaded, your function can be used within a macro. However, returning a value
is not a strict requirement.) The %@AB@%pascal%@AE@% keyword indicates that your
function uses the Pascal calling convention. Finally, your function must be
of type %@AB@%EXPORT%@AE@% to be properly accessed through the editor's dynamic-link
calls.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83503@%%@4@%The sample function %@AS@%Skel%@AE@% is declared as follows:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     #define TRUE  -1%@NL@%
     #define FALSE 0%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     flagType pascal EXPORT Skel (argData, pArg, fMeta)%@NL@%
     unsigned int argData;%@NL@%
     ARG far *pArg;%@NL@%
     flagType fMeta;%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          return TRUE;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83504@%%@4@%Replace the name %@AS@%Skel%@AE@% by the name of your function. This same name should%@EH@%
appear in the second field of the %@AB@%cmdTable%@AE@% data structure.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83505@%%@4@%The parameter list is described below:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83506@%%@AB@%Parameter                   Description%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%argData%@AE@%                     The value of the keystroke used to invoke the%@NL@%
                            function. This parameter is generally not used.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%pArg%@AE@%                        A pointer to a structure that contains almost%@NL@%
                            all the information passed by the editor. This%@NL@%
                            structure is discussed in detail below.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%fMeta%@AE@%                       An integer that describes whether or not a %@AI@%Meta%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            prefix is present. This integer has value true%@NL@%
                            (nonzero) if %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% is present and value false (0)%@NL@%
                            if not.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83507@%%@4@%The parameter %@AB@%pArg%@AE@% points to a structure whose first member is %@AB@%argType%@AE@%. This%@EH@%
variable contains one of six values: %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%, %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%, %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%, %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%,
%@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%, or %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%. Each of these values is defined in Section 8.3.3%@BO:   42a57@%,
"The Command Table." For example, you could test for the presence of a
%@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% with the following code:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     if( pArg->argType == BOXARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         %@AI@%/* take appropriate action for boxarg */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83508@%%@4@%The rest of the structure consists of a union of smaller structures. The C%@EH@%
%@AB@%union%@AE@% type is necessary here; it enables the editor to pass data in a
variety of formats. The choice of format depends on what kind of argument
the user defined.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE83509@%%@4@%The declaration of the %@AB@%ARG%@AE@% structure is:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct argType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int   argType;%@NL@%
         union%@NL@%
         {%@NL@%
             struct  noargType      noarg;%@NL@%
             struct  textargType    textarg;%@NL@%
             struct  nullargType    nullarg;%@NL@%
             struct  lineargType    linearg;%@NL@%
             struct  streamargType  streamarg;%@NL@%
             struct  boxargType     boxarg;%@NL@%
         } arg;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     typedef struct argType ARG;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8350A@%%@4@%The editor returns argument information in one of the nested structures. The%@EH@%
next section describes the contents of each of these structures and provides
examples showing how to use each data format.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.4  Programming Your Function%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84001@%%@4@%When you write an editing function, you have two basic tasks. First, you%@EH@%
interpret information that the editor passes you. Second, you call the
editor's lower-level functions to execute basic editing tasks.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84002@%%@4@%This section focuses on the most typical class of editing functions:%@EH@%
functions that analyze the user-defined argument and modify only the current
file. This class of functions, although huge in scope, depends on only a few
lower-level functions. Once you learn how to write these functions, you can
progress to more advanced operationsÄÄsuch as working on several files at
once or reading keyboard input. Chapter 9%@BO:   50fea@% describes the whole range of
low-level functions available.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84003@%%@4@%A typical editing function might execute the following sequence of steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84004@%  1. Get a handle to the current file by calling %@AB@%FileNameToHandle%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Use information about the user-defined argument to initialize local%@NL@%
     variables.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Process the argument. Modify the current file by calling %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and%@NL@%
     %@AB@%Putline%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Return TRUE or FALSE.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84005@%%@4@%The order above is recommended, but you do not have to follow it strictly.%@EH@%
You can perform Step 2 before Step 1. However, you must get a handle to the
current file before you can modify it.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84006@%%@4@%Sections 8.4.1%@BO:   46181@%-8.4.9 discuss each step.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84100@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.1  Getting a File Handle%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84101@%%@4@%The Microsoft Editor has its own file system. A "file system" is a group of%@EH@%
integrated structures and function calls for modifying files. The editor's
file system is not compatible with that of the C library.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84102@%%@4@%The editor has its own file-handle type, %@AB@%PFILE%@AE@%. This type, along with other%@EH@%
types needed for extensions, is defined in the include file EXT.H. For
example, you can create a file handle %@AS@%pFile%@AE@% with the declaration:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     PFILE   pFile;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84103@%%@4@%Usually, your editing work involves the current file; that is, the file that%@EH@%
now appears in the current editing window. Because the current file is
already open for editing, you do not need to open or initialize the current
file in any way. You simply assign the existing file handle to one of your
own variables.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84104@%%@4@%The %@AB@%FileNameToHandle%@AE@% function returns a handle to a file that is already%@EH@%
open for editing. (More than one file may be open for editing, particularly
if the user has worked on more than one file during the editing session.)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84105@%%@4@%To get a handle to the current file, simply pass two empty strings to the%@EH@%
function:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     pFile = FileNameToHandle( "", "" );%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84106@%%@4@%The first argument to %@AB@%FileNameToHandle%@AE@% takes a file name. The second%@EH@%
argument takes a "short name," which is a base name the editor searches for
in its list of open files. If the first string is empty, the function
returns a handle to the current file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84107@%%@4@%The %@AB@%AddFile%@AE@% function is the other function that returns a file handle.%@EH@%
%@AB@%AddFile%@AE@% causes the editor to open a file for editingÄÄeither a new file or a
file that exists on disk but is not yet open for editing.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84108@%%@4@%See Chapter 9%@BO:   50fea@% for complete information on each function.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84200@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.2  Interpreting the User-Defined Argument%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84201@%%@4@%After getting a handle to the current file, you need to interpret the%@EH@%
user-defined argument.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84202@%%@4@%You determine the type of the user's argument by testing the value of%@EH@%
pArg->argType. If you declare a function that takes only one type of
argument, testing pArg->argType is not necessary. You know in advance what
kind of argument was given, since the editor rejects invalid arguments.
Table 8.1%@BO:   435cc@%, "Meaning of cmdTable Flags," explains how to declare what
arguments your function accepts.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84203@%%@4@%If your function accepts more than one kind of argument, you can use either%@EH@%
if-then-else blocks or switch-case statements to evaluate the user's
argument:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     switch( pArg->argType )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
        case( NULLARG ):    %@AI@%/* Take action for empty arg */%@AE@%%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        case( BOXARG ):     %@AI@%/* Take action for boxarg */%@AE@%%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        case( LINEARG ):   %@AI@%/* Take action for linearg */%@AE@%%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
        .%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84204@%%@4@%The value of pArg->argType is always equal to one of six values:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84205@%  ş  %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
  ş  %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84206@%%@4@%The next six sections consider each of these argument types in detail,%@EH@%
giving declarations and examples for each.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84300@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.3  The NOARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84301@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in the%@EH@%
pArg->arg.noarg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct  noargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         LINE    y;   %@AI@%/* Line number of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     x;   %@AI@%/* Column of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84302@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84303@%%@4@%The %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user did not invoke the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix, and%@EH@%
therefore did not enter an argument. The cursor coordinates are zero-based;
in other words, the start of the file is position (0,0).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84304@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag%@EH@%
%@AB@%NOARG%@AE@% or %@AB@%CURSORFUNC%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84305@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84306@%%@4@%The following example initializes the coordinates (%@AS@%yCur%@AE@%, %@AS@%xCur%@AE@%) with the row%@EH@%
and column of the cursor position:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     COL   xCur;%@NL@%
     LINE  yCur;%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg->argType == NOARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          xCur = pArg->arg.noarg.x;%@NL@%
          yCur = pArg->arg.noarg.y;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84400@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.4  The NULLARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84401@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in the%@EH@%
pArg->arg.nullarg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct  nullargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int     cArg;   %@AI@%/* Number of times Arg was invoked */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    y;      %@AI@%/* Line number of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     x;      %@AI@%/* Column of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84402@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84403@%%@4@%The %@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix but did not%@EH@%
enter an argument. The argument is therefore empty, or null. The cursor
coordinates are zero-based; in other words, the start of the file is
position (0,0).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84404@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag%@EH@%
%@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84405@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84406@%%@4@%The following example initializes the coordinates (%@AS@%yCur%@AE@%, %@AS@%xCur%@AE@%) with the row%@EH@%
and column of the cursor position, and sets %@AS@%cArg%@AE@% equal to the number of
times that the user invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     COL   xCur;%@NL@%
     LINE  yCur;%@NL@%
     int   cArg;%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg->argType == NULLARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          xCur = pArg->arg.nullarg.x;%@NL@%
          yCur = pArg->arg.nullarg.y;%@NL@%
          cArg = pArg->arg.nullarg.cArg;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84500@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.5  The TEXTARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84501@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in the%@EH@%
pArg->arg.textarg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct  textargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int     cArg;   %@AI@%/* Number of times Arg was invoked */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    y;      %@AI@%/* Line number of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     x;      %@AI@%/* Column of cursor */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         char far *pText %@AI@%/* Pointer to textarg string */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84502@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84503@%%@4@%The %@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user's argument defined a string of%@EH@%
text. The cursor coordinates are zero-based, and %@AS@%pText%@AE@% points to a
null-terminated string.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84504@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag%@EH@%
%@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%, %@AB@%BOXSTR%@AE@%, %@AB@%NULLEOL%@AE@%, or %@AB@%NULLEOW%@AE@%. Each of these argument types selects a
string of text in a different way (for example, %@AB@%BOXSTR%@AE@% uses a
cursor-movement argument); however, the format used for all these cases is
the same.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84505@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84506@%%@4@%The following example initializes the coordinates (%@AS@%yCur%@AE@%, %@AS@%xCur%@AE@%) with the row%@EH@%
and column of the cursor position, and sets %@AS@%cArg%@AE@% equal to the number of
times that the user invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix. Finally, the user-defined
%@AI@%textarg%@AE@% is copied into the character array %@AS@%buf%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     COL   xCur;%@NL@%
     LINE  yCur;%@NL@%
     int   cArg;%@NL@%
     char  buf[BUFLEN]; .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg->argType == TEXTARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          xCur = pArg->arg.textarg.x;%@NL@%
          yCur = pArg->arg.textarg.y;%@NL@%
          cArg = pArg->arg.textarg.cArg;%@NL@%
          strcpy (buf, pArg->arg.textarg.pText);%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84600@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.6  The LINEARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84601@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in the%@EH@%
pArg->arg.linearg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct  lineargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int     cArg;   %@AI@%/* Number of times Arg was invoked */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yStart; %@AI@%/* Line number of first line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yEnd;   %@AI@%/* Line number of last line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84602@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84603@%%@4@%The %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user defined a range of lines by%@EH@%
aligning the cursor and arg position in the same column but different rows.
The range of lines includes %@AS@%yStart%@AE@% and %@AS@%yEnd%@AE@%, as well as all lines in
between. Line numbers are zero-based, so that line 0 is the first line in
the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84604@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag%@EH@%
%@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84605@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84606@%%@4@%The following example sets %@AS@%cArg%@AE@% equal to the number of times that the user%@EH@%
invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix, and sets %@AS@%yStart%@AE@% and %@AS@%yEnd%@AE@% equal to the line numbers
of the first and last lines:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     int   cArg;%@NL@%
     LINE  yStart;%@NL@%
     LINE  yEnd;%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg->argType == LINEARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          cArg   = pArg->arg.linearg.cArg;%@NL@%
          yStart = pArg->arg.linearg.yStart;%@NL@%
          yEnd   = pArg->arg.linearg.yEnd;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84700@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.7  The STREAMARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84701@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in%@EH@%
the pArg->arg.linearg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct streamargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int   cArg;     %@AI@%/* Number of times Arg was invoked */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE  yStart;   %@AI@%/* Coordinates of first byte in */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL   xStart;   %@AI@%/*   the stream of text */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE  yEnd;     %@AI@%/* Coordinates of byte just after */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL   xEnd;     %@AI@%/*   the last byte of the stream */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84702@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84703@%%@4@%The %@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user defined a cursor-movement%@EH@%
argument, which the function interprets as a stream of text rather than as a
%@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% or %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%. The stream of text includes %@AS@%yStart%@AE@% and %@AS@%xStart%@AE@% but not
%@AS@%yEnd%@AE@% and %@AS@%xEnd%@AE@%, which gives the location of the character just to the right
of the last character in the stream.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84704@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag%@EH@%
%@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84705@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84706@%%@4@%The following example sets %@AS@%cArg%@AE@% equal to the number of times that the user%@EH@%
invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix. Then the example initializes variables for the
beginning and end of the stream.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     int   cArg;%@NL@%
     LINE  yStart;%@NL@%
     COL   xStart;%@NL@%
     LINE  yEnd;%@NL@%
     COL   xEnd;%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg-argType == LINEARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          cArg   = pArg->arg.streamarg.cArg;%@NL@%
          yStart = pArg->arg.streamarg.yStart;%@NL@%
          xStart = pArg->arg.streamarg.xStart;%@NL@%
          yEnd   = pArg->arg.streamarg.yEnd;%@NL@%
          xEnd   = pArg->arg.streamarg.xEnd;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84800@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.8  The BOXARG Type%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84801@%%@4@%When pArg->argType is equal to %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%, the editor passes information in the%@EH@%
pArg->arg.boxarg structure, which has the format:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     struct  boxargType%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         int     cArg;        %@AI@%/* Number of times Arg was invoked */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yTop;        %@AI@%/* Line number of first line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yBottom;     %@AI@%/* Line number of last line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     xLeft;       %@AI@%/* Leftmost column in box */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     xRight;      %@AI@%/* Rightmost column in box */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84802@%%@4@%%@AB@%Description%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84803@%%@4@%The %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@% type indicates that the user defined a rectangular area on the%@EH@%
screen. Row and column numbers are zero-based; in other words, the start of
the file is position (0,0). The lines and column edges, %@AS@%yTop%@AE@%, %@AS@%yBottom%@AE@%,
%@AS@%xLeft%@AE@%, and %@AS@%xRight%@AE@%, are all included in the area itself.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84804@%%@4@%This argument type is possible if you declared your function with the flag %@EH@%
%@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84805@%%@4@%%@AB@%Example%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84806@%%@4@%The following example sets %@AS@%cArg%@AE@% equal to the number of times that the user%@EH@%
invoked the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% prefix. Then the example initializes variables for the four
borders of the box.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     int   cArg;%@NL@%
     LINE  yTop;%@NL@%
     LINE  yBottom;%@NL@%
     COL   xLeft;%@NL@%
     COL   xRight;%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     .%@NL@%
     if( pArg-argType == LINEARG )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
          cArg    = pArg->arg.boxarg.cArg;%@NL@%
          yTop    = pArg->arg.boxarg.yTop;%@NL@%
          yBottom = pArg->arg.boxarg.yBottom;%@NL@%
          xLeft   = pArg->arg.boxarg.xLeft;%@NL@%
          xRight  = pArg->arg.boxarg.xRight;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84900@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.4.9  Modifying the Current File%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84901@%%@4@%This section deals with the core of an editing functionÄÄreading and%@EH@%
altering the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84902@%%@4@%After you have analyzed the user's argument and got a handle to the current%@EH@%
file, you are ready to work on the file. At this stage, two functions are
most relevant: %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and %@AB@%Putline%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84903@%%@4@%The %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% function reads one line from the file:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     len = GetLine (yStart, buffer, pFile);%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84904@%%@4@%The first argument is a line number, the second a pointer to a buffer, and%@EH@%
the third a file handle. With extension functions, line numbers are
consistently indexed (they are all zero-based so that the first line in the
file is numbered 0), so you can use a line number previously passed by the
editor. The buffer is a previously declared string of characters. %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@%
fills this string with characters and a terminating null byte. Since you are
working on the current file, pass the file handle you received when you
called %@AB@%FileNameToHandle%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84905@%%@4@%Finally, %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% returns the length of the line copied.%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84906@%%@4@%The %@AB@%PutLine%@AE@% function is the flip side of %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and takes almost exactly%@EH@%
the same arguments:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     PutLine (yStart, buffer, pFile);%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84907@%%@4@%The first argument is a zero-based line number. The second argument points%@EH@%
to a buffer containing text that you want to write to the file. The third
argument is a file handle. Again, you can use a handle to the current file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84908@%%@4@%Both %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and %@AB@%PutLine%@AE@% deal with null-terminated strings. You should not%@EH@%
add a new-line character to the string you pass to %@AB@%PutLine%@AE@%. The editor adds
or strips new-line characters as appropriate.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE84909@%%@4@%The following section of code demonstrates the use of %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and %@AB@%PutLine%@AE@% in%@EH@%
a loop that numbers the lines %@AS@%yStart%@AE@% to %@AS@%yEnd%@AE@%:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     for( curLine = yStart, i = 1; curLine <= yEnd; curLine++, i++ )%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         GetLine( curLine, buffer, pFile ); %@AI@%/* Get line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         itoa( i, digits, 10 );             %@AI@%/* Convert i to digit string */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         strcat( digits, ". " );%@NL@%
         strcat( digits, buffer );          %@AI@%/* Prefix buffer with digits */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         PutLine( curLine, digits, pFile ); %@AI@%/* Put line back */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.5  Compiling and Linking%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85001@%%@4@%After writing your C module, you're ready to compile and link. The%@EH@%
procedures for compiling and linking in protected mode are slightly
different from compiling and linking in real mode. Sections 8.5.1%@BO:   4ab20@% and
8.5.2%@BO:   4b1b6@% consider both environments.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   If you created C-extension modules for Version 1.0 of the Microsoft%@NL@%
   Editor, you do not have to recompile or relink your C extensions.%@NL@%
   However, if you do recompile your extensions, make sure that you use the%@NL@%
   new version of the EXT.H include file.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85100@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.5.1  Compiling and Linking for Real Mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85101@%%@4@%To create a C extension for real mode (DOS or the OS/2 3.%@AI@%x%@AE@% compability box),%@EH@%
follow these steps:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85102@%  1. Compile with command line options /Gs and /Asfu. These mandatory%@NL@%
     options establish the proper memory model and calling convention. (If%@NL@%
     you are programming in the Microsoft Macro Assembler (MASM), use near%@NL@%
     code and far data segments, in which SS is not assumed equal to DS.)%@NL@%
     For example:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         %@AS@%CL /c /Gs /Asfu myext.c%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Link the file EXTHDR.OBJ to your extension. The EXTHDR.OBJ file must be%@NL@%
     the first object module on the command line:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         %@AS@%CL /AC /Femyext.mxt exthdr myext%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     Use the /AC option if your extension calls C library functions. The /AC%@NL@%
     option directs the linker to use the compact-model library.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%IMPORTANT%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Strictly speaking, the .MXT file extension is not required; the editor%@NL@%
   can load modules with any file extension name. However, using a file%@NL@%
   extension of .MXT is strongly recommended so that your extensions are not%@NL@%
   confused with true executable (.EXE) files, which can be run directly%@NL@%
   from DOS. Trying to execute an extension as if it were an .EXE file will%@NL@%
   bring the system to its knees.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85200@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.5.2  Compiling and Linking for Protected Mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85201@%%@4@%To create a C extension for protected mode, follow these steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85202@%  1. Compile with command-line options /Gs and /Asfu. These mandatory%@NL@%
     options establish the proper memory model and calling convention. (If%@NL@%
     you are programming in MASM, use near code and far data segments in%@NL@%
     which SS is not assumed equal to DS.) For example:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
          %@AS@%CL /c /Gs /Asfu myext.c%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The same object module can be used for both real and protected mode, so%@NL@%
     you do not have to recompile if you want an extension for both modes.%@NL@%
     However, you do have to relink, as explained below.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Link with the file EXTHDRP.OBJ to your extension along with a%@NL@%
     module-definitions file. The EXTHDRP.OBJ file must be the first object%@NL@%
     module on the command line:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
          %@AS@%LINK /NOI exthdrp myext, myext.dll,, doscalls, myext.def;%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     If your extension calls C library functions, link in the compact-model%@NL@%
     library. Link with the /NOI option, since the OS/2 loader is%@NL@%
     case-sensitive.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85203@%%@4@%The file MYEXT.DEF can be created by copying the file SKEL.DEF (provided%@EH@%
with the editor). No modification is necessary. You can also link with
SKEL.DEF itself.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85300@%%@3@%%@AB@%8.5.3  Loading Your Extension%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85301@%%@4@%Compiling and linking your module with the correct options produces an .MXT%@EH@%
file (for real mode) or a .DLL file (for OS/2 protected mode) the editor can
load and execute on demand.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85302@%%@4@%To use a real-mode extension, set the %@AB@%load%@AE@% switch with the full path name%@EH@%
for your C extension. For example, after you have created the file
MYEXT.MXT, you could place the following statement in the TOOLS.INI file:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     load:%@AI@%path%@AE@%\myext.mxt%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85303@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%path%@AE@% is the location of the extension. The editor responds by%@EH@%
automatically loading your C-extension module into memory upon start-up. You
can also set the %@AB@%load%@AE@% switch with the %@AI@%Assign%@AE@% command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   The load switch can be assigned a number of times, each assignment%@NL@%
   causing the editor to load another extension. All of the extensions%@NL@%
   reside in memory together; no extension is removed from memory until the%@NL@%
   editor terminates.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85304@%%@4@%The load switch can accept an environment variable as described in Section%@EH@%
7.3%@BO:   3a7a5@%, "Special Syntax for Text Switches."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85305@%%@4@%To use a protected-mode extension, place your .DLL file in a directory%@EH@%
specified in the LIBPATH variable. You can set the load switch in the same
way described above; however, when running under protected mode, the editor
ignores the %@AI@%path%@AE@% and the file extension. Therefore, for protected-mode-only
extensions, the only declaration you need is the following:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     load:myext%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85306@%%@4@%To load an extension for both real and protected modes, follow these steps:%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85307@%  1. Compile the source file once.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. Link two times, once for real mode and once for protected mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. Place the protected-mode module (a .DLL file) in a LIBPATH directory.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  4. Use the real-mode %@AB@%load%@AE@% setting. The editor uses the full text of the%@NL@%
     switch setting when in real mode, but ignores the path and file%@NL@%
     extension when in protected mode.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85308@%%@4@%Whenever the editor successfully loads an extension, it checks the TOOLS.INI%@EH@%
file for the tag%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AB@%[M-%@AE@%%@AI@%mxt%@AE@%%@AB@%]%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8530A@%%@4@%in which %@AI@%mxt%@AE@% is the base name of the extension. If the tag exists, the%@EH@%
editor recognizes the settings immediately following the tag.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85310@%%@4@%%@AB@%Special Considerations for OS/2%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85311@%%@4@%Under OS/2 Version 1.1 and later, protected-mode editor extensions may have%@EH@%
file extensions other than .DLL and may be placed in directories other than
those specified in LIBPATH. The editor searches for the extensions specified
in the %@AB@%load%@AE@% statement in the following sequence:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85312@%  1. If an environment variable or a full path is specified, the editor%@NL@%
     searches the appropriate directories, as in the following examples:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         load:$LIB:yourext.mxt%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         load:drive:\dir\ yourext.mxt%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     The editor searches the current directory if there is no environment%@NL@%
     variable or full-path specification.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  2. If the desired extension is not found, and its name is only a base name%@NL@%
     without a file extension, the editor appends the appropriate file%@NL@%
     extension (.MXT for real mode, .PXT for protected mode) and repeats%@NL@%
     Step 1.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
  3. If the editor extension still cannot be located, the editor searches%@NL@%
     for %@AI@%basename%@AE@%.DLL in the directories specified in LIBPATH, where%@NL@%
     %@AI@%basename%@AE@% is the base name of the extension.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85313@%%@4@%In real mode (DOS or the OS/2 3.%@AI@%x%@AE@% compatibility box), only Steps 1 and 2 are%@EH@%
preformed. Under OS/2 Version 1.0, only Step 3 is performed.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85314@%%@4@%Within TOOLS.INI tag declarations, only the base name is significant, not%@EH@%
the file extension. For example, the statements following%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     [M-YOUREXT]%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85315@%%@4@%would always be used, regardless of the file extension that was used to%@EH@%
locate YOUREXT.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85316@%%@4@%The "autoload" feature automatically loads extensions without a %@AB@%load%@AE@%%@EH@%
statement in TOOLS.INI. The editor searches the directories in the PATH
environment variable for file names with the following patterns, and loads
as many of them as it finds:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85317@%%@AB@%Operating System            Extension Autoloaded%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
DOS or OS/2 real mode       M*.MXT%@NL@%
%@NL@%
OS/2 protected mode         M*.PXT%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85318@%%@4@%The file names for the on-line Help extensions supplied with this version of%@EH@%
the Microsoft Editor have the correct form for autoloading. Therefore, they
only need to be placed in any directory in the PATH environment variable;
you do not have to add a %@AB@%load%@AE@% statement to TOOLS.INI.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE85319@%%@4@%Autoloading occurs after TOOLS.INI has been read, so any extension-specific%@EH@%
sections still take effect.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@AI@%NOTE%@AE@%%@NL@%
   Autoloading does not work under OS/2 Version 1.0.%@NL@%
ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8531A@%%@4@%You can load extensions in both real and protected mode by using a single%@EH@%
%@AB@%load%@AE@% statement of the following form:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     load:$PATH:%@AI@%basename%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8531B@%%@4@%The extensions must have the same %@AI@%basename%@AE@% and the default extension (.MXT%@EH@%
for DOS or OS/2 real mode, .PXT for OS/2 protected mode) for the appropriate
operating system. The extensions can go anywhere in the specified path.
Since the file extension is omitted in this %@AB@%load%@AE@% statement, the editor will
append the appropriate extension to %@AI@%basename%@AE@% (be sure the name has no
trailing period) and load the correct file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE8531C@%%@4@%You can also give your extension a name of the form M*.MXT or M*.PXT%@EH@%
(according to the operating system). The extension will be autoloaded
without requiring a %@AB@%load%@AE@% statement in TOOLS.INI. It is also possible to
specify the editor extension for one mode in a %@AB@%load%@AE@% statement, while giving
the extension for the other mode an autoload default name.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE86000@%%@2@%%@AB@%8.6  A C-Extension Sample Program%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE86001@%%@4@%The following C-extension sample program features a function named %@AS@%tglcase%@AE@%.%@EH@%
This function converts uppercase letters to lowercase, and lowercase letters
to uppercase. It acts on the file according to the argument type:%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE86002@%%@AB@%Argument                    Effect%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%NOARG%@AE@%                       Acts on entire current line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@%                     Acts on current line, from the cursor position%@NL@%
                            (inclusive) up to the end of the line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@%                      Acts on the highlighted region.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%                     Acts on the highlighted region (containing a%@NL@%
                            range of complete lines).%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%TEXTARG%@AE@%                     Argument not accepted.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@AB@%STREAMARG%@AE@%                   Not recognized. The argument is treated as %@AB@%%@AE@%%@NL@%
                            %@AB@%BOXARG%@AE@% or %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE86003@%%@4@%In each case, the function responds to the argument by initializing the%@EH@%
limits of an imaginary box. In the case of a %@AB@%LINEARG%@AE@%, the column limits are
set at 0 and BUFLEN (the maximum length of a text line in M). %@AB@%NOARG%@AE@% and
%@AB@%NULLARG%@AE@% are handled in a similar fashion. Once the limits of the area are
initialized, one small section of code does the actual work. This section
calls %@AB@%GetLine%@AE@% and %@AB@%PutLine%@AE@% repeatedly to read and replace lines in the
current file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSE86004@%%@4@%This extension calls C library functions. To successfully link this%@EH@%
extension, include the compact-model library.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*** tglcase.c - case toggling editor extension%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     #define ID      " tglcase ver 1.00 "##__DATE__##" "##__TIME__%@NL@%
     #define NULL    ((void *) 0)%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     #include <stdlib.h>                     %@AI@%/* min macro definition */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     #include <string.h>                     %@AI@%/* prototypes for string fcns*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     #include "ext.h"%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Internal function prototypes%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     void     pascal          id         (char *);%@NL@%
     void     WhenLoaded (void);%@NL@%
     flagType pascal EXPORT tglcase    (unsigned int, ARG far *, flagType);%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/********************************************************************%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** tglcase%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Toggle the case of alphabetics contained within the selected argument:%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  NOARG       - Toggle case of entire current line%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  NULLARG     - Toggle case of current line from cursor to end of line%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  LINEARG     - Toggle case of range of lines%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  BOXARG      - Toggle case of characters with the selected box%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  NUMARG      - Converted to LINEARG before extension is called%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  MARKARG     - Converted to Appropriate ARG form above before extension is%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**                called%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  STREAMARG   - Not Allowed; treated as BOXARG%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  TEXTARG     - Not Allowed%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     flagType pascal EXTERNAL tglcase (argData, pArg, fMeta)%@NL@%
     unsigned int argData;                   %@AI@%/* keystroke invoked with */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     ARG far *pArg;                          %@AI@%/* argument data */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     flagType fMeta;                         %@AI@%/* indicates preceded by meta */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         PFILE   pFile;                  %@AI@%/* file handle of current file */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     xStart;                 %@AI@%/* left border of arg area */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yStart;                 %@AI@%/* starting line of arg area */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     xEnd;                   %@AI@%/* right border of arg area */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         LINE    yEnd;                   %@AI@%/* ending line of arg area */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         int     cbLine;                 %@AI@%/* byte count of current line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         COL     xCur;                   %@AI@%/* current column being toggled */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         char    buf[BUFLEN];            %@AI@%/* buffer for line being toggled*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
         register char c;                %@AI@%/* character being analyzed */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         id( "" );%@NL@%
         pFile = FileNameToHandle( "", NULL );%@NL@%
         switch( pArg->argType )%@NL@%
         {%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** For the various argument types, set up a box%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** (xStart, yStart) - (xEnd, yEnd)%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** over which the case conversion code below can operate%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
             case NOARG:                         %@AI@%/* case switch entire line */%@AE@%%@NL@%
                 xStart = 0;%@NL@%
                 xEnd = BUFLEN;%@NL@%
                 yStart = yEnd = pArg->arg.noarg.y;%@NL@%
                 break;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             case NULLARG:                       %@AI@%/* case switch to EOL */%@AE@%%@NL@%
                 xStart = pArg->arg.nullarg.x;%@NL@%
                 xEnd = BUFLEN;%@NL@%
                 yStart = yEnd = pArg->arg.nullarg.y;%@NL@%
                 break;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             case LINEARG:                       %@AI@%/* case switch line range */%@AE@%%@NL@%
                 xStart = 0;%@NL@%
                 xEnd = BUFLEN;%@NL@%
                 yStart = pArg->arg.linearg.yStart;%@NL@%
                 yEnd = pArg->arg.linearg.yEnd;%@NL@%
                 break;%@NL@%
%@NL@%
             case BOXARG:                        %@AI@%/* case switch box */%@AE@%%@NL@%
                 xStart = pArg->arg.boxarg.xLeft;%@NL@%
                 xEnd   = pArg->arg.boxarg.xRight;%@NL@%
                 yStart = pArg->arg.boxarg.yTop;%@NL@%
                 yEnd   = pArg->arg.boxarg.yBottom;%@NL@%
                 break;%@NL@%
         }%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Within range of lines yStart to yEnd, get each line, and if non-null,%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** check each character. If alphabetic, replace with its case-converted%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** value. After all characters have been checked, replace line in file.%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
         while( yStart <= yEnd )%@NL@%
         {%@NL@%
          if( cbLine = GetLine( yStart, buf, pFile ))%@NL@%
             {%@NL@%
              for( xCur = xStart; (xCur <= min( cbLine, xEnd )); xCur++ )%@NL@%
                 {%@NL@%
                     c = buf[xCur];%@NL@%
               if( (c >= 'A' ) && (c <= 'Z'))%@NL@%
                         c += 'a'-'A';%@NL@%
               else if( (c >= 'a' ) && (c <= 'z'))%@NL@%
                         c += 'A'-'a';%@NL@%
                     buf[xCur] = c;%@NL@%
                 }%@NL@%
              PutLine( yStart++, buf, pFile );%@NL@%
             }%@NL@%
         }%@NL@%
         return 1;%@NL@%
     }%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*************************************************************************%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** WhenLoaded%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Executed when extension gets loaded. Identify self & assign default%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** keystroke.%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Entry:%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  none%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     void WhenLoaded ()%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
     id("case conversion extension:");%@NL@%
     SetKey ("tglcase",  "alt+c");%@NL@%
     } %@AI@%/* end WhenLoaded */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*************************************************************************%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** id%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** identify ourselves, along with any passed informative message%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Entry:%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**  pszMsg      = Pointer to asciiz message to which the extension name%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**                and version are appended prior to display%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     void pascal id (pszFcn)%@NL@%
     char *pszFcn;                                   %@AI@%/* function name */%@AE@%%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         char    buf[80];                                %@AI@%/* message buffer */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
         strcpy (buf,pszFcn);                    %@AI@%/* start with message */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         strcat (buf,ID);                                %@AI@%/* append version */%@AE@%%@NL@%
         DoMessage (buf);%@NL@%
     } %@AI@%/* end id */%@AE@%%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*************************************************************************%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Switch communication table to the editor%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** This extension defines no switches%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     struct swiDesc  swiTable[] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         { NULL, NULL, 0 }%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
     %@AI@%/*************************************************************************%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%**%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Command communication table to the editor%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%** Defines the name, location and acceptable argument types%@AE@%%@NL@%
     %@AI@%*/%@AE@%%@NL@%
     struct cmdDesc  cmdTable[] =%@NL@%
     {%@NL@%
         {"tglcase",tglcase,0, KEEPMETA | NOARG | BOXARG | NULLARG | LINEARG%@NL@%
     |%@NL@%
                               MARKARG | NUMARG | MODIFIES},%@NL@%
         { NULL, NULL, 0, 0 }%@NL@%
     };%@NL@%
%@NL@%
