%@CR:MSEg0001@%%@4@%This glossary defines terms in this manual used in a technical or unique%@EH@%
way.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD001@%%@4@%%@AB@%Arg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A function modifier that introduces an argument or an editing function.
  The argument may be of any type and is passed to the next function as
  input. For example, the command %@AI@%Arg textarg Copy%@AE@% passes the argument
  %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% to the function %@AI@%Copy%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD002@%%@4@%%@AB@%argument%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  An input to a function. The Microsoft Editor uses two classes of
  arguments: cursor-movement arguments and text arguments. Cursor-movement
  arguments (%@AI@%boxarg%@AE@%, %@AI@%linearg%@AE@%, and %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@%) specify a range of characters
  on the screen. Text arguments (%@AI@%markarg%@AE@%, %@AI@%numarg%@AE@%, and %@AI@%textarg%@AE@%) are typed in
  directly. Arguments are introduced by using the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD003@%%@4@%%@AB@%assignment%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  %@AI@%See%@AE@% "function assignment."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD004@%%@4@%%@AB@%box mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The editing mode that lets you highlight cursor-movement arguments as
  rectangular areas of text.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD005@%%@4@%%@AB@%boxarg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A rectangular area on the screen, defined by the two opposite corners: the
  initial cursor position and the current cursor position. The editor must
  be in box mode, and the two cursor positions must be on separate rows and
  separate columns. A %@AI@%boxarg%@AE@% is generated by invoking the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function and
  then moving the cursor to a new location.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD006@%%@4@%%@AB@%buffer%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  An area in memory in which a copy of the file is kept and changed as you
  edit. This buffer is copied to disk when you do a save operation.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD007@%%@4@%%@AB@%C extension%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A C-language module that defines new editing functions and switches. %@AI@%See%@AE@%
  Chapter 8%@BO:   3fbeb@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD008@%%@4@%%@AB@%Clipboard%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A pseudo file that holds text selected with the %@AI@%Copy%@AE@%, %@AI@%Ldelete%@AE@%, or %@AI@%Sdelete%@AE@%
  functions. You can use the %@AI@%Paste%@AE@% function to insert text from the
  Clipboard into a file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD009@%%@4@%%@AB@%configuration%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A description of the specific assignments of functions to keys. For
  example, a BRIEF configuration implies that the Microsoft Editor uses keys
  similar to those that the BRIEF editor uses to invoke similar functions.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD010@%%@4@%%@AB@%cursor%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The blinking white underline character that defines current position. When
  you type characters into the file, they appear at the cursor position.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD011@%%@4@%%@AB@%default%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A setting assumed by the editor until you specify otherwise. The Microsoft
  Editor uses two categories of default settings: function assignments and
  switches.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD012@%%@4@%%@AB@%dialog line%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The line just above the status line. The dialog line reports editor
  messages. You enter text arguments on this line.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD013@%%@4@%%@AB@%emacs%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A popular mainframe editor from which the functions %@AI@%Emacscdel%@AE@% and
  %@AI@%Emacsnewl%@AE@% were taken.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD014@%%@4@%%@AB@%file history%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A list of the most recently edited files, including any files currently
  open for editing. The file history is displayed in the <information-file>
  pseudo file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD015@%%@4@%%@AB@%function assignment%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A method of assigning an editor function to a specific keystroke so that
  pressing the keystroke invokes the function. Use the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%%@AI@%textarg Assign%@AE@%
  command to make an assignment for a single editing session, or you can
  enter the assignment in the TOOLS.INI file so that it may be used during
  any editing session. %@AI@%See%@AE@% Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD016@%%@4@%%@AB@%graphic%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  %@AI@%See%@AE@% "literal."%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD017@%%@4@%%@AB@%initial cursor position%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The position the cursor is in when the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function is invoked.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD018@%%@4@%%@AB@%insert mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  An input mode that inserts rather than replaces characters in the file as
  they are entered.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD019@%%@4@%%@AB@%linearg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A range of complete lines, including all the lines from the initial cursor
  position to the current cursor position. The editor must be in box mode.
  You define a %@AI@%linearg%@AE@% by invoking the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function (pressing ALT+A), then
  moving the cursor to a different line but same column as the initial
  cursor position.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD020@%%@4@%%@AB@%literal%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The corresponding ASCII value of a keystroke.  When a keystroke is
  considered literal or graphic, pressing the key causes the editor to place
  the corresponding value in a file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD021@%%@4@%%@AB@%macro%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A function made up of arguments and previously defined functions. For
  example, you can create a macro that contains a set of repeatedly
  performed functions and assign the macro to a keystroke. Those functions
  can be carried out much more quickly and simply by invoking the macro. %@AI@%See%@AE@%
  Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD022@%%@4@%%@AB@%markarg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A special type of %@AI@%textarg%@AE@% that has been previously defined to be a
  markerÄÄthat is, it is associated with a particular position in the file.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD023@%%@4@%%@AB@%marker%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A name assigned to a cursor position in a file so that this position can
  be referred to within a command by using this name. For example, the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%
  %@AI@%markarg Copy%@AE@% command selects the text between the cursor position and the
  marker position. A marker is assigned using the %@AI@%Arg Arg textarg Mark%@AE@%
  command.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD024@%%@4@%%@AB@%Meta%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A function that modifies other functions so they perform differently. The
  effect of %@AI@%Meta%@AE@% varies with each function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD025@%%@4@%%@AB@%nested macro%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A macro executed by another macro.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD026@%%@4@%%@AB@%numarg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A numerical value you enter on the dialog line, which is passed to a
  function. A %@AI@%numarg%@AE@% is introduced by the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@% function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD027@%%@4@%%@AB@%overtype mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The input mode that replaces characters at the cursor position instead of
  inserting them. Unlike insert mode, this mode does not preserve existing
  text at the cursor position.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD028@%%@4@%%@AB@%pseudo file%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A file kept in memory that does not correspond to a disk file. The name of
  a pseudo file is always enclosed in angle brackets (%@AB@%<>%@AE@%). You can create
  your pseudo files for fast saving of temporary information. In addition,
  the editor creates several pseudo files of its own and gives them special
  meaning. %@AI@%See%@AE@% Chapter 4%@BO:   120e2@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD029@%%@4@%%@AB@%recorded macro%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A macro you create with the %@AI@%Record%@AE@% function. The %@AI@%Record%@AE@% function turns
  record mode on and off. All actions you execute while in record mode are
  by default assigned to the RECORDVALUE macro. %@AI@%See%@AE@% Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD030@%%@4@%%@AB@%regular expression%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A pattern specifying a set of one or more character strings to search for.
  It may be a simple string or a more complex arrangement of characters and
  special symbols that specify a variety of strings to be matched. %@AI@%See%@AE@%
  Chapter 5%@BO:   206bc@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD031@%%@4@%%@AB@%return value%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A value returned by an editing function. The value may be true or false,
  depending on whether the function was successful. This value can be used
  to create complex macros that perform differently depending upon the
  results of individual functions within the macro. %@AI@%See%@AE@% Chapter 6%@BO:   28e3a@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD032@%%@4@%%@AB@%short name%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A file name without a path or file extension. The %@AI@%Setfile%@AE@% and %@AI@%Paste%@AE@%
  functions can take a short name as input and search for a full-length file
  name in the file history that contains the short name.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD033@%%@4@%%@AB@%status line%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The bottom line of the screen. This line contains useful information about
  the current editing session.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD034@%%@4@%%@AB@%stream mode%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The editing mode that lets you highlight cursor-movement arguments as
  continuous streams of text, rather than rectangular areas.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD035@%%@4@%%@AB@%streamarg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  The contiguous stream of characters between two positionsÄÄthe initial
  cursor position and the new cursor position. The editor must be in stream
  mode. You define a %@AI@%streamarg%@AE@% by invoking %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%, moving the cursor to any new
  location, and then invoking %@AI@%Sinsert%@AE@% or %@AI@%Sdelete%@AE@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD036@%%@4@%%@AB@%switch%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A variable that modifies the way the editor performs. The Microsoft Editor
  uses three kinds of switches: Boolean switches, which turn a certain
  editor feature on or off; numeric switches, which specify numeric
  constants; and text switches, which specify a string of characters. %@AI@%See%@AE@%
  Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD037@%%@4@%%@AB@%tag%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  An identifier enclosed in brackets (%@AB@%[]%@AE@%) that marks the beginning of a
  section in the TOOLS.INI file. For example, unless you rename the editor,
  the principal section for editor settings starts at the [M] tag. %@AI@%See%@AE@%
  Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD038@%%@4@%%@AB@%textarg%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A string of text that you enter on the dialog line after invoking the %@AI@%Arg%@AE@%
  function. The text that you enter is passed as input to the next function.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD039@%%@4@%%@AB@%TOOLS.INI%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  A file that contains initialization information for the Microsoft Editor
  and other programs. The file is divided into sections with the use of
  tags. These sections can be loaded automatically when the editor is
  started or by command from within the editor. %@AI@%See%@AE@% Chapter 7%@BO:   3396c@%.%@NL@%
%@NL@%
%@CR:MSEgD040@%%@4@%%@AB@%window%@AE@%%@EH@%%@NL@%
  An area on the screen used to display part of a file. Unless a file is
  extremely small, it is impossible to see all of it on the screen at once.
  Therefore you see a portion of the file through the main editing window at
  any one time. It is possible to see any part of the file by moving or
  scrolling this window. The Microsoft Editor allows you to open multiple
  windows on the screen, using the %@AI@%Window%@AE@% function, for viewing different
  parts of the same file or different files.%@NL@%
